<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats: Bush Too Busy for Texas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush's major proposals for $2.6  
billion in tax cuts and teacher pay raises are in trouble because 
the Republican is too busy running for president to take care of 
his legislative business at home, according to Democratic 
lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's ``absent'' leadership this session was among complaints  
leveled by about 30 Democratic legislators at a news conference 
Tuesday in Austin. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if I'd say he's been missing in action, but it's  
been pretty close to that,'' Rep. Kevin Bailey, D-Houston, said. 
``He's a lot less involved than in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said he will stay in Austin and won't begin campaigning for  
the Republican presidential nomination until after the end of the 
legislative session. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor has had about half the personal involvement in this  
legislative session that he had during the 1997 Legislature, 
according to a Houston Chronicle review of Bush's office calendars. 
</P>
<P>
	If bills on major issues on which Bush campaigned fail, that  
will give opponents of his presidential campaign cause to attack 
him as an ineffective leader. 
</P>
<P>
	The issues that face tough challenges include tax cuts, a  
requirement for girls to notify their parents before they can get 
an abortion, and vouchers that would allow parents to use public 
money to send their children to private school. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor vowed Tuesday to get most of what he asked for from  
the Legislature, including a ``significant'' tax cut. He noted that 
measures to lower the maximum alcohol level for drunken driving and 
to restrict Y2K lawsuits were on their way to his desk or about to 
pass. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a part of the Bush agenda that seems to be moving along  
quite nicely,'' said Bush. ``Most of the issues I campaigned on 
came out of the Senate, and there will be a moment of 
reconciliation (with the House.)'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, an education finance bill that recently came out of the  
Senate only delivered half of Bush's promised $2 billion property 
tax cut, with the rest set for teacher pay. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats in the House Education Committee do not believe there  
is enough money to pay for tax cuts and teacher pay increases. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Sadler, a Democrat and the panel's chairman, is awaiting a  
new state revenue estimate from Comptroller Carole Rylander. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Bush has been responsive. ``I've never been put off,''  
Sadler said. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor insists there's still plenty of time to get what he  
wants from this Legislature. He said he has no concern about 
whether the results of this session affect his presidential bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's important for the work product of this session is that  
it is important for Texas,'' said Bush. ``We'll worry about the 
exploratory business later on. Right now, it's what's best for 
Texas.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
