<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Edge Higher / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices edged higher Wednesday, overcoming  
an early tumble sparked by the resignation of the well-regarded 
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1/8 point,  
or $1.25 per $1,000 in face value. 
</P>
<P>
	Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, spiked as high  
as 5.88 percent in the morning, but finished the day at 5.82 
percent, a shade below Tuesday's 5.83 percent. The yield is a key 
influence on the interest rates charged for many types of loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Reports of Rubin's long-rumored resignation, confirmed by the  
White House in the morning, initially tugged stocks and bonds lower 
as investors worried that the change would upset the delicate 
balance behind the economy's surprising resilience. 
</P>
<P>
	But the markets quickly recovered amid confidence that Lawrence  
Summers, Rubin's deputy and proposed successor, would pursue the 
same course. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were also relieved by the finish of this week's auctions  
of new debt securities by the Treasury, which sold $12 billion in 
10-year notes on Wednesday after selling $15 billion in 5-year 
notes on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were unchanged, while intermediate maturities rose 3/32 point, 
reported Bridge Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 4.58 percent as the  
discount fell 0.02 percentage point to 4.46 percent from late 
Tuesday. Six-month yields fell to 4.68 percent, as the discount 
fell 0.01 percentage point to 4.51 percent. One-year yields edged 
down to 4.75 percent as the discount fell 0.01 percentage point to 
4.53 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, remained unchanged at 4.69 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 3/32 to 122 17/32. The average yield to 
maturity eased to 5.34 percent from late Tuesday's 5.35 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
