<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Decried on SBC-Ameritech Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate's top telecommunications lawmaker  
accused the Federal Communications Commission of unfairly handling 
its review of SBC Communications' planned merger with Ameritech 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., chairman of the Senate Commerce  
Committee, which has jurisdiction over the agency, in a letter 
Wednesday to FCC Chairman Bill Kennard said: ``You must do whatever 
is necessary to remove the institutional unfairness and prejudgment 
that has been permitted to taint this proceeding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, McCain was upset by recent comments made by Thomas  
Krattenmaker, an FCC staff member overseeing the commission's 
review. 
</P>
<P>
	Krattenmaker, at a public hearing on the merger last week, said  
the planned SBC-Ameritech merger, as now structured, ``flunks the 
public interest test.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An FCC spokesman said Kennard, responding to McCain's letter,  
``expressed his full confidence in the expertise and integrity of 
the commission's professional staff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Krattenmaker also said that the commission's staff tentatively  
had concluded the merger should be rejected unless changes are made 
to address concerns that it would blunt competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC and the companies are trying to negotiate possible  
conditions that would be placed on the merger to address those 
concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain also complained that Robert Atkinson, another FCC staff  
member involved in the merger review, previously had worked for 
AT&AMP;T, which opposes the SBC-Ameritech merger. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T spokesman Jim McGann said Atkinson worked briefly for AT&AMP;T  
after it acquired Teleport Communications Group, which sells local 
phone service and data communications primarily to businesses. 
Atkinson left AT&AMP;T a couple of months ago to work for the FCC, 
McGann said. 
</P>
<P>
	SBC and Ameritech say their merger, approved by the Justice  
Department, is good for competition. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
