<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft May Buy Brit Cable Biz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. is talking with Cable &AMP; Wireless  
PLC about the possible purchase of the British company's cable TV 
business, The Wall Street Journal reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The head of Cable &AMP; Wireless, Britain's No. 2 telecommunications  
firm, confirmed that talks were under way with Microsoft, but 
refused to say whether the two sides were discussing such a deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief executive Graham Wallace also refused to confirm that he  
had spoken Tuesday with Microsoft financial chief Greg Maffei. 
</P>
<P>
	The Journal said Wallace and Maffei had talked about a deal in  
which Microsoft would buy 30 percent of Cable &AMP; Wireless 
Communications PLC for more than $4 billion. The newspaper 
attributed its report to unidentified people familar with the 
situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do continually talk to Microsoft,'' Wallace said today.  
``That's just the way this business works.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft officials in London could not immediately be reached  
for comment on the report. 
</P>
<P>
	If true, discussions about a possible cable-TV acquisition would  
mark a broadening of Microsoft's efforts to penetrate Britain's 
cable business. The U.S. software giant announced plans in January 
to invest $500 million in NTL Inc., Britain's third-largest cable 
operator. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of its more recent $5 billion investment in AT&AMP;T,  
Microsoft agreed to swap stock for a 30 percent share in another 
British cable firm, Telewest Communications PLC. That share has 
been held by MediaOne Group Inc., which had agreed earlier to be 
acquired by AT&AMP;T. 
</P>
<P>
	At stake is access to Britain's extensive cable network, which  
Microsoft and others hope to use to provide telephone, Internet and 
other services. Much of the British cable system uses fiber-optics, 
which allows for high-speed data transmission. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable &AMP; Wireless owns 53 percent of its cable-TV unit. It was  
already said to be discussing a possible merger of the unit's 
residential operations with those of Telewest. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's effort to take a minority stake in Cable &AMP; Wireless  
Communications is part of those merger talks, the Journal said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace said he was optimistic that Britain's three main cable  
companies would eventually merge into one or two national cable 
operators. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
