<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 12:35:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. County Pushes After-School Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Board of Supervisors got a standing ovation from a group of  
single mothers Tuesday after approving $74 million for free child 
care at 225 elementary schools with large numbers of children from 
families on welfare. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of the best gifts that mothers throughout the city  
and the county can get for Mother's Day,'' said Margaret Prescod of 
the Every Mother is a Working Mother Network, which pushed for the 
program. ``It's more substantial than the flowers we get.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 16,000 children could be enrolled in the program,  
which is funded by federal and state welfare grants. It will get 
under way this summer and expand through next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It should really make life easier for so many people,'' said  
Lynn Bayer, director of the county's welfare department. ``The 
reality is that many of these children don't receive child care and 
go home to empty houses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, supervisors said, they hope to increase the funding  
to $120 million and expand it to include older children. 
</P>
<P>
	The program will concentrate on education rather than the  
after-school recreation some districts now offer. 
</P>
<P>
	While districts will work out the details, some concepts include  
helping children with their homework and test preparation, and 
giving them access to computers. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a real paradigm shift in terms of after-school  
programs,'' said Phil Kauble of the county Office of Education. 
</P>
<P>
	Affordable child care has been a concern since welfare reforms  
began forcing many recipients to work. The Los Angeles area lags 
behind other urban areas in available child care for poor working 
mothers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
