<DOCNO> APW19990512.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 06:05:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Chung Testifies Before House Panel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After Clinton donor Johnny Chung underwent  
four hours of questioning on Capitol Hill, he shook hands with Rep. 
Dan Burton and declared, ``Well Mr. Chairman, one down, 120 to 
go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to congressional staffers, Chung was referring Tuesday  
to the number of witnesses Burton says have refused to appear in 
the two-year House campaign fund-raising investigation, thwarting 
the efforts of Republicans to get first-hand testimony about the 
financing of the presidential campaign in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eighty people have taken the Fifth; a lot of people have left  
the country or stayed overseas,'' said Burton, R-Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the 120, former Little Rock restaurateur Charlie Trie,  
goes on trial in Arkansas next Monday, charged with obstructing a 
Senate probe into campaign fund-raising abuses by allegedly 
ordering a subordinate to get rid of subpoenaed documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing before Burton's Government Reform Committee, Chung  
said he was told by a Chinese banker that Trie had asked for $1 
million from the Chinese government for political donations. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung also testified that he was approached last year by a  
California businessman named Robert Luu who first threatened, then 
offered money if Chung would be uncooperative with the Justice 
Department investigation of campaign finance abuses. According to 
Chung, Luu said he was acting on behalf of a woman who had been the 
intermediary between Chung and the chief of Chinese military 
intelligence. The intelligence chief, Gen. Ji Sheng De, provided 
Chung $300,000, saying it should be used to re-elect President 
Clinton, Chung testified. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung testified that the FBI taped and photographed some of the  
conversations with Luu. 
</P>
<P>
	``Luu ... mentioned that he received money from Beijing'' and  
``Luu said they would give me money to take care of my legal 
expenses and my family and I could retire,'' said Chung. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung said Luu then introduced him to an attorney in San  
Gabriel, Calif., identified during the hearing as David Brockway. 
</P>
<P>
	``The lawyer gave me an example of someone who did not cooperate  
and how everyone around him was taken care of,'' Chung said. ``He 
said that this client was sentenced to a country club jail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brockway, a Los Angeles defense attorney, said he met with Chung  
once last year at Luu's urging, but added that he's not connected 
with anyone in the Justice Department and never promised Chung 
anything. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chung is making this up,'' Brockway said in a telephone  
interview late Tuesday. ``He had already pleaded guilty so I said, 
'You don't need me.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Brockway said Luu works for him as an interpreter and described  
him as a Vietnamese refugee who has no connections with any Chinese 
officials. Luu could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Luu eventually grew suspicious in his conversations with Chung  
and Luu ``started making self-serving statements on the tapes and 
tried to distance himself from previous statements,'' said Chung. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung said that initially, Luu threatened that he should not  
cooperate with the FBI. ``The message was as follows: `If you keep 
your mouth shut, you and your family will be safe,''' Chung told 
lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung testified he felt uncomfortable channeling $300,000 from  
the Chinese chief of military intelligence into political 
contributions, so he spent most of it on business instead. A Senate 
Intelligence Committee report says the FBI traced $20,000 as 
political donations to the Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung detailed how a 2 1/2-year political giving spree won him  
access to the White House for his well-heeled Chinese clients. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have mixed feelings about the president and the first lady,  
but I can't help but think that they used me as much as I used 
them,'' Chung said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung also alleged that a U.S. Embassy official in Beijing, who  
has since left the State Department, helped him get visas for 
dozens who wanted to visit the United States. Chung alleged he did 
financial favors for the official, Charles Parish, and took him to 
a Democratic fund-raiser and a private tour of the first lady's 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department is investigating Parish, spokesman Maria  
Rudensky said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
