<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First of Small Boats Finishes Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- After chasing French skipper J.P.  
Mouligne three-quarters of the way around the world, British 
yachtsman Mike Garside finally beat his rival to a port in the 
Around Alone single-handed sailing race. 
</P>
<P>
	Garside won the fourth leg from Uruguay to Charleston on Tuesday  
but Mouligne, nearing the finish line, would still be the winner in 
the 50-foot yacht division. 
</P>
<P>
	Giovanni Soldini, who finished Saturday in a larger, 60-foot  
yacht, was the overall winner in record time. 
</P>
<P>
	Mouligne, whose Cray Valley slowed as it approached Charleston,  
telephoned his shore crew it was strange to be finishing a race 
that has consumed him for several years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're here safe, alive,'' Garside said after being greeted by  
several hundred people Tuesday Charleston's City Marina. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine publisher said he entered the race not for  
adventure, but to win. He did not, but did take a leg from 
Mouligne. 
</P>
<P>
	``The second time I made landfall in Charleston, I had been  
beaten in the Atlantic Alone by J.P. Mouligne, and I was mad that I 
didn't win,'' Garside said ``I didn't realize how presumptuous of 
me that was until I raced him halfway around the world. He is the 
best single-handed sailor in the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garside, 54, sailed one of the most modern boats in the fleet  
but was not a typical sailor. 
</P>
<P>
	A former Special Forces officer, he had survived combat and a  
gunshot wound. While recovering, he read about long-distance 
sailing and decided to sail around the world with his family. 
</P>
<P>
	He took a one-week how-to course, then sailed around the world  
between 1980 and '82 -- the last time Garside had sailed before the 
Around Alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Although their relationship was a bit rocky at first, Garside  
and Mouligne came to respect each other. And Mouligne was the first 
to congratulate him via e-mail as Garside neared the finish on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Garside said he finally learned how to sail his boat, which he  
joked did not come with an instruction manual. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I learned about sailing I got from the Cray Valley Web  
site,'' he said. ``I'd read what J.P. said I'd done wrong and take 
notes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He plans to return to publishing and to continue sailing.  
</P>
<P>
	``I always knew I could win a leg,'' he said. ``I had the boat  
to do it. It's just that I wasn't up to the bloody job. But I've 
finally mastered the boat and I pushed it really, really hard.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 17:22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- In its most important labor-law ruling in  
years, Mexico's supreme court has decided in favor of ``open shop'' 
rules at companies, allowing employees to belong to any union, or 
none at all. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tuesday ruling on four constitutional appeals, filed by two  
unions and two individual workers, sets precedent for state and 
federal courts. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling could affect the power long enjoyed by a handful of  
huge, pro-government unions that automatically register employees 
as members when they are hired and deduct union dues from their 
paychecks. 
</P>
<P>
	The court upheld a requirement that a union have a minimum of 20  
members, or meet other requirements to prove it represents at least 
some workers in a given industry. The ruling also upholds the 
rights of employees to quit -- or refuse to join -- a union. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling will take effect as soon as it is published in the  
official gazette. 
</P>
<P>
	Mandatory union membership has long discouraged the growth of  
independent unions here. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Workers have fixed an undersea  
sewage pipe that leaked tons of fetid waste onto Rio's prime 
beaches, but state and city officials can't agree whether the water 
now is safe. 
</P>
<P>
	The city's environmental secretariat took down ``no swimming''  
signs at Ipanema beach on Wednesday and put up new ones saying: 
``safe for swimming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But a few feet away, a warning from Rio de Janeiro state's  
environmental agency Feema advised beachgoers to stay out of the 
water. 
</P>
<P>
	The city government says its measurement of fecal coliform  
bacteria in the water, a common gauge of raw sewage contamination, 
shows the water is safe except around Leme and Copacabana beaches 
and parts of Ipanema. 
</P>
<P>
	But state Environment Secretary Andre Correa says the city  
government has been ``too hasty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- A gas canister used for cooking  
exploded Wednesday in a low-income Sao Paulo district, killing a 
family of four, the city's fire department said. 
</P>
<P>
	The department's press office said a couple and their two  
children were killed in the blast caused by a leak in the canister. 
It did not know what caused the leaking gas to explode. 
</P>
<P>
	The small concrete home was completely destroyed by the  
explosion. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A sister-in-law of former President Carlos  
Salinas de Gortari has dropped an appeal and paid a fine for her 
conviction on witness-tampering charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Paulina Castanon, wife of Salinas' brother Raul and a prominent  
socialite, dropped the appeal because she has hepatitis and needs 
to leave the country for medical treatment, she was quoted by local 
media as saying. She maintained she was innocent. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge in the case had said he feared Castanon would not  
return if she were allowed to leave the country. Castanon said she 
had hepatitis C and was seeking a new treatment available only in 
Miami or Barcelona, Spain. A liver transplant would be the only 
treatment available in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Castanon was sentenced to three years in prison in 1997 for  
trying to get a witness to change his testimony in a murder case 
against her husband and lying to a judge about those attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, she paid a fine of $2,025, which exempts her from  
the prison sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Raul Salinas was sentenced in January to 50 years in prison for  
masterminding the 1994 murder of a political rival. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- The Guatemalan army denied on Wednesday  
accusations by a U.N. agency that it helped former paramilitaries 
escape from a jail after they were convicted in the 1993 murder of 
a farmworker. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12 ex-paramilitaries had been sentenced to 25 years for the  
killing, but in April an angry mob of their neighbors stormed the 
jail where they were being held, freed them and apparently helped 
them hide. 
</P>
<P>
	An army press statement said that at ``no point'' was there any  
act by the military to help the convicts flee. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, the U.N. Mission to Guatemala said there is  
evidence the army helped the mob free the prisoners, and that this 
could represent a violation of peace accords signed in 1996 between 
the government and leftist rebels which ended Guatemala's 36-year 
civil war. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the accords, the country's paramilitary Civilian  
Self-Defense Patrols were supposed to cut all military ties and 
disband. The paramilitary groups were formed in 1981 to assist the 
army in carrying out a brutal counterinsurgency campaign during the 
civil war. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. report said soldiers dressed as civilians were seen in  
the mob and an army commander refused to dispatch troops to stop 
the mob. 
</P>
</TEXT>
