<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Air Exec Pledges $200M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Philippine Airlines chairman Lucio  
Tan has assured government officials he can raise $200 million in 
new capital for the rehabilitation of the troubled flag carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu told reporters Wednesday that  
it ``looks like there is finally a solution'' but added ``Until the 
money is in, we can't say it's done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under a recovery plan, the $200 million must be injected into  
the company by June 4. Tan, who owns 70 percent of the airline, has 
personally pledged $100 million and is trying to find an investor 
group to put up the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan, as the majority stockholder, has the right to infuse fresh  
capital into the airline over at least two other potential investor 
groups, Espiritu said. 
</P>
<P>
	Espiritu said Deutsche Lufthansa AG -- Europe's second-biggest  
carrier -- will manage the airline, which is mired in debts totaling 
$2.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it appears Lufthansa will take over management from a  
group of former Cathay Pacific executives. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan has been in Frankfurt where he has been negotiating with  
Lufthansa officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite objections from the U.S. Export-Import Bank, which holds  
16 percent of PAL's debt, the rehabilitation plan is expected to be 
approved later this month by the Philippine Securities and Exchange 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	European credit agencies owed around 40 percent of the total,  
however, wrote to the SEC earlier this week warning that their 
support for PAL should not be taken for granted, an official said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the agencies expressed concern in the letter about a  
recent management shakeup in which Tan reappointed himself chief 
executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan's move also angered the U.S. Ex-Im Bank, which withdrew its  
support for the rehabilitation plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan stepped down as chief executive only a few months ago under  
pressure from creditors, who wanted professional managers to run 
the airline. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately from Tan, the government is also trying to encourage  
new investors to take an equity stake in PAL, and has said that 
Kuwaiti aviation interests are among several interested groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Espiritu said the government doesn't want state financing  
institutions which have stakes in PAL to plow fresh funds into the 
carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	While President Joseph Estrada has said there will be no  
government bailout, some officials have said the financing 
institutions might be given some leeway on this as an investment 
decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
