<HEADLINE> Mistrial in Case of Houston Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- For the second time in a year, a mistrial was  
declared in the federal conspiracy and bribery case against two 
current and one former city councilmen who allegedly accepted 
envelopes stuffed with cash. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge David Hittner declared a mistrial Wednesday  
after jurors failed to agree on a verdict for Councilmen John 
Castillo and Michael Yarbrough and former Councilman John Peavy Jr. 
Jurors deliberated for six days. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors hinted at a third trial.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is far from over as far as we're concerned. It won't be  
over until justice is done,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael 
Attanasio said. 
</P>
<P>
	The three men are accused of taking thousands of dollars to vote  
to allow a group of minority businessmen to invest in a city hotel 
project. The investors were undercover FBI operatives. 
</P>
<P>
	The three, along with former City Councilman Ben Reyes and  
former Port Commissioner Betti Maldonado, were first tried last 
year but that jury also could not reach a verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	Reyes and Ms. Maldonado were convicted at their December  
retrial. Reyes was sentenced to nine years in prison, while Ms. 
Maldonado received four years and three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
