<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 15:54:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Venturi Is Presidents Cup Captain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IRVING, Texas (AP) -- If the American team lacks enthusiasm about  
the next Presidents Cup, it won't come from the top. Ken Venturi 
was glowing Wednesday when he was introduced as U.S. captain for 
the 2000 matches. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be captain is something that was only made in dreams,''  
Venturi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Venturi, the 1964 U.S. Open champion and a golf analyst for CBS  
Sports for 31 years, will take charge of a team that looked 
lifeless in a 20 1/2-11 1/2 loss to the International team last year at 
Royal Melbourne in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is very enthusiastic about it,'' PGA Tour commissioner Tim  
Finchem said. ``I have to believe that will rub off on the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 2000 matches will be played at the Robert Trent Jones Golf  
Club in Gainesville, Va., where the United States won the first two 
editions of the Presidents Cup. It's not far from where Venturi won 
his only major championship, at Congressional. 
</P>
<P>
	The International team is expected to announce its captain as  
soon as next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Finchem said he asked Venturi to be captain about two months  
ago, then told him to keep it a secret. That was no small task. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just wanted to hug him and kiss him,'' Venturi said. ``I  
can't tell you how much I'm looking forward to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Venturi follows Hale Irwin, Arnold Palmer and Jack Nicklaus as  
captain of the Presidents Cup, which began in 1994 and was 
patterned after the Ryder Cup to give foreign players born outside 
Europe a chance to take part in team match play. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike those captains, Venturi has been removed from the game as  
a player for 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will not be a playing captain,'' Venturi joked, adding that  
he might add Gene Sarazen and Byron Nelson as his wild-card 
selections. 
</P>
<P>
	Then again, he knows the tour and its players as well as anyone  
because of his work for CBS Sports since 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	``He will be an incredible captain from the standpoint of having  
relationships and knowledge about the players,'' Finchem said. 
``You see Ken Venturi at a tour event, always out on the practice 
tee talking to the players, learning about what players are 
thinking about and taking a look at how they're playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Venturi already is getting strong endorsement from the players.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's pretty neat that Ken is our captain,'' Tiger  
Woods said. ``He knows us better than Arnold or Jack, because he 
sees us out here, he talks to us and he watches us play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Venturi's career already is one of the most successful in golf,  
even if he has just 14 victories. 
</P>
<P>
	He stammered so badly as a child that doctors told his mother he  
may never speak properly. Venturi overcame that to become perhaps 
the most popular golf analyst in television. He was honored by the 
PGA of American in April with the Lifetime Achievement Award in 
Journalism. 
</P>
<P>
	His career on the golf course lasted only 14 years because of  
Carpal-Tunnel Syndrome, but it was packed with achievements. 
</P>
<P>
	He nearly became the first amateur to win the Masters in 1956  
until an 80 in the final round left him one stroke behind Jack 
Burke Jr. Then at Congressional in 1964, he nearly collapsed from 
heat exhaustion in the 36-hole final but hung on to beat Tommy 
Jacobs by four strokes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Captaining the team is an honor that I can never, ever thank  
you enough for,'' Venturi told Finchem. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he winked at him.  
</P>
<P>
	``We'll bring it back home.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
