<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 15:57:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Leader Backs G-8 Peace Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova  
expressed backing Wednesday for a peace plan drawn up by western 
powers and Russia to resolve the crisis over Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Rugova met with German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer, one of  
a number of sessions he has held with German and Italian leaders 
since Yugoslavia unexpectedly allowed him to leave the country May 
5. 
</P>
<P>
	In a brief statement, Rugova repeated his call for Yugoslavia to  
withdraw its forces from Kosovo and accept an international force, 
including NATO troops, to supervise the return of refugees to 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the main goal was the return of the hundreds of  
thousands of refugees who have fled the Serb province for 
neighboring lands. ``I'm very saddened that Kosovo is practically 
empty,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rugova, who met with Pope John Paul II on Monday, said he  
supported the peace plan worked out last week in Bonn by the seven 
leading industrial nations and Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan does not define the sort of international force to be  
deployed in Kosovo -- in deference to Russia's reluctance at seeing 
a NATO-led force. It also calls for Kosovo to remain part of 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	During their talks, Fischer urged Rugova to use his influence to  
bring the different factions of Kosovo Albanians to ``agree on 
political goals,'' the foreign minister's spokesman, Martin 
Erdmann, said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Kosovo Albanians have to speak with one voice so the  
international community will hear them,'' Fischer was quoted as 
telling Rugova. 
</P>
<P>
	Erdmann said Rugova and his family are taking temporary  
residence near Bonn for the time being. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army accused Rugova of  
being an ``emissary'' for Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and 
denounced him for not speaking out about the suffering of the 
Kosovo Albanians since he left Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after NATO bombing began March 24, Rugova met Milosevic.  
Serb TV showed the two men shaking and hands and also attributed 
statements to Rugova including an apparent call for the end to the 
NATO airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	Western officials say he and his family had been under house  
arrest in Kosovo since the airstrikes began, and the KLA at the 
time dismissed the meeting as coerced. Since leaving Yugoslavia, 
Rugova has avoided commenting on either his reported detention or 
his meeting with Milosevic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
