<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Seeks Milosevic's Indictment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bipartisan congressional human rights  
commission says the Clinton administration is failing to gather 
usable war crimes evidence against Yugoslav leader Slobodan 
Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``In spite of all that has happened in Bosnia and now Kosovo,  
the United States administration still seems to cling to the idea 
that Milosevic is someone with whom we can cut a deal,'' Rep. Chris 
Smith, R-N.J., co-chairman of the congressional Helsinki 
Commission, said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before NATO attacks on Kosovo, the House and Senate passed  
resolutions last year calling upon the Clinton administration to 
gather evidence for an indictment of Milosevic based on atrocities 
in Bosnia and elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said he plans to introduce another resolution to push for  
more aggressive legal action against the Yugoslav leader, Serb 
commanders and others for atrocities in Kosovo. He said 
administration officials have repeatedly told him they have no 
specific collection of evidence against Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	Nina Bang-Jensen, special counsel for the independent Coalition  
for International Justice, which assists the U.N. Yugoslav war 
crimes tribunal in the Hague, Netherlands, told the commission at a 
hearing Tuesday that the tribunal's record so far on the Kosovo 
crisis has been disappointing. 
</P>
<P>
	She urged that immunity not be considered for Milosevic as part  
of any peace deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton administration officials have pledged full cooperation  
with the war crimes tribunal and say they are supporting efforts to 
gather evidence among Kosovo refugees against Serb military forces 
and police. 
</P>
<P>
	Alarmed by new talk of achieving peace in Kosovo by negotiating  
with Milosevic, Rep. Ben Cardin, D-Md., called for a 
``superindictment'' of the Serb leader under war crimes tribunal 
provisions that allow public announcement of an indictment. 
Currently, the Hague-based tribunal dealing with former Yugoslav 
states keeps its indictments secret until the accused is arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardin said there is bipartisan concern on Capitol Hill ``as to  
whether the Clinton administration is placing a high enough 
priority on assisting and making sure that the war crimes tribunal 
can carry out its mission.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cardin said the concern is increased by recent statements about  
a negotiated peace agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 10:35:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress: How Much Cash for Kosovo? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House and Senate negotiators are driving  
toward giving President Clinton at least $4.9 billion more than he 
wanted for the air campaign against Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	But first, lawmakers trying to wrap up a compromise wide-ranging  
spending bill will have to resolve disputes over mining 
regulations, Alaskan fishing and other issues. Bargainers from the 
two chambers planned to meet again today in hopes of shaking hands 
on a measure they want to zip through Congress this week. 
</P>
<P>
	While they were working on it, participants urged the White  
House to rethink its threat to veto the measure because of its 
excessive defense spending, cuts in domestic programs, and other 
provisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The administration should wait to see what the product is,''  
said the House Appropriations Committee chairman, Rep. Bill Young, 
R-Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has asked for $6 billion for the bombing campaign  
against Yugoslavia. The House beefed that up to $13 billion last 
week, adding money for equipment, training, a pay raise for the 
troops and other items. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate never voted on a plan of its own. But during  
negotiations Tuesday, the Senate Appropriations Committee chairman, 
Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, offered $10.9 billion, knocking out $1 
billion the House approved to modernize overseas U.S. military 
bases. 
</P>
<P>
	In effect, that became the minimum figure Congress is likely to  
provide for the conflict and for a GOP-led effort to beef up U.S. 
armed forces at home and abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	House and Senate bargainers tentatively agreed to include $678  
million for refugees who have fled the province of Kosovo, $112 
million more than Clinton proposed. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill contains nearly $1 billion to help Central America  
rebuild from recent natural disasters, particularly last fall's 
Hurricane Mitch, which devastated Honduras, El Salvador, Nicaragua 
and Costa Rica. Also sure to be included is aid to American farmers 
struggling because of plummeting prices for cotton, hogs and other 
commodities, and money to help the recovery from the recent 
Midwestern tornadoes and to buttress the Federal Emergency 
Management Agency's coffers for future disasters. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to the bargainers, House Speaker Dennis Hastert,  
R-Ill., and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., told them 
to provide $11 billion for defense plus aid for natural disasters 
and farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	The leaders also said negotiators should drop provisions ``which  
add significantly to the cost'' of the compromise bill, such as new 
loan programs. They said other items should be retained, such as an 
administration-opposed provision that would bar the federal 
government from sharing the $246 billion settlement states have 
reached with the tobacco industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, battles were being waged over provisions added by  
senators that include help for the steel, oil, gas, mining and 
ranching industries. 
</P>
<P>
	In a new one, Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., said he would abandon  
an attempt to block the Interior Department from designating a 
protected habitat for the endangered silvery minnow, which lives in 
his state. After initially saying he would offer even broader 
language preventing the designation of new protected habitats for 
any species, he ran into objections from the White House and other 
senators and said he would pursue the prohibition in separate 
legislation later. 
</P>
<P>
	Pleas by House members to drop the items seemed to fall on ears  
that were all but deaf. 
</P>
<P>
	To one such request, Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., responded,  
``That great philosopher, Mae West, said, `Too much of anything is 
simply wonderful.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd is author of language that would provide $140 million to  
some steel companies hurt by low-cost foreign competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Especially numerous were fights over environmental provisions.  
Environmental groups said senators were using the must-pass bill to 
carry language that otherwise would not pass. And led by Rep. 
Sherwood Boehlert, R-N.Y., House GOP moderates circulated a letter 
saying the provisions ``would be a serious procedural, political 
and policy mistake that could jeopardize passage of any conference 
report on the House floor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fights included:  
</P>
<P>
	--An effort by Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., to block the Fish and  
Wildlife Service from listing the Alabama sturgeon as an endangered 
species. He says such a listing would restrict dredging in the 
state's waterways, threatening the timber industry and other 
industries that ship their products on barges. 
</P>
<P>
	--Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., was trying to overturn a court  
ruling that mining companies can't expand their milling operations 
on public lands. Environmentalists complain those operations 
pollute water. The ruling affects the Crown Jewel gold mine in 
Gorton's state and other Western hard-rock mines. 
</P>
<P>
	--Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, wants to prevent the National  
Park Service from phasing out commercial fishing in the waters off 
Glacier Bay National Park until courts decide the issue. 
Environmentalists say that could take years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
