<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chargers Sign Defensive End Fontenot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- The San Diego Chargers signed six-year veteran  
defensive end Al Fontenot to a one-year contract today, filling one 
of their offseason needs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chargers turned to Fontenot after they had trouble  
re-signing end Marco Coleman, an unrestricted free agent. Signing 
Fontenot apparently won't close the door for Coleman, but likely 
would force him to take less money if he does decide to return to 
San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	Fontenot spent the last two seasons with Indianapolis and his  
first four with Chicago. He has 17 1/2 sacks and 264 tackles in his 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	He had 4 1/2 sacks in 1996, his final year with the Bears, and  
again in 1997, his first with the Colts. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, quarterback Mark Rypien visited the Chargers  
and, to no one's surprise, failed his physical exam. He underwent 
arthroscopic surgery on his right rotator cuff on Feb. 19. 
Nonetheless, he met with general manager Bobby Beathard, coach Mike 
Riley and offensive line coach Joe Bugel, who coached with the 
Washington Redskins when Rypien played for them. 
</P>
<P>
	``The doctor felt, and rightly so, that I could use a little  
more range of motion,'' said Rypien, who expects to be fully healed 
in three to four weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Rypien sat out last season due to his young son's terminal  
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Like I told Bobby, my heart and mind are back in football,''  
Rypien said. ``I want to play again. Physically, I want to know if 
I can do it. I'm not there yet, but it's nice to know they have 
interest. They have Ryan (Leaf), Jim (Harbaugh) and Craig 
(Whelihan) still here. If I do come, it would be a chance to battle 
for a spot on the team.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
