<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Storm Victims Re-Establish Identity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOORE, Okla. (AP) -- Authorities issuing new driver's licenses to  
replace those lost in last week's tornadoes are taking a thumbprint 
from victims to make sure the new IDs are given to their rightful 
owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials are also quizzing people about their personal history  
and asking for other information to ensure impostors don't wind up 
with replacement birth certificates, homeowner's certificates or 
other crucial documents. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's information in that tornado that's been blown all over  
creation,'' state Department of Public Safety examiner Sabra Denton 
said Tuesday, staffing a driver's license office at the First 
Baptist Church in Moore, Okla. ``We're a compassionate outreach 
here, but we're still protecting the public.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For many victims, the twisters that killed 41 people in Oklahoma  
carried away nearly all of their vital papers. 
</P>
<P>
	In Midwest City, residents who ask for duplicate documents but  
have no ID are given a pop quiz to prove they were homeowners. 
Police records specialist Hazel Hamer takes out a map and asks them 
to point to where their houses once stood. 
</P>
<P>
	``We realize some people have lost everything,'' Hamer said.  
``We just go by the map and we check the utility records to make 
sure the name and address on the bills match the addresses people 
are giving us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Williamson of the state Department of Public Safety has  
processed applications for more than 100 driver's licenses over 
several days at the Moore church. 
</P>
<P>
	People have been offering everything from fishing licenses to  
American Association of Retired Persons membership cards to prove 
their identity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I took a guy awhile ago who had his entire criminal booking  
record with his name and address on it,'' Williamson said. ``He got 
his license.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To guard against fraud, Williamson calls up driving histories  
and quizzes applicants about speeding tickets, maiden names or how 
long they have been driving. 
</P>
<P>
	Everyone is asked to give a thumbprint, which scares away  
criminals and gives state investigators some key evidence if the 
license is used to commit fraud, Williamson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have had some people come into the exam stations who change  
their stories or don't know all the answers,'' he said. ``They 
leave pretty quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Melissa Hess, 24, hid in a cellar while the twisters destroyed  
her two-story Moore home. When she emerged, everything was gone, 
including the file box where she kept all her bank records and her 
two son's birth certificates. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have my identification, I don't have my checkbook, I  
don't have my credit card,'' Mrs. Hess said. ``The only thing left 
at my house is the grill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kent and Kellie Taylor were among the lucky ones. Taylor had his  
driver's license in his pocket when he took cover in a closet with 
his children, ages 18 months and 9 years, as the tornado ripped 
away the roof of their three-bedroom home. 
</P>
<P>
	He should be able to quickly replace his marriage license and  
his children's birth certificates. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I'm still married to him and I'm not going to let him  
forget that,'' Mrs. Taylor joked Tuesday, as the couple drove 
through the rubble that once was their neighborhood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 10:45:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that are moving substantially or trading  
heavily today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
	Federated Department Stores, up 2 1/8 at 53 1/8.  
</P>
<P>
	The company reported first-quarter earnings of 40 cents per  
share, up from 27 cents a year earlier and beating analysts' 
expectations of 31 cents. 

</P>
<P>
	Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, down 3 3/8 at 90 1/8.  
</P>
<P>
	The clothing retailer earned 23 cents a share in the first  
quarter, up 92 percent from 12 cents a share in the year-ago period 
and up from analysts' estimates of 17 cents. The company also said 
it should meet second-quarter earnings estimates of 28 cents per 
share but said sales growth at stores open at least a year will 
slow to between 5 percent and 6 percent this year from 22 percent 
rise in the first quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	Lyondell Chemical Co., down 3/16 at 19 7/16.  
</P>
<P>
	The company said it will sell 35 million common shares at $19 a  
share and offer $1.9 billion of senior secured notes and $500 
million of senior subordinated notes to institutional buyers. In 
addition, Lyondell will borrow $1 billion under its credit 
facility. The total $4 billion net proceeds will be used to retire 
``substantially all'' of the company's debt maturing through the 
year 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	The Alpine Group, Inc., up 3 3/16 at 17 9/16.  
</P>
<P>
	The company agreed in principle to sell its 83.4 percent owned  
unit, Premier Refractories International Inc., to Cookson Group 
PLC, a London-based technology company, for approximately $115 
million in stock and the assumption of approximately $295 million 
in debt. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
	Cisco Systems, up 5 5/16 at 117 3/16.  
</P>
<P>
	The computer network equipment maker posted net income of 38  
cents a share, up from 4 cents in the year-earlier period, 
including charges. The results narrowly exceeded Wall Street 
analysts' expectation of 37 cents. 

</P>
<P>
	Lycos, up 10 5/8 at 108 7/8.  
</P>
<P>
	USA Networks, up 2 3/4 at 38 5/8.  
</P>
<P>
	Ticketmaster Online-CitySearch, up 3 13/16 at 36 7/16  
</P>
<P>
	The companies formally called off their complicated merger  
agreement. In a mutual agreement announced today, USA Networks and 
Ticketmaster also agreed to not acquire Lycos stock or make any 
proposal to acquire Lycos stock until July 15. If Lycos becomes the 
subject of an acquisition proposal prior to July 15, Lycos may be 
required to pay USA Networks and Ticketmaster an aggregate of $35 
million under certain circumstances. The original merger agreement 
called for Lycos to be merged with certain USA Networks' assets and 
with Ticketmaster-Online. 

</P>
<P>
	TCA Cable TV, up 8 7/16 to 60 1/2  
</P>
<P>
	Cox Communications, down 2 5/16 to 85 11/16  
</P>
<P>
	Cox Communications said it will acquire the Tyler, Texas, cable  
television developer for $3.26 billion in cash and stock, plus the 
assumption of $736 million in debt. Cox, an Atlanta-based cable 
operator, will pay $63.89 for each TCA share, a 23% premium over 
its closing price Tuesday. 

</P>
<P>
	Broadcom Corp., up 6 1/16 at 98 3/4.  
</P>
<P>
	The communications technology maker unveiled its chip that can  
deliver video, voice and data over conventional copper wire 
networks 10 times faster than current technology. The Irvine, 
Calif.-based company said the new chip will allow companies to 
continue using existing copper wiring inside their offices while 
achieving more network speed and capacity. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 06:15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  MAC Names New Commissioner Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Rick Chryst, who handles marketing for the  
Atlantic Coast Conference, became the new commissioner of the 
Mid-American Conference on Tuesday, nine days after a Big East 
official backed out of the job. 
</P>
<P>
	An assistant commissioner with the ACC, Chryst said during a  
news conference he was unfazed by being the No. 2 pick of the MAC 
university presidents. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm coming in here as excited as if this was a week ago  
Friday,'' Chryst said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom McElroy, senior associate commissioner of the Big East, was  
named to the MAC post on April 30. 
</P>
<P>
	But a couple of days later, McElroy opted out, saying the move  
would create a hardship on his family. 
</P>
<P>
	Chryst said he was convinced McElroy didn't reverse course  
because of some hidden negative about the MAC. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the job is exactly as when I started on this road,''  
applying for the MAC job about two months ago, Chryst said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm anxious to do the job, excited to do the job and proud to  
do the job,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio University president and chair of the MAC Council of  
Presidents Robert Glidden said Chryst's contract is a five-year 
deal at a ``presidential level'' salary. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope this will be our last news conference -- at least for a  
month or so,'' Glidden said in a joking reference to the McElroy 
episode. 
</P>
<P>
	Chryst wouldn't go into details about his plans for the MAC,  
which is moving its headquarters from Toledo to Cleveland. But he 
said improving corporate sponsorship and creating workable 
schedules for the 13-school league that ensure opportunities for 
playing national games will be a couple of his priorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 06:15:29 </DATE_TIME>
