<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 14:25:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CEO Says Kodak Is Making Revival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Eastman Kodak Co. is climbing back to  
prosperity after ``falling into a deep chasm'' and being forced to 
chop 19,900 jobs last year, chief executive George Fisher told 
shareholders Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot have a year like 1997 again when we fell off the  
map,'' said Fisher, alluding to Kodak's laggard response to price 
wars with Japanese rival Fuji Photo Film Co. that tore into 
revenues and profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Kodak is cutting $1.2 billion in costs and slashing about  
one-fifth of its worldwide payroll of 100,500 through the end of 
this year, moves that Fisher acknowledged had created a 
heavy-hearted climate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have put people through the ringer on restructuring,'' he  
told reporters at Kodak's annual meeting. ``Last year at this time 
our morale ... was the worst since I've been here.'' He joined the 
firm in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's too bad that we had to let some people go. But once we've  
done that, people will begin to believe that not only the company's 
future is brighter but their future is brighter. That's the key to 
improving morale. We're working hard on it and I think we're making 
progress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not back to where we're driving on all cylinders,''  
interjected Kodak president Dan Karp. But aggressive cost-cutting 
and focusing on innovation is making Kodak more competitive and 
driving growth, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's biggest photography company has seen a sharp rebound  
in sales and profits. Revenues rose 6 percent to $3.1 billion in 
the first quarter of 1999 after falling in eight previous quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Kodak is projecting at least 10 percent annual growth in  
earnings-per-share and an 8-to-12 percent growth in sales annually 
through 2004. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0033 </DOCNO>
