<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Panel To Lower Trident Levels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Discouraged by a long Russian delay on an  
arms-reduction pact, the Senate Armed Services Committee was ready 
to support a plan for reducing the Navy's nuclear-missile sub fleet 
from 18 to 14, congressional officials said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Four of the Trident submarines now armed with nuclear missiles  
would be refitted for other purposes under the plan expected to win 
the panel's backing as it works behind closed doors on a defense 
spending bill for fiscal 2000, said officials who spoke on the 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, the committee and its chairman, Sen. John Warner,  
R-Va., had resisted efforts to scale back the number of 
nuclear-missile carrying subs without parallel reductions by 
Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal legislation requires the United States to maintain an  
18-boat Trident force, the level agreed to under the Strategic Arms 
Reduction Treaty with Russia, known as START I. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy's long-range plan is to go to a force of 14  
nuclear-weapons-fitted subs, most likely with seven on each coast. 
But that plan assumed that the Russian parliament would approve the 
successor to START I, known as START II. 
</P>
<P>
	START II was approved by the United States and agreed to by  
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, but has languished before the 
Russian parliament for six years. 
</P>
<P>
	The recent worsening in U.S.-Russian relations caused by NATO  
airstrikes against Yugoslavia has made it even less likely that the 
Russian parliament will vote any time soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Adm. Jay Johnson, chief of Naval Operations, told the committee  
earlier this year that the Pentagon would like to use four of the 
Trident subs for non-nuclear purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon's views that 14 subs with nuclear weapons would be  
adequate were restated in a recent report to Congress, the 
congressional sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten Tridents are at Kings Bay, Ga., and eight are at Bangor,  
Wash., near Seattle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
