<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patriots Stadium Bill Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The New England Patriots could have a new stadium  
in Foxboro by 2001 under legislation proposed by Massachusetts 
lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would provide $70 million for roads, sewers and other  
utilities needed for the stadium, Gov. Paul Cellucci said. 
</P>
<P>
	The stadium is expected to cost $225 million and seat about  
68,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers said the bill could be discussed at a hearing by  
Monday and then passed by both House and Senate on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems as if the end zone is in reasonable sight,'' House  
Speaker Thomas Finneran said. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawmakers said they had had no input from Patriots owner  
Robert Kraft on the bill but did work with the NFL on the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure they didn't have two of their top guys sitting down  
with us ... for the fun of it. There's a reason why those people 
were there,'' Cellucci said. 
</P>
<P>
	Finneran defended the lack of contact with Kraft.  
</P>
<P>
	``Very rarely do you write legislation in which you ask people  
that might be affected for a complete and total sign off. Here's 
the legislation. If you don't like it, it's a free country you can 
do whatever you want. It's his team,'' Finneran said. 
</P>
<P>
	Patriots spokesman Stacey James had no comment and referred  
questions to the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL called the bill an ``important step toward preserving  
the Patriots in Massachusetts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We will study the impact of the proposed legislation and look  
forward to working closely with state officials to resolve any 
remaining issues promptly and cooperatively,'' the league said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the collapse of their deal with Connecticut on April 30,  
the Patriots said they plan to ``stay in Massachusetts for a long 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state will receive $1.4 million per year to help offset the  
cost of the infrastructure improvements: $400,000 from off-site 
parking operators located within three miles of the stadium and $1 
million from the team. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was much more modest than the $380 million deal offered  
by Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Finneran: ``We all indicated with one voice to league  
officials, `You're not going to do any better. You're just not 
going to do any better in Massachusetts.''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
