<HEADLINE> Canucks Sign Top Prospect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- The Vancouver Canucks signed  
top prospect Bryan Allen, a defenseman, to a three-year contract 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial terms of the deal were not disclosed, but it was a  
contract -- with additional incentive clauses -- similar to the NHL 
rookie maximum $975,000-a-year offer that Allen rejected just prior 
to the preseason signing deadline last October. Allen was the 
Canucks' top pick and fourth player selected in last June's NHL 
entry draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bryan is rated as one of the best NHL prospects in the world.  
... '' Canucks president-general manager Brian Burke said. ``He's 
got a mean streak. He's mobile, he's hostile. ... He's going to be 
fine. He would've made the team coming out of training camp last 
year. We're very high on him. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite being hobbled by knee and shoulder injuries, Allen had a  
solid season as captain of the Ontario Hockey League's Oshawa 
Generals. In his third year as a junior, Allen recorded a 
career-high seven goals and 22 points in 37 games. He also played 
for Canada's national junior team which won the silver medal at 
last winter's World Junior Championships. 
</P>
