<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 17:14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nets: Newark Good for State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Faced with three proposals on where the New  
Jersey Nets and Devils will play, Gov. Christie Whitman on 
Wednesday cautioned that an arena with just one team is unlikely to 
have her support. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman's remarks came a day after the Nets said they will move  
from the state-run Meadowlands sports complex to a new arena they 
hope to build in downtown Newark. 
</P>
<P>
	Without offering specifics, the Nets told Whitman and the  
Meadowlands leadership in a letter delivered Tuesday that their 
Newark plan is a good deal for taxpayers because it ``better 
enables the state to capitalize on existing investment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team made no announcement and did not release the letter,  
which was obtained Wednesday by The Associated Press. It was signed 
by one of the owners as well as the franchise's president. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman reiterated Wednesday that her goal is to keep the  
state's five professional teams in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where they stay in New Jersey is secondary to keeping them  
here,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	All now play at Meadowlands venues: The NFL's Giants and Jets,  
and the New York-New Jersey MetroStars of Major League Soccer in 
Giants Stadium; and the NBA's Nets and the NHL's Devils at 
Continental Airlines Arena. The complex also includes the 
Meadowlands race track. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority, which operates  
the Meadowlands, wants to build a new arena for the Nets and 
Devils. The leases for the Nets and Devils expire in 2007. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nets would like both teams to play in Newark, but the Devils  
want to go it alone and build an arena in Hoboken. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman said the proposals are under review, but asserted ``that  
under nobody's scenario for a new arena have we seen finances that 
show it working unless two teams are there. We really need to have 
two teams in any arena that's built.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman said she would be meeting with Devils owner John  
McMullen shortly. She met Tuesday with Nets owners. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nets plan includes an arena as well as an office building,  
hotel and parking center on 40 acres in downtown Newark, and a 
stadium for the MetroStars. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman said if both the Nets and Devils leave, ``the  
Meadowlands can survive with or without the Continental Arena being 
a sport venue, a sports center.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sports authority and the teams agree the 18-year-old arena  
is outmoded, and cannot be refurbished to provide enough luxury 
boxes and other amenities that make money for teams. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nets' letter provides no indication on when the team would  
leave the complex in East Rutherford. 
</P>
<P>
	Nor does it say whether the Nets have obtained financing for  
their $300 million plan, of which one-third would come from state 
taxpayers for transit improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	Nets president Michael Rowe on Wednesday discussed the  
Nets-Whitman meeting, saying the ownership is willing to be 
partners with the sports authority and the Devils to bring an arena 
to Newark. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll move heaven and earth to attempt to get that done,''  
Rowe said. ``We do not care who owns the arena. It could be the 
city, it could be the county, it could be the Devils.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Nets are ``a bit'' short of the funds needed, having  
secured $200 million so far, noting that figure includes the team 
foregoing some revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Acknowledging that the three competing plans have left ``a  
triangular impasse,'' Rowe stressed the Nets would work for a 
solution. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray Bateman, chairman of the sports authority, said he doubted a  
single-sport arena is viable. 
</P>
<P>
	``If both franchises were to go to Newark, it could happen. If  
both don't go to Newark, it would not happen,'' Bateman said. ``I 
don't see the state operating or supporting two arenas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McMullen in December 1997 announced he will move his club to a  
hockey-only arena that includes theaters, restaurants and shops he 
plans to build in Hoboken for $270 million, of which just $30 
million would be from the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked Wednesday if he has arranged any financing, McMullen said,  
``I don't believe that's a problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In March, the sports authority announced plans for a privately  
financed $212 million arena for basketball and hockey at the 
Meadowlands. 
</P>
<P>
	The new arena would be next to Giants Stadium, while the  
existing home of the Nets and Devils would be demolished to make 
room for a privately financed, $165 million sports-themed complex. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
