<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Monet Painting Auctioned for $12M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A day after a Cezanne still life drew $60.5  
million at auction, prices came down to earth at Sotheby's sale of 
Impressionist and modern art. 
</P>
<P>
	The total for Tuesday's session, which featured two Monets and a  
Degas pastel that didn't find a buyer, was -- at $55.6 million -- 
well under the price for the single Cezanne. 
</P>
<P>
	Monet's ``Haystack,'' an 1891 work that is one of a series, sold  
for $12 million, while ``Waterloo Bridge, Effect of Fog,'' an 
atmospheric London scene painted in 1899-1900, sold for $9.3 
million. The buyers were anonymous, as were the sellers. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 48 lots offered Tuesday, 18 failed to find buyers. Among  
them were a Degas pastel of a ballet dancer, a Toulouse-Lautrec 
portrait of a redheaded woman sitting in a garden and a striking 
Paul Klee painting titled ``Fire Source.'' The auction house had 
estimated that each would sell for between $6 million and $8 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Diana Brooks, the president and chief executive officer of  
Sotheby's North America, said she expected several of the unsold 
works would quickly be sold privately. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's single-owner sale of artworks from the estate of  
socialite Betsey Cushing Whitney and her late husband, financier 
John Hay ``Jock'' Whitney, brought in $128.3 million as bidders 
snapped up all 50 of the lots offered. 
</P>
<P>
	The $60.5 million for the Cezanne was a record for the artist  
and the fourth-highest price ever paid for an artwork sold at 
auction. 
</P>
<P>
	All prices include Sotheby's commission of 15 percent of the  
first $50,000 and 10 percent of the rest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
