<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *Edward Abraham    	
</P>
<P>
	OXFORD, England (AP) -- Sir Edward Abraham, an Oxford University  
professor and biochemist who played an important role in the 
development of penicillin, died Sunday. He was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	As a researcher at Oxford, Abraham worked with Ernest Chain and  
Howard Florey on the purification of penicillin, and went on to 
develop the cephalosporin class of antibiotics now used extensively 
in the treatment of respiratory infections such as pneumonia and 
bronchitis. 
</P>
<P>
	He was knighted by Queen Elizabeth II in 1980.  

</P>
<P>
                         *William P. Gruber    	
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- William P. Gruber, a veteran business writer who  
retired last year from the Chicago Tribune, died Tuesday of a heart 
ailment. He was 67. 
</P>
<P>
	He was business editor of Chicago Today when it folded in 1974  
and then joined the Tribune. Gruber wrote a column chronicling the 
comings and goings of the area business community. 
</P>
<P>
	Gruber is survived by a brother and a sister.  

</P>
<P>
                        *John Ruggles Herbert    	
</P>
<P>
	SPRING HILL, Fla. (AP) -- John Ruggles Herbert, a former editor  
of The Patriot Ledger and the Boston Herald, died Monday. He was 
90. 
</P>
<P>
	Herbert joined The Ledger in the early 1930s, becoming managing  
editor in 1936 and the paper's editor 16 years later. 
</P>
<P>
	After leaving The Ledger in 1967, Herbert took over as editor of  
the Boston Herald. In 1970, he was named executive editor of the 
Boston Herald Traveler in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Hearst Corp. bought the Herald Traveler, he became  
president and chairman of the board at Quincy Co-operative Bank in 
1975, and retired in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	His leadership in supporting a free press in Latin America won  
him honors in the early 1960s. The Dominican government presented 
him with its highest civilian honor. 
</P>
<P>
	Herbert, a former Pulitzer Prize juror, was a life member of the  
Inter-American Press Association, and founder of the association's 
Technical Center in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides his wife, Margot, Herbert is survived by two sons, three  
grandchildren and five great-grandchildren. He is also survived by 
three stepchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Robert Keane    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Robert Keane, a longtime newspaper union  
organizer who began his career as a payroll clerk at the Daily 
News, died Tuesday of pneumonia. He was 76. 
</P>
<P>
	Keane was a Newspaper Guild negotiator for a decade and a half,  
and represented the union in talks with the Daily News, the New 
York Post, the New York Amsterdam News and Scientific American, 
among other publications. 
</P>
<P>
	Keane became involved in the Daily News Guild unit around 1960,  
and later became its chairman. He soon went to work full-time as a 
Guild organizer, helping to negotiate job security provisions at 
the Daily News in the late 1960s that became a model for workers at 
other newspapers and magazines, said Barry Lipton, president of the 
New York Guild. 
</P>
<P>
	Keane left the Guild in the 1970s to become administrator of the  
Guild-News pension fund, from which he retired in the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	He and his late wife, Norine, had eight sons and a daughter,  
four of whom entered the news business. One son, Kevin, is 
administrator of the Wire Service Guild in New York; another, Paul, 
is an entertainment editor at the Daily News; and daughter Lillian 
Berry works in advertising sales at the News. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Keane is also survived by 18 grandchildren and four  
great-granddaughters. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Tom Savage    	
</P>
<P>
	WESTON, Mass. (AP) -- The Rev. Tom Savage, former president of  
Rockhurst College, died Monday of severe respiratory problems. He 
was 51. 
</P>
<P>
	Savage became president of the Jesuit college when he was 41 and  
left in 1996, saying eight years was enough time to make a 
difference. He moved to California and worked for William M. Mercer 
Inc., a human resources consulting company. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kansas City, Savage served on the boards of the Ewing Marion  
Kauffman Foundation and the Kansas City Board of Trade. He was 
co-chairman of a group which produced a city master plan that the 
Kansas City Council adopted in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Savage, who was ordained a priest in 1979, had been assistant  
academic vice president at Fairfield University in Connecticut 
before being named president at Rockhurst. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Rosemary Valaire    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Rosemary Valaire, a former soloist with  
Britain's Royal Ballet and influential teacher at the Westside 
School of Ballet for three decades, died Friday of a brain tumor. 
She was 68. 
</P>
<P>
	Valaire was born as Rosemary Feuerheerd in London and adopted  
her stage name from the character Valerius in William Shakespeare's 
play ``The Two Noble Kinsmen.'' Valaire was a soloist with the 
Royal Ballet from 1946 until 1954 and held the prestigious Solo 
Seal. 
</P>
<P>
	She later reconstructed the Royal Ballet's version of ``Sleeping  
Beauty'' for several companies, including the American Ballet 
Theater in 1976, when she coached Natalia Makarova and Mikhail 
Baryshnikov for the lead roles. Valaire was widely known for her 
adherence to classical ballet. 
</P>
<P>
	She began teaching in 1967 at the Westside School of Ballet in  
Santa Monica, where she teamed up with Mounsey, a former New York 
City Ballet dancer, and worked through three decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
