<DOCNO> APW19990512.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 15:15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft, Sony Make Music Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Sony Music Entertainment will begin selling music  
and videos online as well as in stores, marking the recording 
industry's latest attempt to cash in on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony Music's partnership with Microsoft Corp. is the latest in a  
flurry of deals as music publishers scramble to balance their 
desire for getting a piece of the exploding online music market 
with their fears of copyright piracy on the wide-open world of the 
Web. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers will be able to download music singles beginning this  
summer, when Microsoft's Windows Media 4.0 software becomes 
available, the companies said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement followed last week's disclosure by Universal  
Music Group, the world's largest music company, of a partnership 
with InterTrust Technologies Corp. to develop a system to let 
customers download music to their computers in a secure format that 
prevents mass copying. 
</P>
<P>
	``The CD is headed the way of the vinyl record,'' said analyst  
Mark Hardie of Forrest Research Inc. of Cambridge, Mass., who 
forecast a transition into ``something even more convenient.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The industry has been on the album for about 40 years, and  
it's getting set to move off of that single-product orientation. 
It's going to take a lot of effort and will likely cause a great 
deal of pain, but it's going to happen,'' Hardie said. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance is expected to result in wider distribution and  
promotion for Sony and Microsoft's products, executives of both 
companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any opportunity for the consumer to purchase music in the  
physical or the virtual world should hopefully expand the market as 
a whole,'' Fred Ehrlich, Sony senior vice president and general 
manager for New Technology and Business Development. ``We know 
there is a demand out there for digital music right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Music singles will be priced at about the same cost as buying  
one in a store, Ehrlich said. The exact price will be set when the 
singles are ready to be released, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He emphasized that Sony no intention of circumventing retailers,  
who will be able to offer the digital singles through their own Web 
sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardie predicted that record stores were unlikely to disappear,  
but said their offerings were likely to evolve as technology 
develops. 
</P>
<P>
	``Brick-and-mortar retailers are going to have to figure out how  
to participate in digital delivery,'' he said. ``I expect they will 
pretty soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A three-minute song will take about five minutes to download  
using a 28.8 modem and Microsoft's Windows Media, said Will Poole, 
senior director of marketing and business development in 
Microsoft's streaming media division. It will take up just 1 1/2 
megabytes of space on a personal computer, compared with 10 
megabytes for the same amount of uncompressed audio, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new version of Windows Media will meet standards of the  
Secure Digital Music Initiative, which is designed to protect 
copyrights and ensure secure online transactions, Poole said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's one of the next frontiers for the industry as  
people talk about the convergence of the media and computer 
industries,'' said Microsoft's president, Steve Ballmer. ``To have 
the opportunity to work with a major company like Sony is very 
exciting for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Security has been a big obstacle for the music industry.  
</P>
<P>
	New technologies such as MP3, which gives near-CD quality to  
music downloaded from the Internet, have created a huge traffic in 
pirated music. Anyone with easily obtainable software and equipment 
can record music from a CD onto a computer and then give it away to 
millions of people by posting it on a Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 3, a day before Universal's announcement, RealNetworks,  
the Seattle-based maker of Internet audio and video software, 
unveiled plans for RealJukebox, a product designed to make it 
easier to download and play music on a computer. 
</P>
<P>
	Analyst Ron Rappaport, of Zona Research in Redwood City, Calif.,  
wasn't surprised by the developments. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there's a domino effect. Once one mover falls, the  
rest will follow,'' Rappaport said. ``Now they're in a position 
where they have to move and move fast, else their competition eats 
their lunch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sony Music Entertainment, headquartered in New York, has a  
catalog of more than 500,000 sound and video recordings, including 
artists such as Mariah Carey, Will Smith, Celine Dion and Ricky 
Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	Ehrlich declined to say how many singles Sony sells annually,  
nor what percentage the company would offer digitally. 
</P>
<P>
	He emphasized that the deal was not exclusive, and Sony would  
continue to participate in a project with BMG Entertainment, EMI 
Recorded Music, Universal Music Group and Warner Music Group to 
offer entire albums online. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, based in Redmond, is the world's largest computer  
software publisher. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
