<DOCNO> APW19990512.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 15:44:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Salinger Love Letters To Be Sold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The woman who hides nothing -- writer Joyce  
Maynard -- is selling letters she received from the man who hides 
everything -- reclusive author J.D. Salinger. 
</P>
<P>
	The letters, to be auctioned at Sotheby's, are considered  
documents of the rarest sort from an author who has shunned 
publicity, sued to protect his privacy, and has not published 
anything in 34 years. 
</P>
<P>
	They are expected to sell for $60,000 to $80,000.  
</P>
<P>
	The 14 letters were written in 1972-73 when Salinger, author of  
``The Catcher in the Rye,'' had an affair with Ms. Maynard. He was 
53; she was 18 and dropped out of Yale University to live in the 
Cornish, N.H., house where he still resides. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Ms. Maynard published ``At Home in the World,'' in  
which she detailed her relationship with Salinger. 
</P>
<P>
	``My decision to sell these letters is not some kind of act of  
retribution against Salinger,'' she said Wednesday. ``It's a 
financial decision. I'd rather put my efforts to supporting my 
three children than to have a box of Salinger letters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Maynard, who is divorced, has a 21-year-old daughter in  
college and two teen-age sons. 
</P>
<P>
	Salinger initiated the correspondence after reading an article  
Ms. Maynard wrote for The New York Times Magazine in 1972 called 
``An 18-Year-Old Looks Back on Life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He praised the article and later provided a phone number. The  
first letters were signed ``Sincerely, J.D. Salinger''; later, they 
ended, ``Love, Jerry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salinger successfully sued to stop a biographer from quoting  
other letters he wrote, so Sotheby's is guarding the content of 
these. The catalogue description quotes only two or three words 
from the letters. 
</P>
<P>
	Marsha Malinowski, Sotheby's manuscript expert, described the  
correspondence as ``love letters -- that couldn't be more clear -- 
from a gentleman quite taken with an 18-year-old writer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letters also illuminate Salinger's obsession for privacy.  
``He warns her of the impending fame, to be careful of what happens 
when you go in front of the public eye,'' Ms. Malinowski said. 
</P>
<P>
	His topics range from movies and TV -- he liked Hitchcock and ``I  
Love Lucy'' -- to his writing routines and taking his children to 
sporting events. At one point, he wrote of feeling depressed and 
drained after socializing. 
</P>
<P>
	The correspondence stopped after Ms. Maynard moved in. The last  
note, sent after they split up, coldly answers her questions about 
homeopathic medicine, and states that her letter is just one in a 
pile he is answering. He signs off, ``It's late, kiddo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salinger cannot stop Ms. Maynard from selling the letters, which  
are to be auctioned June 22. 
</P>
<P>
	Salinger's agent, Phyllis Westberg, had no comment. His lawyer,  
Andrew Boose, did not return a call. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Maynard, who has written extensively about her life,  
including her divorce, her kids and her physical appearance, said 
she has no qualms about bringing attention to a man who doesn't 
want it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've made a very different life decision than the one Jerry  
Salinger made years ago,'' she said. ``I'm not uncomfortable 
talking about my experiences and my feelings. Neither do I feel 
someone else's decision to be private and secretive obligates me to 
live the same way.'' 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
