<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Avalanche Excellent Away From Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- For the Avalanche, the good news is they're right  
back in their series with Detroit. The bad news is they still must 
win in Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche improved to 4-0 on the road during the playoffs  
with a 5-3 victory last night over Detroit. The Red Wings still 
lead the second-round series 2-1, but Colorado can pull even with a 
win Thursday in Game 4. 
</P>
<P>
	And no matter what happens in Game 4, the series definitely  
returns to Colorado for a fifth game Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche are just 1-4 at McNichols Arena, which will be  
replaced by the Pepsi Center next fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado center Dale Hunter can't figure out why his team is so  
much better on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I had an answer, we'd bottle it and take it home with us,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even during the season, the Avalanche were slightly better on  
the road. They were 23-14-4 when traveling, 21-14-6 when in Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit forward Wendel Clark, one of four key players the Red  
Wings picked up at the March 23 trading deadline, thinks some teams 
are more patient away from home. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, in the playoffs, most teams are playing good -- if  
not better -- on the road than they are at home, anyway,'' Clark 
said. ``It's not just one team. I think it's the playoffs in 
general.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After scoring twice in the first period of Game 1 against  
Detroit, the Avalanche failed to score again for the next 122 
minutes, 44 seconds. Along the way, Detroit won the first game 3-2 
in overtime and took a 4-0 win in Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	But all that frustration ended when Colorado had a two-man  
advantage and Claude Lemieux banged home a goal 11:00 into the 
first period Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Game 1, we played a good game,'' Colorado coach Bob Hartley  
said. ``The Red Wings got the final shot. I don't think we have to 
waste any energy on Game 2. It was a bad effort. We all know it. 
We've moved on. We were able to flush it from our system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It helped, too, that Bill Ranford, the backup Detroit  
goaltender, was suddenly coming unglued. 
</P>
<P>
	Ranford, the 1990 NHL playoff MVP with Edmonton, was starting  
his third straight game in goal in place of Chris Osgood, who is 
out with a sprained right knee. But the Avalanche scored on five of 
their first 23 shots and Ranford was replaced by Norm Maracle. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Wings coach Scotty Bowman most likely will start Ranford in  
Game 4. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's up to Scotty,'' Ranford said. ``I've been taking this  
day to day. I'm not getting caught up in that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings, seeking their third straight Stanley Cup  
championship, had won 11 straight playoff games -- including the 
last five last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, suddenly, they don't seem so invincible. And they certainly  
don't relish the prospect of wiping out whatever edge they had by 
winning the first two games. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is always pressure,'' Clark said. ``That's part of it  
and that's the exciting part of playoff hockey. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't get to the second round and not expect to meet a  
good team to play against. Just because they were down 0-2, they 
weren't going to roll over and die. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is too much character and too many good players over in  
that dressing room to do that. We know we're in for a fight to win 
this series.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
