<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 15:44:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Deports Man for Nazi Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An Indiana man who admitted serving in a  
Nazi-sponsored killing battalion during World War II left the 
United States permanently Wednesday for Lithuania, the Justice 
Department announced. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazys Ciurinskas, 81, who lived in Crown Point, Ind., left the  
country Wednesday afternoon by plane from Chicago, the department 
said. On April 15, U.S. Immigration Judge Anthony Petrone in 
Chicago had ordered Ciurinskas removed from this country based on 
his admitted participation in acts of Nazi-sponsored persecution. 
</P>
<P>
	Eli M. Rosenbaum, director of the department's Nazi-hunting  
Office of Special Investigations, said the removal order was part 
of a settlement agreement in which Ciurinskas admitted he was an 
armed member of the 2nd Lithuanian Schutzmannschaft (Protective 
Detachment) Battalion and concealed that service when he applied 
for a visa to enter the United States in 1949. 
</P>
<P>
	Ciurinskas also conceded he was subject to removal under a  
provision of U.S. law that requires removal of any alien who 
assisted Nazi persecution, the department said. 
</P>
<P>
	After a trial, a federal judge in Indiana revoked Ciurinskas'  
naturalized U.S. citizenship in 1997 because of his service in the 
2nd Battalion. The court noted that the battalion assisted the 
Nazis in 10 killing actions in Lithuania and Byelorussia, now 
Belarus, that murdered more than 19,000 Jewish men, women and 
children in the fall of 1941. The court concluded that Ciurinskas 
participated in at least one such action. 
</P>
<P>
	Ciurinskas is one of several members of the 2nd Battalion that  
the special investigations office has ousted from this country. Two 
other members of the 2nd Battalion have been ordered deported to 
Lithuania. 
</P>
<P>
	Juozas Naujalis was ordered removed by the immigration court in  
Chicago in 1997, but is appealing his case to the U.S. Board of 
Immigration Appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	Another 2nd Battalion member, Antanas Mineikis of Gulfport,  
Fla., was deported to Lithuania in 1992 after admitting he drove 
multiple truckloads of civilian victims to mass shooting sites and 
observed their murders. ``I saw women and children shot,'' Mineikis 
admitted in a sworn statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, Rosenbaum criticized Lithuania for dragging  
its feet in prosecuting two other major Nazi-collaborators that his 
office pursued in this country. Rosenbaum said then that the U.S. 
government has evidence that 91-year-old Aleksandras Lileikis had 
been feigning illness to avoid trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Lileikis, who lived for 40 years in Norwood, Mass., outside  
Boston, is accused of executing Jews for the Nazis while serving as 
head of security police in the Lithuanian capital of Vilnius during 
the German occupation. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosenbaum's office got a U.S. District Court to revoke Lileikis'  
naturalized U.S. citizenship in 1996 and was moving to deport him 
when he returned to Lithuania. 
</P>
<P>
	A Lithuanian medical panel also has said that 91-year-old Kazys  
Gimzauskas, who was Lileikis' wartime deputy, is too ill to stand 
trial. Gimzauskas fled to Lithuania from his home in St. 
Petersburg, Fla., in 1993. He, too, was stripped of his naturalized 
U.S. citizenship in a proceeding begun by Rosenbaum's office. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials said Wednesday that the Lithuanian trials of  
Lileikis and Gimzauskas remain stalled. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2nd battalion's killings in Lithuania and Byelorussia were  
``calculated and unspeakably brutal,'' Rosenbaum said. Captured 
wartime documents show the fall 1941 killing spree ``repulsed even 
the Nazis,'' Rosenbaum added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 06:05:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Passage of Hate Crimes Bill Sought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A woman whose son died after a beating  
inflicted partly because he was gay says a bill extending civil 
rights protections to homosexuals may spare other families similar 
suffering. 
</P>
<P>
	The death last fall of Matthew Shepard, 21, a University of  
Wyoming college student, became a rallying point for gays 
nationwide who are seeking state and federal legislation to protect 
them from discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	An emotional Judy Shepard delivered the message to a Senate  
committee Tuesday as she described the late-night telephone call 
that informed her and her husband that their son had lapsed into a 
coma after the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	While conceding the bill is not a ``cure-all,'' she said  
enacting it ``will send the message that this senseless violence is 
unacceptable and un-American. It will let perpetrators of hate 
violence know their actions will be punished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If even one family can avoid getting that phone call in the  
middle of the night because of this legislation, then it will be 
worth it,'' Mrs. Shepard added. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents say the bill is unnecessary because states have not  
avoided prosecuting such crimes. One of the two men charged in 
Shepard's death pleaded guilty to murder last month and was 
sentenced to two consecutive life terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics also say the bill itself would discriminate by creating  
special classes of victims such as gays, would greatly expand the 
federal government's power and jurisdiction and would have a 
``chilling effect'' on free speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``While well-intentioned, a law like this could be greatly  
abused,'' said Robert Knight, senior director of cultural studies 
at the conservative Family Research Council, which opposes the 
legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, sponsored Sens. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., and Edward  
Kennedy, D-Mass., would add disability, gender and sexual 
orientation to federal civil rights law and make it easier for the 
Justice Department to investigate and prosecute. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton supports the measure.  
</P>
<P>
	Current federal law prohibits crimes based on race, color,  
religion or national origin. Eight states have no hate crimes laws. 
Laws in 21 states cover sexual orientation. Twenty-two state laws 
include gender, and 21 cover disability. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch asked for  
additional information on bias crimes after Deputy Attorney General 
Eric Holder said ``the data we have are inadequate.'' Hatch, 
R-Utah, also voiced reservations about Congress stepping into an 
arena reserved for states -- criminal prosecutions. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI collects data from local police agencies. But Holder  
said the number is often underestimated because many victims don't 
report the offenses and police don't always recognize them as bias 
crimes or collect the information. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest FBI statistics show 8,049 reported hate crimes in  
1997. Of that, 1,102 incidents were motivated by the victim's 
sexual orientation, Holder said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said local and state authorities prosecute most hate crimes,  
and the Justice Department would intervene only in the rarest 
cases, such as when a local prosecutor is unable or unwilling to 
prosecute. Hatch asked for examples. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the states are doing the job, then what's the need for  
really broad legislation that basically may not be necessary under 
the circumstances?'' Hatch said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S. 622.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
