<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Foot Cream Sheds Prescription </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lamisil Cream, the top-selling prescription  
medication for athlete's foot, on Tuesday began selling over the 
counter. 
</P>
<P>
	Because Lamisil cures athlete's foot with one week of treatment  
compared to four weeks for the competition, Swiss drugmaker 
Novartis predicts strong demand even though Lamisil Cream is $1 to 
$2 more expensive than leading over-the-counter products. 
</P>
<P>
	Novartis already markets the third-leading over-the-counter  
athlete's foot medication -- Desenex. Schering-Plough dominates the 
category with its No. 1 selling Lotrimin and No. 2 selling Tinactin 
brands. 
</P>
<P>
	Athlete's foot, or tinea pedis, is a fungus of the foot  
affecting about 10 percent of the U.S. population each year. The 
infection, characterized by an annoying itch typically between the 
fourth and fifth toes, is usually spread in showers and locker 
rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamisil Cream differs from other over-the-counter athlete's foot  
remedies because it actually kills the fungi that cause the 
infection, rather than only inhibiting fungal growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamisil Cream had $69.3 million in sales in 1998, according to  
Novartis. In comparison, Lotrimin had $57.7 million in sales for 
the 52-week period ended March 28, 1999, according to market data 
firm Information Resources Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamisil Cream also treats other fungus-related skin conditions.  
</P>
<P>
	``Lamisil does seem very effective and to work faster than other  
medications,'' said Dr. Darrell Rigel, president of the American 
Academy of Dermatology. 
</P>
<P>
	Novartis is taking the drug over the counter because its studies  
show 85 percent of consumers diagnose and treat the condition 
themselves. Lamisil was first introduced as a prescription product 
in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	A small tube of Lamisil Cream now sells for between $7.50 and  
$9, about a third of the prescription price. Novartis expects 
consumers to pay up to $2 more for Lamisil Cream because they only 
have to use a fourth as much as competing brands to get rid of 
their athlete's foot. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to gaining market share from rivals, Novartis hopes  
to attract the nearly 30 percent of athlete's foot sufferers who 
don't treat the ailment, said Barry Cohen, a Novartis marketing 
executive. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem with other athlete's foot medications is most  
consumers only take them for a few days and stop applying them once 
the itching stops, Cohen said. As a result, the consumer never 
completely overcomes the infection and the itching returns again 
and again. 
</P>
<P>
	``The beautiful part is that Lamisil is used the way consumers  
behave today,'' Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Novartis will continue to sell Desenex, which comes in a powder  
form. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Administration approved the switch of Lamisil  
Cream to over the counter in March. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
