<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Constant Change for Timberwolves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- It's a real circus in the Target Center this  
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only are the Minnesota Timberwolves scrambling to tweak  
their game plan again as their first-round playoff series with San 
Antonio moves north, but they're being forced to work around the 
Shrine Circus, which booked the arena through the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The circus will be dismantled and reassembled twice by Friday  
night, which is an appropriate backdrop for the Wolves, who have 
done much of the same thing throughout this truncated season. 
</P>
<P>
	Change worked wonders for Minnesota in its 80-71 upset of the  
Spurs in San Antonio on Tuesday night, which evened the best-of-5 
series at a game each. 
</P>
<P>
	``They did everything better than we did,'' Spurs center David  
Robinson said. ``They were better in every respect. We didn't shoot 
the ball, we didn't rebound, we didn't get loose balls, we didn't 
defend. We were bad offensively and didn't execute. Everything 
broke down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	You can credit the changes in the Timberwolves' execution and  
emotion. 
</P>
<P>
	After fading down the stretch in Game 1 when Terrell Brandon and  
Kevin Garnett got into foul trouble, the Wolves went with a bigger 
lineup and a more aggressive attitude in the rematch and both stars 
benefitted. 
</P>
<P>
	First, 6-11 center Dean Garrett replaced 6-7 forward Sam  
Mitchell in the starting lineup and helped hold Robinson to six 
shots and 11 points, and Mitchell was effective coming off the 
bench. 
</P>
<P>
	The Timberwolves outrebounded the taller Spurs, Garnett was a  
force down the stretch, Brandon logged 47 minutes and the 
supporting cast made a spectacular debut, highlighted by Anthony 
Peeler's game-clinching 3-pointer. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you could see how our team focuses, you'd know it's playoff  
time,'' Garnett said. ``We eat, sleep and dream about the Spurs. 
The focus is there. I feel confident going home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So, why deviate from the successful shift in strategy?  
</P>
<P>
	``Because the Spurs are a veteran team and they're going to  
watch that film and figure out ways to stop us on both ends,'' said 
Brandon, who joined the team in a midseason trade from Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	``Besides, we didn't play a perfect ball game. We only scored 80  
points. We can do a lot of things better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota now has the homecourt advantage, but for the  
Timberwolves to join the 1994 Denver Nuggets as the only No. 8 
seeds ever to advance into the second round, they're going to have 
to be willing to change some more, coach Flip Saunders agreed after 
Wednesday's practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what the playoffs are: adjustments, adapting to  
different situations,'' Saunders said. ``That's when it is the most 
fun. I think our players, they expect that we're going to do 
different things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Timberwolves fed off Saunders' enthusiasm. He looked more  
like a traffic cop than a basketball coach on the sideline Tuesday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they see you show a sense of urgency, they're going to show  
that same sense of urgency,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Saunders had to make sure his players didn't bask in their  
success for too long. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're a very good basketball team. There's a reason they're  
the No. 1 seed in the league and they got homecourt advantage,'' 
Saunders said. ``But we've got a lot more confidence now knowing 
it's 1-1. We're coming back home; we've played extremely well at 
home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd be very disappointed if we didn't have a sellout crowd, if  
our crowd isn't going crazy because this is another step in the 
evolution,'' Saunders added. ``Last year we won a playoff game, we 
took it to a Game 5, didn't win it. So, we've kind of knocked on 
the door. We're knocking on the door again. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's about time to open it and walk through it. We've got an  
opportunity to do that here at home.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
