<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Letterer Dies at Age 91 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- C. Earl Leslie, who worked in the White House  
social office to hand letter everything from inaugural invitations 
to historic documents, died of cancer May 6 in Alexandria, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Leslie mastered the art of engrossing -- a form of lettering  
commonly used in the Middle Ages -- at a young age and moved here in 
1933 to be secretary to then-Interior Secretary Harold L. Ickes. He 
moved to the White House two years later, where he served during 
the administrations of Franklin Roosevelt, Harry Truman and Dwight 
Eisenhower. 
</P>
<P>
	Leslie's work varied from the proclamation of German surrender  
in World War II to place cards for state dinners. Leslie, who 
served as assistant chief of the White House's social office, was 
sometimes called upon by the Secret Service as a hand-writing 
expert. 
</P>
<P>
	Leslie continued engrossing independently for 20 years after  
leaving the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., Leslie learned his lettering  
technique at age 13 before joining his father and brother in their 
art studio. He is survived by a daughter, a granddaughter, a 
brother and a sister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
