<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Forces Cross Albania Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAJRAM CURRI, Albania (AP) -- In one of their deepest  
cross-border incursions so far, Yugoslav soldiers stormed two 
northern Albanian villages in an offensive aimed at cutting supply 
lines of the Kosovo rebels, international observers said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Word of the fighting came with NATO Secretary-General Javier  
Solana announcing that that U.S. Apache helicopters would see 
action ``very soon'' in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``The conflict is not going to be sent into Albania,'' Solana  
said in the Albanian capital of Tirana. ``I want to reassure the 
people of this country that NATO will not tolerate any action 
against this country stemming from the presence of NATO forces.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Serbs and the rebels clashed throughout the day Tuesday and  
late into the night. There was only sporadic shelling along the 
border Wednesday, and it appeared the Yugoslav forces had pulled 
back to their side of the frontier, the observers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelling is a daily routine along the border, and the Yugoslav  
forces have made brief, periodic forays across the Albanian border 
in hot pursuit of KLA rebels. But Tuesday's fighting was unusually 
heavy, observers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebel Kosovo Liberation Army controls small parcels of  
southwestern Kosovo and has been funneling fighters and weapons 
into other parts of the embattled province. But the rebels have 
been outgunned by the much more powerful Yugoslav army. 
</P>
<P>
	Artillery shells exploded on both sides of the Kosovo-Albanian  
border, sending up columns of gray smoke visible from the Albanian 
town of Bajram Curri, only six miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the deepest penetration (by Yugoslav forces) and the  
longest we have seen,'' Pier Gonggrijp, head of the Bajram Curri 
office of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, 
said Wednesday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20 Yugoslav troops occupied the border village of Perroi i  
Thanes, about a half-mile inside Albania, said Pier Gonggrijp, a 
local official of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in 
Europe, citing witnesses at the border. About 50 Yugoslav soldiers 
clashed with KLA forces and took the border village of Kasaj, 
Gonggrijp said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty wounded KLA fighters were hospitalized in Bajram Curri on  
Tuesday, and KLA sources said three others were killed in the 
fighting. There was no word on Yugoslav casualties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 09:35:10 </DATE_TIME>
