<DOCNO> APW19990512.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 21:11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Only Judge Can Allow Penguins' Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- If the Pittsburgh Penguins are to become the  
Portland Penguins, the road to Oregon must first pass through a 
U.S. bankruptcy judge's office, not that of NHL commissioner Gary 
Bettman. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the hardened stance taken recently by the NHL, one  
designed to accelerate the Penguins' bankruptcy proceedings, 
Bettman concedes the league can't move them unless Judge Bernard 
Markovitz's allows it. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, league officials suggested the NHL could disband or  
relocate the team if the 1999-2000 season was approaching and the 
Penguins' case was not resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Lemieux group is moving at an appropriate rate of speed,''  
said Bettman, who is attending the Maple Leafs-Penguins playoff 
series. ``These are complicated issues, and the bankruptcy judge is 
doing what he believes is in the best interests of the bankruptcy 
proceedings. I learned long ago never to disagree with a judge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Especially one who controls the fate of one of only two NHL  
franchises in a top-25 United States TV market -- St. Louis is the 
other -- without winter competition from an NBA franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven months ago, shortly after the Penguins filed for Chapter  
11 protection, the NHL agreed to a court order that it would not 
seek to vacate the franchise while the Penguins were in bankruptcy. 
Markovitz also has ruled that the Penguins' arena lease, which runs 
through 2007, is binding. 
</P>
<P>
	Markovitz on Tuesday rejected the NHL's request to move up the  
creditors' vote on Lemieux's bid from June 24. But he did agree to 
hear the league's request that its own plan move forward at the 
same pace as Lemieux's. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL plan, which Bettman said is strictly a backup in case  
Lemieux's bid falters, calls for the Penguins to be sold for $85 
million to an out-of-town owner -- presumably, Seattle Seahawks 
owner Paul Allen, the Microsoft co-founder -- in time to relocate 
for next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would like to have the Penguins reorganize in Pittsburgh,  
but if that doesn't work, we have to look at the alternatives: Is 
there a buyer who is prepared to take the franchise on very short 
notice for next season?'' Bettman said. ``Taking a club at the end 
of June, to start selling tickets and get up and running for the 
start of next season would be no picnic for anyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Allen, who also owns the NBA's Portland Trail Blazers, said he  
has not made a specific bid for the Penguins. But he did not deny 
being interested in putting an NHL franchise into the nearly new 
Rose Garden arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Another bankruptcy judge, M. Bruce McCullough, said the NHL is  
working on three schedules for next season: one with the Penguins 
in Pittsburgh, another with them on the West Coast, presumably 
Portland, and a third without them. 
</P>
<P>
	If nothing else, the news that a deep-pockets owner is willing  
to relocate the Penguins immediately caused a rumble Wednesday not 
only in Pittsburgh, but in the state capital of Harrisburg. 
</P>
<P>
	With much of the Penguins' financial mess blamed on an  
unfavorable arena lease that management firm SMG has refused to 
renegotiate, City Council president Bob O'Connor again raised the 
possibility of using eminent domain to reclaim the arena. City 
Council decided Tuesday to delay exploring any such action for now. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Connor said he met briefly with Bettman at Tuesday's playoff  
game to discuss the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best thing is to keep the team here,'' O'Connor said.  
``There is a history and tradition here that can't be duplicated 
elsewhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Harrisburg, Gov. Tom Ridge, who shepherded the funding  
package for four new stadiums in Pittsburgh and Philadelphia 
through the Legislature three months ago, said he is amenable to 
discussing a new arena once new local Penguins ownership is in 
place. 
</P>
<P>
	Privately, city and state government officials believe a new  
arena to replace the 38-year-old Civic Arena would be an easier 
sell to taxpayers than the stadiums, because it would be used 
year-around for concerts, circuses and meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had one conversation with ... Gary Bettman, and I told  
him that after the legal matters have been resolved that I 
anticipate, given the age of the (Civic Arena), that they will be 
looking for some public assistance, and we would be open to that 
discussion,'' Ridge said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Kevin Constantine said the Penguins' history of attracting  
big crowds and fielding competitive teams should not be overlooked. 
The Penguins have played to about 90 percent of arena capacity 
while reaching the Stanley Cup playoffs each year since 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's so much fun in this town because of hockey, it would  
be a shame to not have it in Pittsburgh,'' he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 08:05:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arnett Signs With Internet Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Veteran correspondent Peter Arnett, who ended  
his 18-year association with CNN last month, has landed a job with 
a new Internet broadcaster that specializes in international news. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnett will do interviews with major international leaders for  
foreigntv.com, a media service that was started by Al Primo, a 
television consultant who pioneered ``Eyewitness News'' for local 
TV. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll do about one interview per month and also advise Primo in  
setting up bureaus in cities around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnett and CNN parted ways nine months after he narrated an  
ill-fated report charging the U.S. military used nerve gas on 
American defectors during the Vietnam War. CNN later retracted the 
story and disciplined Arnett. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnett, who won a Pulitzer Prize for The Associated Press for  
his Vietnam coverage, said the Internet venture reminded him of CNN 
in its early days. He had no immediate plans for a return to 
broadcast TV. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really feel that CNN is the state of the art in covering  
action news,'' he said. ``To try to go against them would be a 
little foolhardy and I would feel slightly ridiculous.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 16:21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  UCLA's Davis To Enter NBA Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- UCLA point guard Baron Davis and his  
surgically repaired left knee are headed to the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``The NBA is calling and I think I'm ready for the challenge,''  
Davis said Wednesday in announcing he would forgo his final two 
years of eligibility to enter the NBA draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do have the ability to make an impact and I want that  
challenge,'' he said. ``This has been a lifelong dream for me. I 
feel it's time to be challenged at the highest level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, a 6-foot-2 1/2 sophomore, averaged 15.9 points, 5.1 assists  
and 2.5 steals for the Bruins last season. He missed the first four 
games while recovering from a knee injury that occurred during the 
1998 NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``My injury put things in perspective,'' he said. ``I don't  
think it played that big of a part (in his decision) ... I just 
felt at this point in my life, with the way my knee is now it's at 
full strength, that it can only get better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a freshman, before injuring his knee, Davis averaged 11.7  
points, 4.0 rebounds, 5.0 assists and 2.4 steals. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, 20, said he decided two days ago to enter the draft.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was still going back and forth. It's a hard decision,'' he  
said. ``It's not about money because money can't buy all the 
experiences I had here, all the laughs and all the crying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a campus news conference, Davis was flanked by his  
grandmother, who raised him, and his sister, his brother-in-law and 
Lavin. Davis said he promised his grandmother he would eventually 
earn a college degree. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bruins had a 46-18 record in Davis' two seasons, with  
third-place finishes in the Pacific-10 Conference both years. UCLA 
reached the final 16 of the NCAA tournament when Davis was a 
freshman, but lost to Detroit in the first round this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of my dreams along the way was to win a national  
championship, and it kind of hurts my heart that I will have to 
leave that behind,'' he said. ``I wanted to be known as one of the 
greatest point guards ever to play at UCLA. I didn't hang any 
(national) banners, so it's kind of hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	UCLA coach Steve Lavin said he talked to scouts and NBA  
officials, including Jerry West of the Lakers and Elgin Baylor of 
the Clippers, and they told him Davis could go as high as a No. 2 
pick and most likely no lower than a No. 6 pick. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question he's a lottery-level pick,'' Lavin said.  
``Baron was a very gifted, special player that you could go a 
lifetime as a coach and maybe only have a handful of players who 
are at Baron Davis' level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis named the hometown Lakers and Clippers as the two teams  
he'd like to play for. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kind of want to get thrown to the fire at a young age,''  
Davis said. ``I know that going up against guys like Stephon 
(Marbury), Allen Iverson and Jason Kidd night in and night out is 
going to do nothing but make me better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis informed his teammates Tuesday night that he was leaving.  
Several of them attended the news conference, and said they would 
miss Davis' emotional floor leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	``The playmaking ability Baron brought us is not going to be  
there,'' said forward Sean Farnham, who will be a senior. ``Baron 
is one of those players that come along every so often, but few and 
far between. He gave us unbelievable excitement.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 16:21:03 </DATE_TIME>
