<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 20:11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pollin To Sell Washington Capitals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Abe Pollin is passing the torch to a  
computer-marketing whiz, giving the nation's capital a 
new-generation owner for the NHL's Capitals and, eventually, the 
NBA's Wizards and the MCI Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying he wanted to spend ``a little less time in sports, and a  
little more time doing things for folks who are less fortunate,'' 
Pollin said Wednesday he is selling the Capitals, plus a minority 
interest in Washington Sports &AMP; Entertainment -- which owns the 
Wizards, the MCI Center and US Airways Arena -- to a partnership 
headed by America Online executive Ted Leonsis. 
</P>
<P>
	``And someday when I decide to call it quits,'' Pollin said,  
``he will have first and last crack to own it all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leonsis, along with local entrepreneur Jonathan Ledecky and  
Capitals president Dick Patrick, is making an initial investment of 
about $200 million in the sale. About $85 million of that is the 
price for the money-losing Capitals. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollin, accompanied by his wife and two sons, said he started  
looking for a buyer a year ago because he ``wanted to go out on 
top'' after the Capitals made their first-ever appearance in the 
Stanley Cup finals. With his sons expressing no interest in leaving 
their careers to take over his business, the 75-year-old executive 
said he agonized over the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did not want a repeat of the mess that the Redskins went  
through in their transition,'' Pollin said. ``We were talked to by 
a lot of people, met with a lot of people and there was one person 
who stood out among all of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Noting that more and more teams are sold to corporations, Pollin  
said he wanted someone who would be an active member of the 
community. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would never sell to a corporation,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	With the free time and money he gains from selling the Capitals,  
Pollin plans to do more charity work. One of his first duties will 
be chairing a UNICEF relief effort for Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	He remains in charge of the Wizards and his $200 million  
downtown arena, which opened in December 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to stress here and now that I am not retiring.'' he  
said. ``My goal is to bring another NBA championship to Washington 
and we're not going to quit until we do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leonsis, 43, is president of AOL Interactive Properties Group,  
an arm of AOL that describes itself as the ``leading online content 
programmer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is a 1977 graduate of Georgetown and has been labeled by The  
Wall Street Journal as ``one of the Web world's most influential 
players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing I know how to do is bring customers in,''  
Leonsis said. ``When I joined AOL (in 1994), we had 800,000 
members. When I moved to my new position, we had 8 million. So I 
understand the power of marketing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the sale is approved by NHL owners, who next meet June 22,  
Patrick would continue as president of the Capitals and assume more 
of the day-to-day operation of the club. He said he plans to retain 
general manager George McPhee and coach Ron Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dick is in charge of the Capitals,'' Leonsis said. ``And I'll  
be the fat guy with the cigar in the owners' box yelling and 
screaming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new owners plan to aggressively market the teams on the  
Internet. Ledecky promised a web strategy that will be ``at the 
cutting edge'' for major sports teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Ledecky is chairman of Building One Services Corp., one of  
America's largest facilities maintenance companies. He is the 
group's number-cruncher. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's no secret the Capitals have been losing money for  
years,'' Ledecky said. ``We want to put a winning product on the 
ice, but at the same time we have to make the numbers work because 
that's the way teams have gotten into trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ledecky said the group has set aside extra money beyond the $200  
million rebuild the Capitals into a contender. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have one mission -- to etch our names on the Stanley Cup,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	News of the sale came as another NHL club, the bankrupt  
Pittsburgh Penguins, is close to being sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The Capitals would be the second of three major sports team  
sales expected this year in Washington. The NFL most likely will 
approve the sale of the Redskins to another local marketing 
upstart, 34-year-old Daniel Snyder, later this month. D.C. United 
of Major League Soccer is also on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	``Based on everything we've heard, preliminarily, we are not  
anticipating any problems,'' NHL commissioner Gary Bettman said of 
the Capitals sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollin purchased the Wizards, then known as the Baltimore  
Bullets, in 1964 and became sole owner in 1968. He built his first 
arena, the Capital Centre in Landover, Md., in 1973 and moved his 
NBA team there. The Capitals, Pollin's expansion NHL franchise, 
opened play there a year later. 
</P>
<P>
	This season for Pollin could be summed up in one word: losing.  
The Capitals and Wizards both missed the playoffs for the first 
time since 1980-81. The Capitals, just one season after making the 
finals, finished 31-45-6. 

</P>
</TEXT>
