<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Park Death Ruled a Homicide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The death of a magazine executive who had  
apparently gone jogging in Central Park has been ruled a homicide, 
making it the park's first this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Matthew Herman, a 33-year-old Fortune magazine advertising  
manager, was found lying face down in dirt on Monday morning by a 
man walking his dog near 69th Street, a couple of blocks north of 
the Central Park zoo. 
</P>
<P>
	While Herman had had medical problems in the past, medical  
examiners say the 6-foot, 185-pound man died of neck compression, 
possibly by being placed in a chokehold. There were no finger marks 
on his neck, but police said bruises marked Herman's lower neck, 
upper chest and arms. He also had bloodshot eyes, which can result 
from chest compression. 
</P>
<P>
	Herman had undergone brain surgery several years ago and last  
month, was hospitalized for three weeks last month with tremors. 
</P>
<P>
	A park visitor first noticed Herman lying on the grass Sunday  
evening, but from her vantage point a distance away it just looked 
like a jogger perhaps sprawled out for a snooze. She told police 
she saw a man in his 40s standing nearby, and police said today 
they hoped to question him. 
</P>
<P>
	Police initially thought Herman died of a heart attack while  
jogging because there were no obvious signs of a struggle. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said robbery did not appear to be a motive.  
Herman's keys, tape player and watch remained on his body, and his 
wallet was found in his undisturbed West 57th Street apartment, 
along with an uneaten dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had taken out something to eat with the intention of having  
it when he came back,'' Deputy Inspector Joseph Reznick said. 
</P>
<P>
	Herman's body was identified on Tuesday after his parents  
contacted authorities to say they were unable to reach him. His 
father last saw him Sunday at 6:30 p.m. as he dropped him off 
following a Mother's Day visit in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Fellow Fortune executives said they were baffled by Herman's  
death. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not a person here who didn't think he was the nicest  
guy on the face of the Earth,'' said Jolene Sykes, the magazine's 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Compared with last year, overall crime is down in Central Park.  
By this time in 1998, there were 40 crimes reported, including one 
killing. So far this year, there have been 10 robberies and two 
assaults in addition to Herman's killing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
