<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Demands End to NATO Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Boris Yeltsin warned today that Russia  
may pull out of Yugoslav peace efforts if its proposals are not 
taken into consideration, Russian news agencies reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The weight of the threat was unclear, as the announcement came  
on a day of political turmoil. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours earlier, Yeltsin fired Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov,  
igniting a major political crisis -- and the day before impeachment 
proceedings against Yeltsin were scheduled to begin in Russia's 
parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Primakov's dismissal is likely to have serious implications for  
the Kosovo crisis. Russia's internal political problems could 
distract the Kremlin's efforts to find a diplomatic solution to the 
Balkan conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not taking part in this war, it is not our country that  
started it,'' Yeltsin said before Russia's Security Council today, 
the ITAR-Tass and Interfax news agencies reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people obviously aren't understanding our repeated  
proposals'' for solving the crisis around the Yugoslav province of 
Kosovo, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has opposed NATO's airstrikes on Yugoslavia but has  
sought to mediate a political solution, sending envoys shuttling 
around Europe for talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier today, Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said there is little  
hope of finding a quick political solution if NATO persists in its 
airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivanov lashed out at NATO's insistence that it will continue its  
strikes as he began talks with Deputy Secretary of State Strobe 
Talbott, who is seeking Moscow's support for a negotiated deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``This does not benefit the negotiating process. If the NATO  
military leadership pursues this course, all efforts aimed at 
seeking a political settlement might become futile,'' Ivanov said. 
</P>
<P>
	Talbott said NATO's strategy on Kosovo had not changed despite  
Russia's insistence that successful negotiations can't take place 
unless NATO bombing halts. 
</P>
<P>
	After meeting with Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, Talbott said  
NATO's position is ``clear and firm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Talbott said he and Ivanov also discussed a peace plan worked  
out by the seven leading industrial nations and Russia earlier this 
month in Bonn. The two made no major breakthroughs. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, Ivanov said there was a chance that the talks with  
Talbott could produce a breakthrough. He said the two sides would 
try to work out a common approach on a Kosovo settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin discussed the Kosovo situation today with his special  
envoy on the problem, ex-premier Viktor Chernomyrdin, to see if 
there was any way to advance the diplomatic process. Talbott was to 
meet later with Chernomyrdin. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States and NATO want Moscow to back their demands on  
ending the conflict. Moscow backs a peacekeeping force for Kosovo 
and the return of refugees, but has not agreed to NATO's demand for 
the withdrawal of Yugoslav forces from the province. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has demanded a halt to the NATO attacks despite the  
alliance's insistence that it will not stop until Belgrade meets 
its basic demands. 
</P>
<P>
	French President Jacques Chirac was due to arrive in Moscow  
later today. Kosovo was expected to top the agenda of his talks 
with Russian leaders, including Yeltsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin hinted that Russia and China might coordinate their  
attempts to solve the crisis, but would offer no more details. He 
did, however, say that China might take part in a U.N. peacekeeping 
force in Kosovo, if the Yugoslav government agrees to such a force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
