<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Lower at Midday / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks slipped at midday Thursday  
following news U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin will step down. 
The dollar was higher against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 52.54 points,  
or 0.31 percent, ending the morning session at 16,894.82. On 
Wednesday, the average rose 204.18 points, or 1.22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.10 yen at midday, up 0.24 yen from late  
Wednesday in Tokyo and also higher than its late New York level of 
120.95 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss in the Tokyo Stock Exchange was limited in part because  
many players consider the choice of Rubin's successor, Deputy 
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, as signaling continuity rather 
than divergence in U.S. financial policies, said Tsuyoshi 
Nomaguchi, a strategist at Daiwa Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	President Bill Clinton announced Wednesday that he would  
nominate Summers, a former Harvard University professor who has 
worked closely with Rubin, as his third Treasury secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock market sentiment in Tokyo was also hurt after Russian  
President Boris Yeltsin on Wednesday dismissed his prime minister, 
Yevgeny Primakov, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 6.51 points, or 0.48 percent, to 1,354.64. 
The TOPIX closed up 5.33 points, or 0.39 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar was moving little after gaining  
ground on dollar-buying prompted by a belief that Rubin's successor 
may maintain a strong dollar policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday morning, Eisuke Sakakibara, Japan's vice finance  
minister for international affairs, said he doesn't expect any 
change in U.S. foreign exchange policy because of Rubin's 
departure, expected around July 4. 
</P>
<P>
	``They will continue on course. They have a very strong team,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the euro declined because of Primakov's dismissal.  
The currency was traded at 128.94 yen at midday, down from 129.15 
yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.350 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.340 percent, driving 
its price down to 101.33 yen from 101.42 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
