<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Billboards Come Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A convenience store chain announced today  
that it will take down cigarette billboards in five states that 
critics said violated a 46-state agreement with the tobacco 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Wawa Food Markets said in a statement that although the  
settlement's ban on tobacco billboard advertising did not include 
retailers, the chain was discontinuing the practice voluntarily 
because it created ``confusion in the marketplace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Barg, a medical newsletter publisher who heads the  
antismoking group Tobacco Free Education and Action Coalition for 
Health, said Wawa's decision may have been prompted by plans for a 
demonstration at a Wawa billboard that was to be filmed by ABC's 
``Good Morning America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barg said he was glad the signs were coming down but unhappy  
that their legality remained unresolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wawa is painting this as a purely voluntary action on their  
part,'' he said. ``If that is not clarified by the attorney general 
and the tobacco companies, then that gives license to other 
retailers who are less responsible to do this advertising, totally 
negating the billboard advertising provisions of the settlement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pennsylvania Attorney General Mike Fisher praised Wawa's  
decision, which he said followed discussions he had with a company 
vice president, whom he did not identify. 
</P>
<P>
	But while Fisher said he was committed to enforcing the tobacco  
settlement's ban on billboard advertising, he stopped short of 
saying that the ban applies to retailers. ``The cooperation of 
responsible retailers like Wawa helps in that goal,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The tobacco industry settlement with 46 states required  
cigarette companies to strip the Marlboro man and other cigarette 
symbols from billboards by April 23. 
</P>
<P>
	But Wawa, a privately-held chain of nearly 500 stores in  
Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Delaware, Maryland and Virginia, 
continued to feature a bright red pack of Marlboros with the words 
``$2.19 for limited time only,'' on many of its highway billboards. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher said 100 billboards in the five states, including about  
40 in Pennsylvania, were expected to be removed within about 10 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	``We recognize that our continued use of tobacco billboards  
created confusion in the marketplace,'' Wawa said in its statement. 
``Following discussions with the attorney general ... and 
evaluating consumer response, we voluntarily decided to discontinue 
our long-standing practice of tobacco billboard advertising.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barg said ``Good Morning America'' called him after an  
Associated Press story last week described Wawa's plans to continue 
advertising cigarettes on billboards. He said he was interviewed by 
the television show on Wednesday and had planned a demonstration 
Thursday at a Wawa billboard in Manayunk. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to try to mark this occasion of the first major  
test of the tobacco settlement and try to establish clearly that 
this is not purely a matter of voluntary restraint, but something 
that violates the settlement,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 17:14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Targets Internet Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators have charged 18 people and  
eight companies with using the Internet to defraud investors, in a 
third nationwide ``sweep'' against online investment scams. 
</P>
<P>
	The Securities and Exchange Commission announced the action  
Wednesday, alleging that 14 separate schemes deceived investors 
around the world by selling bogus securities over the Internet. All 
told, the investors lost around $2.25 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegedly fraudulent investments included interests in gold  
mines, computer software, prefabricated hospitals in Turkey and a 
product described as a new way of processing gold. Eight of the 
cases involved the sale of so-called ``prime bank'' notes, what the 
SEC said were nonexistent securities promoted as being 
high-yielding, risk-free investments. 
</P>
<P>
	The market watchdog agency made the allegations in eight civil  
lawsuits and six administrative actions. All 14 cases involved 
people allegedly selling or marketing phony securities using the 
World Wide Web and making ``outrageous'' promises to investors, 
such as annual returns exceeding 100 percent or even 2000 percent 
of an initial investment. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC also charged several individuals with acting as  
unregistered brokers and selling unregistered securities. 
</P>
<P>
	In some of the cases, the agency said its 200-member Internet  
surveillance team discovered the questionable offerings before any 
securities were sold, preventing any potential investors from 
losing money. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is in many respects a pre-emptive strike,'' SEC  
Enforcement Director Richard Walker told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Nancy Smith, director of the SEC's Office of Investor Education  
and Assistance, said, ``People spend more time choosing a computer 
than they spend researching Internet investments. Investors can 
take their own pre-emptive strikes against Internet fraud simply by 
checking out investments before they buy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC was seeking civil fines and court orders against the  
investment promoters and companies, compelling them to refrain from 
the allegedly fraudulent activity. In two of the cases, federal 
judges have granted temporary restraining orders against the 
promoters and companies. One of the cases was settled, with the 
person charged neither admitting nor denying wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	The actions were seemingly mild, but the regulators' options are  
limited. They do not have legal authority to shut down investment 
promoters' Web sites, for example. 
</P>
<P>
	The civil enforcement actions were brought by SEC's headquarters  
in Washington and by its offices in Atlanta; Boston; Denver; Fort 
Worth, Texas; New York; Philadelphia and San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	The actions were the latest moves in a nationwide crackdown  
against investment fraud in cyberspace started by the SEC last 
October. In ``sweeps'' in October and February, the agency targeted 
people promoting legitimate stocks over the Internet who don't 
disclose they are paid to do so by the companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Such stock promotions are known as ``touting.'' Stock touting is  
not illegal in and of itself, but any compensation received from 
the companies must be fully disclosed, including the nature and 
amount of payment in cash or stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker said Wednesday that as a result of the SEC's previous  
action, disclosure by Internet touters has been ``substantially 
enhanced'' but is still not ``perfect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., chairman of a Senate Appropriations  
subcommittee, recently proposed increasing the SEC's budget, now at 
$337.4 million, by $5.5 million next year to fight investment fraud 
over the Internet. That would bring the agency's funding to the 
level requested by the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cops won't catch every crook in cyberspace, so investors  
need to watch out for themselves,'' said Peter Hildreth, president 
of the North American Securities Administrators Association, which 
represents state securities regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	``Regulators will not allow con artists and charlatans to hijack  
... (the Internet) and turn it into the electronic equivalent of a 
restroom wall,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: The SEC advises investors to read its guide  
titled ``Internet Fraud: How to Avoid Internet Investment Scams'' 
before buying any investment promoted on the Internet. The 
publication is available on the investor assistance and complaints 
link of the agency's Web site at www.sec.gov. It also is available 
by calling 1-800-SEC-0330. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors also are urged to report suspicious investment  
offerings to Enforcement(at)sec.gov or to use the Enforcement 
Complaint Center at www.sec.gov/enforce/comctr.htm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
