<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Negotiators Agree on Kosovo Funds  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional negotiators agreed today to  
provide $11.6 billion for the air assault on Yugoslavia and to 
boost overall defense spending, nearly doubling the amount 
President Clinton requested. But disputes over lawmakers' demands 
for favored items were holding up the bill. The biggest chunk of 
the bill -- and the item with the strongest political appeal -- was 
the money for U.S. participation in NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia. 
Clinton sought $6 billion, but negotiators added $5.6 billion for a 
troop pay raise, equipment maintenance, refugee assistance and 
weapons purchases. 

</P>
<P>
	US Remains Firm on China, WTO Entry  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Clinton administration will remain firm  
on requirements for China's entry to the World Trade Organization 
while seeking to ease tensions caused by the accidental bombing of 
the Chinese embassy in Yugoslavia, Commerce Secretary William Daley 
said today. The bombing has complicated negotiations, but there are 
no plans to back off concessions won during negotiations before 
Premier Zhu Rongji's visit to Washington last month or demands that 
China further open its markets. NATO officials blamed the bombing 
mistake on outdated maps. 

</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary To Resign  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, who helped  
spur the national economy into an unprecedented expansion, 
announced his resignation today. President Clinton said he would 
nominate Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, a former 
Harvard professor, as his third Treasury secretary. Rubin told 
reporters after the announcement that he has not made any decision 
on what position he will take after leaving the administration. 

</P>
<P>
	Gun-Show Restrictions Rejected  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Republican-controlled Senate rejected  
restrictions on sales at gun shows today in Congress' first vote on 
gun control since last month's shooting spree in a Colorado high 
school. Instead, on a vote of 53-45, the Senate supported voluntary 
background checks on private sales at gun shows. The developments 
marked a defeat for gun control advocates, who had claimed the 
shooting at Columbine High School would give their cause momentum. 
Instead, their plan was killed 51-47. 

</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian Associate Investigated  
</P>
<P>
	RIO RANCHO, N.M. (AP) -- An associate of Dr. Jack Kevorkian is  
under investigation in the death of a 54-year-old woman who had 
multiple sclerosis. Police said today that evidence relating to the 
woman's death has been recovered from Dr. Georges Reding's home 
near Galesburg, Mich. Reding was arrested last year with Kevorkian 
when the pair dropped off a body at a suburban Detroit hospital. 
Reding was found innocent of charges he interfered with police and 
resisted arrest. 

</P>
<P>
	Berlin Airlift Anniversary Marked  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Allied air power overcame the Soviet blockade of  
West Berlin 50 years ago and will carry NATO through to victory in 
its fight over Kosovo, the British defense minister said today. At 
a ceremony marking the anniversary, George Robertson said the 
airlift to ``save a free Berlin'' showed ``that our armed forces 
can and should be a real force for good in the world. That is our 
clear and unmistakable message'' in the current campaign in Kosovo, 
he said. Later, he said that NATO's air campaign alone would force 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to accept the alliance's 
conditions to end the conflict. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Mixed  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks were mixed Thursday amid concern over  
Russia's political situation. The Nikkei gained 9.59 points to 
16,956.95 in early trading. In New York on Wednesday, the Dow Jones 
industrial average closed down 25.78 at 11,000.37. 

</P>
<P>
	Knicks Crush Heat 97-73  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Knicks unleashed one of the most  
dominant flurries imaginable tonight, using an incredible 32-2 run 
to take control of the game -- and their first-round series -- in 
defeating the Miami Heat 97-73. The victory gave the Knicks a 2-1 
lead in the best-of-5 series and left Miami on the brink of 
first-round elimination at New York's hands for the second-straight 
season. A multi-pronged offense boosted the Knicks as Latrell 
Sprewell scored 20 off the bench, Allan Houston had 18, Patrick 
Ewing 15 and Marcus Camby 13. 

</P>
<P>
	Sabres 3, Bruins 2  
</P>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Dixon Ward scored the winning goal midway  
through the third period and Dominik Hasek blanked Boston for the 
final 51 minutes as the Buffalo Sabres skated to a 3-2 playoff win 
over the Bruins tonight. Rhett Warrener knocked in his own rebound 
to tie the game at 6:44 of the third period. Ward connected 2:54 
later as the Sabres took a 2-1 lead in the best-of-7 Eastern 
Conference semifinal series. Vaclav Varada passed from the side of 
the net to Ward in the slot and he scored from short range. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
</P>
