<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Gear Up for Summer Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Temperatures won't be the only thing rising  
this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans will travel in record numbers this year, despite an  
increase in gas, airline and car rental prices, according to an 
industry survey. 
</P>
<P>
	Vacationers plan to take 271 million trips this summer, a 4  
percent increase from last year, the Travel Industry Association of 
America said Tuesday in its annual forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, we have the perfect recipe for a healthy summer  
travel season -- low inflation, rock-bottom unemployment and high 
consumer confidence,'' said Suzanne Cook, the group's senior vice 
president for research. ``Throw in a surging stock market and you 
have the makings for a robust summer travel season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to a survey the group conducted in April with AAA,  
American travelers intend to take more time off this year but spend 
less money doing it. They also plan to take just as many trips, if 
not more, than they did last year. A ``trip'' is considered any 
journey at least 100 miles from home. 
</P>
<P>
	The hot spots for vacationers remain the same. Most people -- 76  
percent -- plan to head to the beach or lake. Sixty-eight percent 
will visit a city and 45 percent a historic site and 42 percent 
have camping plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The travel industry group said more Americans are going to  
family reunions and casinos, while fewer plan to go fishing or 
attend cultural events. 
</P>
<P>
	Most people plan to reach their summer getaway by car.  
</P>
<P>
	Eighty-four percent of those surveyed said they plan to use an  
automobile to get places, despite rising gasoline prices. The 
current national average for regular unleaded fuel, $1.16 per 
gallon, is up 6 cents from last May and prices should continue to 
rise, but that probably won't change any minds, said Jack Mannix, 
an AAA spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we've seen historically is, Americans feel a sense of  
entitlement to a vacation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once in a while, what we do see is, if there is a price  
increase and people do want to economize because of that, they may 
go a little less distance, they may stay a little shorter period of 
time, but we don't anticipate a big impact from that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rising jet fuel prices also are likely to lead to higher air  
fares, but 13 percent of Americans still plan to travel by air this 
summer. That's a 3 percent increase over last year. 
</P>
<P>
	On average, those surveyed expect to spend $956 and 8.5 nights  
on their longest trip, down from the $972 and eight nights they 
spent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida continues to be Americans' top vacation spot, followed  
by California, Hawaii, Colorado and Texas. New York, Nevada, 
Arizona, Washington state and the District of Columbia were the 
other top 10 destination states. 
</P>
<P>
	The summer vacation season will be jump-started by Memorial Day  
weekend. AAA and the industry group expect a record 33.3 million 
Americans to travel during that holiday, a 4 percent increase over 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Travel Industry Association of America represents more than  
2,000 travel-related organizations, including tourism offices, 
visitor bureaus, hotels, airlines and cruise companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
