<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DeBartolo York Wants Suit Dismissal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Denise DeBartolo York has asked a federal  
judge in Ohio to dismiss a lawsuit her brother filed against her 
for breach of contract. 
</P>
<P>
	York and the family-held Edward J. DeBartolo Corp. sued Edward  
DeBartolo Jr. in April, demanding he repay $94 million to the 
company. It also sought to oust DeBartolo from any management role 
with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	The siblings each own a 50 percent stake in the family business,  
a Youngstown, Ohio-based real estate development firm that is also 
the nominal owner of the 49ers. 
</P>
<P>
	DeBartolo responded a week later with a $150 million lawsuit  
alleging that York reneged on a deal to turn the team over to him 
as part of an August 1998 agreement. That deal would have divided 
the assets of their jointly owned business, with DeBartolo gaining 
sole possession of the team in return for $350 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In her request for dismissal filed Wednesday, York said certain  
conditions of their deal were not met, rendering it null and void. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``spin-off'' deal would have given DeBartolo control of the  
49ers and York control over the remaining assets of the 
corporation. The conditions included the Internal Revenue Service 
declaring the transaction tax-free for both DeBartolo and the 
corporation and the NFL approving DeBartolo's ownership of the 
49ers. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS said it couldn't rule because the NFL suspended  
DeBartolo from managing the 49ers, and the NFL said it doesn't give 
preapproval to anyone, York spokesman Sam Singer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``She had no control over the IRS not issuing a ruling, she had  
no control over the NFL not giving preapproval, so she didn't 
breach her contract with Eddie,'' Singer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
