<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Close Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose Wednesday on an overnight rise  
on Wall Street and investment in companies that have recently made 
bullish announcements. The U.S. dollar was lower against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average climbed 204.18  
points, or 1.22 percent, to finish the day at 16,947.36. On 
Tuesday, the average closed down 233.83 points, or 1.38 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.86 yen, down 0.02 yen from late Tuesday in  
Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 120.97 yen 
overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices bounced back, following  
Tuesday's gains in New York, where the Dow Jones industrial average 
jumped 18.90 to 11,026.15, just shy of its record high close of 
11,031.59 on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in a number of technology companies, including Sony,  
Softbank and long-distance telephone carrier DDI, posted strong 
gains following a rise in their counterparts in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was supported by remarks from Okiharu Yasuoka, a  
member of the ruling Liberal Democrats, suggesting that the party 
would consider an extra budget. 
</P>
<P>
	But the government's continued vagueness on additional economic  
stimulus measures kept many investors on the sidelines and directed 
buyers toward companies that have been the focus of upbeat news. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Nintendo Co. and Matsushita Electric Industries Ltd.  
rose sharply on reports they will tie up to develop advanced game 
consoles. 
</P>
<P>
	Takeda Chemical Industries shares jumped after it said it would  
market a new drug to treat AIDS, and Taisho Pharmaceuticals posted 
hefty gains on news it will sell a U.S.-developed hair-growth 
stimulant in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei average moved as high as 17,104.49 during the  
morning, but profit-taking by domestic investors in the afternoon 
knocked the market off its early highs. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 5.33 points, or 0.39 percent, to 1,361.15. The 
TOPIX closed down 18.04 points, or 1.31 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 648.77 million shares, down from 727.60 million shares 
Tuesday. Advancing issues outnumbered retreaters 740 to 478, while 
105 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar slipped as selling of the  
greenback by Japanese exporters offset buying by Japanese 
institutional investors amid an absence of market-moving news. 
</P>
<P>
	``The dollar/yen rate has mostly been determined by Japanese  
investors and exporters recently,'' said Hirokazu Note, assistant 
general manager of foreign exchange at Sumitomo Bank. ``But they 
mostly balance each other out, leaving the dollar range-bound 
between 119.50 yen and 121.50 yen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yasuoka's comments on plans for an extra budget failed to boost  
the yen as traders awaited more concrete proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 120.60 yen and 121.10 yen in  
Wednesday's trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro remained under pressure due to continued unrest in  
Kosovo. It was quoted at 129.15 yen in morning trading, down from 
130.90 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.340 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.355 percent, 
driving its price up to 101.42 yen from 101.28 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
