<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Opposes Concealed Weapons Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole believes she's found her  
silver-bullet issue in the Republican presidential campaign: guns. 
</P>
<P>
	The former American Red Cross president is using a string of  
moderate positions on gun control to distinguish herself from 
front-runner George W. Bush and the rest of the GOP field. 
</P>
<P>
	She told a women's group Tuesday night that she doesn't think  
Americans should be allowed to carry concealed weapons and that she 
backs a mandatory requirement to sell child safety locks with guns. 
</P>
<P>
	On both issues, she disagrees with the 10 other GOP hopefuls.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think police work is hard enough already,'' she said. ``No  
one should make it harder. I think it's wrong to let people carry 
concealed weapons.'' Mrs. Dole said the issue should be left for 
states to decide. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the remarks moved Mrs. Dole squarely in the political  
middle on the contentious gun-control issue, leaving GOP 
consultants debating whether conservative primary voters will 
accept the stance. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is odd. It's certainly attention-getting for the national  
media,'' Republican consultant Michael Hudome said. ``But it 
probably won't work in a Republican primary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Scott Reed, who managed the 1996 presidential campaign  
of Mrs. Dole's husband, Bob Dole, called it a wise strategy. ``She 
is differentiating herself from the front-runner and attracting a 
coalition back to the GOP -- a coalition made up of women and 
mothers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three weeks after the Colorado high school shooting, Republican  
presidential candidates are staking out territory on guns and 
school violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than Bush and Mrs. Dole, no GOP candidate supports further  
legislation to restrict access to guns. Typical of the rest of the 
field is Gary Bauer, the conservative activist who says the 
shootings are the result of deeper social problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush and Mrs. Dole already have said they support the federal  
bans on assault weapons and armor-piercing bullets. Mrs. Dole 
unveiled those stances in a New Hampshire gathering of presidential 
hopefuls, drawing a cool reception from activists. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, as Texas governor, signed into law a measure allowing  
state residents to get a license to carry a concealed weapon; it 
requires training and a background check. 
</P>
<P>
	``Governor Bush has a record of doing in office what he says he  
will do on the campaign trail,'' spokeswoman Karen Hughes said, a 
subtle reference to the fact that Mrs. Dole has never held elective 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know many women and men in Texas who have gone through the  
training and who have a license and who feel safer because of that 
legislation -- particularly women who travel or work late at 
night,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole's campaign believes there is growing support for her  
position on guns -- even among GOP voters -- and they are betting 
that she will get credit for taking a tough stand even if their 
polls are wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the right thing to do, and I won't shy away from the  
tough issues, even if some in my party don't like it,'' Mrs. Dole 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
