<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Students Differ on Gun-Control Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Florida high school students Melissa Coronado  
and Denise Kolb have their differences over gun laws. Kolb, 18, 
wants to see Congress pass stricter laws to keep guns out of the 
hands of teens. Coronado, 16, wants police and courts to be harder 
on the kids who break existing laws. 
</P>
<P>
	They both think teen violence was a problem long before the  
April 20 Columbine High School massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sad that it took an incredible tragedy like this to raise  
concerns,'' said Kolb, a senior at South Dade Senior High School in 
Homestead, Fla., speaking after a discussion of gun laws Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 120 students from high schools nationwide attended the  
meeting as part of a yearly civic education program held in 
Washington by the Close Up Foundation, a nonprofit group. The talk 
was one of few national, public forums for young people to address 
gun laws. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, they heard from Robert Walker, president of Handgun  
Control Inc., and Glen Caroline, director of the grassroots 
division of the National Rifle Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker told the students that new laws are needed to close what  
he called loopholes allowing underage teens and criminals to buy 
handguns and illegal weapons from unlicensed dealers at gun shows. 
Only licensed dealers do background and identification checks, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to treat guns like cars,'' Walker said.  
</P>
<P>
	Caroline countered by saying there are more than 20,000 federal,  
state and city gun laws that are woefully under-enforced. Congress 
should concentrate on giving more funds to law enforcement agencies 
and gun-safety education programs, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NRA, a gun industry lobbying group, has been criticized for  
holding a convention in Denver a week after the shooting in nearby 
Littleton. Two students, whose weapons included two illegal 
sawed-off shotguns, killed 12 classmates and a teacher before 
committing suicide. Investigators believe at least some of those 
weapons were purchased at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gun shows are a horrendous idea,'' said Kolb. ``There's no way  
you should be able to sell and buy guns at free will at a table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Megan Dreisbach, a 17-year-old sophomore from Kingwood Regional  
High School in Wolfesboro, N.H., said, ``My dad hunts. ... But an 
incident like Littleton makes you wonder what happens when you 
allow guns into the hands of people our age.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Cummings, a 17-year-old junior who attends Katahdin High  
School in Sherman Station, Maine, believes gun ownership is a right 
that shouldn't be compromised. 
</P>
<P>
	``I grew up in a rural area,'' he said. ``Hunting is like a big  
deal. You have to look at the problem for what it is and not blame 
guns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coronado, a junior at South Dade, also doesn't believe more laws  
are the answer: 
</P>
<P>
	``I know that I can't buy a gun, but if some kids really want  
guns there's nothing stopping them. It's just like drugs.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
