<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants' Strahan Wants New Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Now that the New York Giants have  
given linebacker Jessie Armstead his due, two-time Pro Bowl 
defensive end Michael Strahan wants his. 
</P>
<P>
	Strahan, whose contract expires at the end of the 1999 season,  
said Wednesday that he would like to have a new contract in place 
before the Giants start training camp in late July. 
</P>
<P>
	While Strahan would not say how much money he wants, it's likely  
he would want to be among the NFL's highest-paid defensive ends. 
That would earn him between $6 million and $7 million annually. 
</P>
<P>
	``Football is a business and I am not making any demands,''  
Strahan said. ``I'm not saying I'm not going to do this and that 
and I'm not coming to minicamp. I'll be here in good faith. 
</P>
<P>
	``But at the same time, when it comes to the contract, fair is  
fair,'' he added. ``Let's get it done and make it fair to both 
sides, that's all I want.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armstead, who like Strahan earned his second straight Pro Bowl  
selection last season, was given a seven-year, $33 million contract 
that included a $6 million signing bonus earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've already heard all the jokes, we could do this if Strahan  
didn't want all the money,'' Strahan quipped. ``Strahan hasn't 
asked for one penny yet so no one knows what I want. Pretty soon, 
everyone will find out, and I don't want to hear you guys saying, 
`You want that much.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Giants general manager Ernie Accorsi said he has spoken with  
Tony Agnone, Strahan's agent, but they have not started serious 
negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Strahan had a career-high 15 sacks last season, one more than in  
1997 when the Giants won the NFC East. He also had 67 tackles, two 
forced fumbles and an interception that he returned for a touchdown 
last season, his sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Giants can't reach a contract agreement with Strahan,  
they would probably make him a franchise player, meaning they could 
match any offer he received in free agency. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to be here, I want to stay here,'' Strahan said.  
``We're going to see what happens. I'm not saying I want to go 
anywhere or be traded. I just want to win games. I think we can win 
games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strahan has been miffed at some teammates of late for failing to  
attend the team's off-season workout programs after the Giants 
posted an 8-8 record last season and missed the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody needs to do what it takes to win,'' he said. ``You  
don't win by showing up in July at training camp and saying `I'm 
here, I'm ready.''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
