<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Congress Agrees on $11.6B for Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional negotiators agreed today to  
provide $11.6 billion for the attacks on Yugoslavia and to boost 
overall defense spending, nearly doubling the amount President 
Clinton requested. But disputes over items including fishing in 
Alaska's Glacier Bay and taxpayer assistance for some U.S. steel 
companies were hindering completion of the package, which leaders 
want to send to Clinton by week's end. The biggest chunk of the 
bill was for U.S. participation in the NATO bombing. Though 
lawmakers are divided over the attacks, many opponents are 
reluctant to oppose funds for troops in the field. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Reports Busiest Day of Attacks  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO struck bridges, airfields, and  
destroyed MiG fighters on the ground in its busiest day of attacks 
against Yugoslavia, the allies said today. NATO reported a record 
327 sorties that resulted in airstrikes against Yugoslavia 
yesterday and early today -- the greatest number since the campaign 
began March 24. Both sides reported particularly heavy NATO 
bombardments in Kosovo. Meanwhile, President Slobodan Milosevic for 
the first time acknowledged military casualties, saying ``many'' 
had died. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Rejects Gun-Show Restrictions  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Republican-controlled Senate supported a  
system of voluntary background checks at guns shows today after 
rejecting a measure that would require instant checks for such 
private sales. Gun control advocates had claimed that last month's 
shooting spree at a Colorado high school would give their cause 
fresh momentum. Instead, their plan was killed on a 51-47 vote. 
Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, who is a member of the National Rifle 
Association board, said that his voluntary plan contained 
incentives to entice private collectors to conduct checks, 
including limited protection from liability. 

</P>
<P>
	Rubin Resigning From Treasury Post  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin will step down  
from his post in July with the national economy in an unprecedented 
expansion and the global economy on the mend. President Clinton 
announced today that he would nominate Deputy Treasury Secretary 
Lawrence Summers, a former Harvard professor, as his third Treasury 
secretary. The stock market tumbled at the first reports of Rubin's 
departure, but quickly turned around. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin Fires Primakov  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia was plunged into political crisis today  
when President Boris Yeltsin dismissed the prime minister and 
Cabinet in an apparent pre-emptive strike on a parliament seeking 
to impeach him. The sacking of Yevgeny Primakov was the third time 
in just over a year that Yeltsin has ousted a premier. Yeltsin 
named Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin as acting prime minister. 
Stepashin, 47, previously commanded tens of thousands of troops and 
police. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Accuser Passed Lie Detector  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A second FBI test found Kathleen Willey was  
truthful when she alleged that President Clinton made a sexual 
advance, according to newly released documents. A federal judge 
unsealed the results this week after news organizations, including 
The Associated Press, challenged the secrecy surrounding them. The 
polygraph questions did not address the issue of whether Clinton's 
alleged advance was unwanted. Mrs. Willey says she rebuffed 
Clinton, who denies making any sexual advance. 

</P>
<P>
	Brain Shocks Trigger Depression  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Electrical stimulation of the brain can trigger  
bouts of deep depression that come and go almost instantly. French 
doctors made the discovery while treating a woman with Parkinson's 
disease. They implanted electrodes in her brain to stimulate the 
parts that malfunction in her disease but found that turning on one 
electrode made her profoundly sad. The depression disappeared after 
the stimulation ended. Researchers say the discovery raises the 
possibility that brain stimulation could aid in treating 
depression, addiction and aggression. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes Down 25.78  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices ended mixed today as blue chips  
recovered most of a sharp drop following Treasury Secretary Robert 
Rubin's resignation, and the broader market rose on strength in 
technology issues. The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 
25.78, at 11,000.37. Decliners outnumbered advancers 1,657-1,377 on 
the NYSE. The Nasdaq composite index rose 39.83 to 2,606.51. 

</P>
