<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Wire Rod Imports Vote Splits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) --The U.S. International Trade Commission reached  
a split decision Wednesday on whether steel wire rod imported from 
Japan and other countries is hurting U.S. producers. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the six commissioners found that steel wire rod is  
being imported into the United States in such increased quantities 
as to pose a serious threat to the domestic industry. The other 
three commissioners concluded just the opposite. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the ITC, the findings now will be forwarded to  
President Clinton, who can consider either determination as the 
commission's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission will hold a hearing on remedy on June 8 and will  
forward any recommendations to the president by mid-July. 
</P>
<P>
	Steel wire rod is used in fasteners, medical and dental  
instruments and other products. 
</P>
<P>
	United Steelworkers of America and a number of U.S. steel  
manufacturers filed the initial complaint against Japan and other 
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
