<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 06:05:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Considers China WTO Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- When Nora Yeung's foreign customers sought to  
eliminate her Hong Kong-based trading company as the middleman for 
purchasing gifts and stationery from mainland Chinese 
manufacturers, she started to worry. 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't take her clients long, however, to realize how much  
easier it was to buy their products through her company, Planet 
Earth Inc., instead of doing it on their own in China. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the end of the day, they all came back and didn't actually  
do business with those companies,'' Yeung said. ``It's the trust 
factor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The difficulties that confront foreign companies in China have  
helped many traders in Hong Kong make their fortunes, but the cash 
is not pouring in like it used to. Some worry the flow could ebb 
even more with China's anticipated entry to the World Trade 
Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	That may not happen anytime soon. NATO's bombing of the Chinese  
Embassy in Yugoslavia resulted in angry protests and has strained 
U.S.-Chinese relations. That could make it difficult for China's 
leaders to make new and unpopular market-opening pledges to gain 
entry to the WTO. 
</P>
<P>
	The day China does enter the organization, Hong Kong will  
certainly take some blows as some foreign companies bypass this 
expensive trading center and cut their deals in China on their own, 
analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	For China, WTO membership would give it the chance to boost  
exports, but would also pry open its markets to foreign 
competition. Hong Kong could see its traders lose some business to 
China, even though they also likely would benefit in the long run 
by having a much bigger market to pursue on the mainland. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the short-term losers could be Hong Kong's crucial import  
and export trade, which employs 14 percent of the work force. The 
bulk of that business is re-exports, in which goods are imported 
and then re-exported to other countries, sometimes with 
improvements made here such as packaging. 
</P>
<P>
	Re-export trade with China accounts for 94 percent of the $148  
billion in goods that pass through Hong Kong each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Stationery dealer Yeung, for example, imports products from  
China and sends them directly to Hong Kong's ports, which offer 
more flexible schedules and often cheaper rates to the United 
States than Chinese ports. 
</P>
<P>
	The value of Chinese goods re-exported through Hong Kong, which  
has already been falling -- down 12.4 percent in March compared with 
March 1998 -- could slip even more. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say the territory of 6.8 million people is more likely  
to benefit from the trickle-down effect of an overall increase in 
business between China and foreign partners. 
</P>
<P>
	China's external trade could double to $600 billion within 5  
years of joining WTO, estimates Fred Hu, an economist who follows 
China for investment bank Goldman Sachs Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Hong Kong gets a slice of that,'' he said, ``Hong Kong will  
stand to gain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until the WTO talks wrap up, estimates for Hong Kong's potential  
gains are hard to make, analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite some shifts to China, many companies maintain Hong Kong  
as a base where they can also get top quality financial and legal 
services, said Bill Galvin, Hong Kong-based director of Kurt Salmon 
Associates Inc., which advises consumer firms. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the WTO agreement secures greater access to China's  
financial sector, Hong Kong banks won't lose clients to Chinese 
banks, said Robin Hammond, regional banking analyst for Paribas 
Asia Equity Ltd. Instead, Hammond predicts the local banks will 
instead find more opportunities in China. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a long process to get the Chinese banks up to Western  
standards,'' Hammond said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, as Chinese companies become more savvy, some old Hong  
Kong trading companies are expanding into consulting and other 
services to stay one step ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hong Kong is not just a middleman,'' asserted Edward Leung,  
chief economist for the Trade Development Council. ``Hong Kong 
provides a one-stop shop of supporting services and will not be 
easily replaced by any city in China.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And until Chinese companies can prove they're up to par, foreign  
companies will still need Hong Kong, experts say. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of foreigners are still reluctant to go into China,''  
Yeung said. ``They might visit a factory once, but they'd rather 
pay you to do it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
