<DOCNO> APW19990512.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 11:25:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Seeks To Limit Y2K Lawsuits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House neared a vote Wednesday on a bill to  
limit millennium-bug lawsuits -- a measure that businesses say is 
needed to avoid a year-2000 financial catastrophe. The White House 
sees it as slanted against consumers and deserving of a 
presidential veto. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would try to stem a potential flood of lawsuits  
arising from computer breakdowns by establishing a 90-day waiting 
period before lawsuits can be filed, encouraging mediation, capping 
punitive damage and limiting class action lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reality today is that unbridled Y2K litigation is  
jeopardizing coordination and teamwork'' to fix computer problems, 
said Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., one of the chief sponsors of the 
bill. ``This adversarial mentality hampers private sector efforts 
to solve Y2K problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill has the strong backing of business groups and the high  
tech industry, who warn that the problem arising from computers 
that misread the 2000 date could result in hundreds of billions of 
dollars in lawsuits, crippling the economy and undermining efforts 
to fix faulty computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Litigation could arise from computer glitches if businesses find  
they can't process credit cards and customer information records or 
lose money because of supply or power disruptions. Consumers might 
sue if there are problems in medical equipment or their access to 
prescription drugs. Backers of the legislation say they are only 
trying to stop frivolous, not legitimate claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Jasinowski, president of the National Association of  
Manufacturers, says the litigation bill has become a key vote by 
which the group will rate lawmakers' support for American 
businesses. ``It would be an entirely avoidable catastrophe if 
Congress didn't pass this bill and ended up swamping the economy in 
a tidal wave of litigation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the White House says President Clinton's senior advisors  
would advise him to veto the House bill in its present form because 
it goes too far in limiting the legal rights of those with 
legitimate complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, it said, ``may, in fact, decrease the incentives  
organizations have to assist customers and business partners to be 
ready for the transition to the next century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But two senior White House officials, presidential aide Bruce  
Lindsey and National Economic Council Director Gene Sperling, also 
wrote a letter to House Speaker Dennis Hastert Tuesday stressing 
that they want to get a bill passed and outlining possible areas of 
compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration, they wrote, wants to see the bill limited to  
commercial claims, exempting consumers. But they showed some 
flexibility on the issue of ``proportionate ability.'' Supporters 
want defendants to be liable only for their share of any damage, 
reducing the tendency of plaintiffs to go after companies with deep 
pockets, but consumer groups argue that this would work to the 
disadvantage of lower income plaintiffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The administration has realized this is a train moving down  
the tracks,'' said Bruce Josten, executive vice president of the 
U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ``This will be one of the biggest 
accomplishments of the whole Congress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate is considering a bill that has been amended to meet  
some of the concerns of the administration. However, that bill was 
pulled from the Senate floor two weeks ago after the Republican 
leadership blocked a Democratic attempt to add extraneous issues, 
including a minimum wage hike, to the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, the current Senate bill, backed by Sens. John  
McCain, R-Ariz., Ron Wyden, D-Ore., and Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., 
would exempt consumers and small businesses from punitive damage 
caps. It also does not have House language that gives defendants a 
``reasonable effort'' defense and limits the liability of corporate 
directors and officers to $100,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House supports a House Democratic version that also  
has a 90-day cooling off period and limits plaintiffs from 
asserting claims for economic damages that are not covered by 
contract. But it takes out the ``reasonable efforts'' defense, the 
punitive damage caps and officer caps. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to do something, but we don't need to take steps that  
will dismantle key protections for consumers and small 
businesses,'' Democratic leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri said. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 775.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 17:14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Only Judge Can Allow Penguins' Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- If the Pittsburgh Penguins are to become the  
Portland Penguins, the road to Oregon must first pass through a 
U.S. bankruptcy judge's office, not that of NHL commissioner Gary 
Bettman. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the hardened stance taken recently by the NHL, one  
designed to accelerate the Penguins' bankruptcy proceedings, 
Bettman concedes the league can't move them unless Judge Bernard 
Markovitz's allows it. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, league officials suggested the NHL could disband or  
relocate the team if the 1999-2000 season was approaching and the 
Penguins' case was not resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Lemieux group is moving at an appropriate rate of speed,''  
said Bettman, who is attending the Maple Leafs-Penguins playoff 
series. ``These are complicated issues, and the bankruptcy judge is 
doing what he believes is in the best interests of the bankruptcy 
proceedings. I learned long ago never to disagree with a judge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Especially one who controls the fate of one of only two NHL  
franchises that competes in a major U.S. market -- St. Louis is the 
other -- without winter competition from an NBA franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven months ago, shortly after the Penguins filed for Chapter  
11 protection, the NHL agreed to a court order that it would not 
seek to vacate the franchise while the Penguins were in bankruptcy. 
Markovitz also has ruled that the Penguins' arena lease, which runs 
through 2007, is binding. 
</P>
<P>
	Markovitz on Tuesday rejected the NHL's request to move up the  
creditors' vote on Lemieux's bid from June 24. But he did agree to 
hear the league's request that its own plan move forward at the 
same pace as Lemieux's. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL plan, which Bettman said is strictly a backup in case  
Lemieux's bid falters, calls for the Penguins to be sold for $85 
million to an out-of-town owner -- presumably, Seattle Seahawks 
owner Paul Allen, the Microsoft co-founder -- in time to relocate 
for next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would like to have the Penguins reorganize in Pittsburgh,  
but if that doesn't work, we have to look at the alternatives: Is 
there a buyer who is prepared to take the franchise on very short 
notice for next season?'' Bettman said. ``Taking a club at the end 
of June, to start selling tickets and get up and running for the 
start of next season would be no picnic for anyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Allen, who also owns the NBA's Portland Trail Blazers, said he  
has not made a specific bid for the Penguins. But he did not deny 
being interested in putting an NHL franchise into the nearly new 
Rose Garden arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Another bankruptcy judge, M. Bruce McCullough, said the NHL is  
working on three schedules for next season: one with the Penguins 
in Pittsburgh, another with them on the West Coast, presumably 
Portland, and a third without them. 
</P>
<P>
	If nothing else, the news that a deep-pockets owner is willing  
to relocate the Penguins immediately caused a rumble Wednesday not 
only in Pittsburgh, but in the state capital of Harrisburg. 
</P>
<P>
	With much of the Penguins' financial mess blamed on an  
unfavorable arena lease that management firm SMG has refused to 
renegotiate, City Council president Bob O'Connor again raised the 
possibility of using eminent domain to reclaim the arena. City 
Council decided Tuesday to delay exploring any such action for now. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Connor said he met briefly with Bettman at Tuesday's playoff  
game to discuss the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best thing is to keep the team here,'' O'Connor said.  
``There is a history and tradition here that can't be duplicated 
elsewhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Harrisburg, Gov. Tom Ridge, who shepherded the funding  
package for four new stadiums in Pittsburgh and Philadelphia 
through the Legislature three months ago, said he is amenable to 
discussing a new arena once new local Penguins ownership is in 
place. 
</P>
<P>
	Privately, city and state government officials believe a new  
arena to replace the 38-year-old Civic Arena would be an easier 
sell to taxpayers than the stadiums, because it would be used 
year-around for concerts, circuses and meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had one conversation with ... Gary Bettman, and I told  
him that after the legal matters have been resolved that I 
anticipate, given the age of the (Civic Arena), that they will be 
looking for some public assistance, and we would be open to that 
discussion,'' Ridge said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Kevin Constantine said the Penguins' history of attracting  
big crowds and fielding competitive teams should not be overlooked. 
The Penguins have played to about 90 percent of arena capacity 
while reaching the Stanley Cup playoffs each year since 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's so much fun in this town because of hockey, it would  
be a shame to not have it in Pittsburgh,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 18:43:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies Send Thomson To Minors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Eight days after shipping one of their two best  
young pitchers to Triple-A, the Colorado Rockies demoted the other, 
fueling speculation that the club is looking to trade for an 
established starter. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamey Wright was optioned to Colorado Springs on May 4. John  
Thomson followed suit today. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Jim Leyland insisted that neither demotion should be  
viewed as punishment. Instead, it is an opportunity for both to 
sort out some problems with their mechanics, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking Thomson's place on the major league roster will be  
outfielder Derrick Gibson, not another pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked who would move up in the rotation to replace Thomson,  
Leyland said, ``Nobody. We don't need anybody for a while. I'll 
need a fifth starter next Tuesday. I'll announce that at a later 
date.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if the fifth starter would come from the current Rockies  
staff, Leyland said, ``No, it will not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if the fifth starter would come from Colorado Springs or  
via trade, he said, ``I'm not discussing that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Immediate speculation centered on Arizona's Andy Benes, Kansas  
City's Kevin Appier, Minnesota's Brad Radke and Oakland's Kenny 
Rogers. All are either in the final year of contracts or are 
looking to be unloaded by teams seeking to reduce payroll. 
</P>
<P>
	Left-hander Bobby Jones came out of the Rockies' bullpen to take  
over Wright's starting job, but there are no other starting 
candidates on the staff and few prospects are ready for big-league 
duty at Colorado Springs. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomson allowed six runs and eight hits in 2 2-3 innings as the  
Rockies lost to the New York Mets 10-5 Wednesday. His record fell 
to 0-5 and his ERA ballooned to 11.84. 
</P>
<P>
	Leyland said his conversation with Thomson was ``almost a  
duplicate of what we talked to Jamey about. He's got to get a feel 
for pitching, he's got to tighten up his slider, and he's got to 
get a better changeup. Right now, everything is hard and he can't 
get hitters off his hard stuff. When you can't get big-league 
hitters off of something hard, you're going to get roughed up. It's 
that simple.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leyland emphasized that both Thomson and Wright have bright  
futures with the organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not punishment,'' he said after the Thomson move. ``We  
like him a lot. He's a big league pitcher in the future. At this 
particular time, he's not a big league pitcher. To be honest with 
you, it's not fair to John Thomson to put him out there right now. 
The poor guy is 0-5 and his earned-run average is very high, 
obviously. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him the same thing I told Jamey. If Jamey Wright and  
John Thomson don't in the not-too-distant future come through for 
us, we're going to be hurting unless we go out and get somebody, 
because we don't have a lot of depth. So we're counting on them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomson, 25, started 27 games for the Rockies in 1997 and 26 in  
1998, going 7-9 with a 4.71 ERA in '97 and 8-11 with a 4.81 ERA 
last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kind of knew it was coming if I didn't turn it around,''  
Thomson said. ``I agree with everything he said. I wouldn't send 
myself out there the way I've been throwing. I've been terrible. If 
I knew what was wrong, I would fix it. I would have fixed it 
yesterday or two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't say I'm not upset about it, because you work so hard  
to get here. But it's what's right for the team right now. It's not 
fair to put the team in the hole 6-0.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
