<DOCNO> APW19990512.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 16:16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Soccer Stadium in Football Country </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- The nation's first stadium built  
specifically for major professional soccer opens Saturday in a city 
known more for Woody Hayes and his ``three yards and a cloud of 
dust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A capacity crowd of 22,500 will watch the Columbus Crew play the  
New England Revolution in the state-of-the-art stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Some seats are as close as 8 feet from the field. Fans can get a  
close-up of the action on a mammoth video screen. The tilted banks 
of lights at each corner and the open-air loges -- with bars and TVs 
-- give the stadium a European feel. 
</P>
<P>
	All this in a city of about 700,000 people who usually build  
their social calendars around Ohio State football each fall. 
</P>
<P>
	For the moment, Columbus' pro sports market belongs exclusively  
to Major League Soccer. An NHL expansion franchise, the Blue 
Jackets, won't begin playing until 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The soccer team, with its stark logo of construction workers,  
has gained a foothold in this white-collar market. The new stadium 
has features that should expand the fan base beyond those who 
revere Hayes, the late coach of the Buckeyes from 1951-78. 
</P>
<P>
	Tailgating will be encouraged at a huge party patio, where bands  
will play before and after games. Tents will hold catered parties 
for corporations and fans. Inside the stadium, an entertainment 
area features sports-related video games. 
</P>
<P>
	There also will be beer. That couldn't be sold at the team's  
previous home, Ohio Stadium, which is on the campus. 
</P>
<P>
	``While I don't believe because we serve beer someone will come  
out to the new stadium, I do believe that if we didn't serve beer, 
some people might not come,'' Crew president and general manager 
Jamey Rootes said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Crew had to move out of cavernous Ohio Stadium -- where an  
average of 93,000 fans pay $34 a seat to watch football games -- 
when the university began renovating the 77-year-old structure. 
</P>
<P>
	In its first three seasons there, the Crew averaged 12,200 a  
game. Even with dividers to cluster fans into tighter formations, 
the crowds looked and sounded small. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a little bit tough connecting with the fans at Ohio  
Stadium,'' midfielder Brian Maisonneuve said. ``The best thing 
about this stadium is that the fans will be right on top of us, and 
the crowd noise will be that much louder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the new facility's $25 million pricetag was picked up by  
Crew owner Lamar Hunt and his partners after voters repeatedly 
refused to finance a soccer stadium downtown and in the suburbs. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunt, also the owner of the NFL's Chiefs and the MLS' Wizards,  
said the site at the state fairgrounds was ideal. There was no need 
to build parking lots, access roads or freeway ramps. 
</P>
<P>
	``They all existed for the fairgrounds that have been at that  
location for over 100 years,'' Hunt said. ``We have a location 
that's on an interstate freeway with 148,000 cars per day going 
by.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Painted the Crew's yellow, black and silver colors, the stadium  
adds an air of permanence to the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans have responded. Season-ticket sales are up 60 percent to a  
total of 8,500 and Saturday's game has been sold out for weeks. The 
average ticket price is $14. 
</P>
<P>
	The team says sponsorship revenues, approaching $1 million, have  
topped last season's total. It has sold all 30 of its luxury boxes, 
some priced at $13,770 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	While awaiting completion of the 10-month project, the Crew --  
which won just four road games all last season -- had to open with 
seven straight away games. 
</P>
<P>
	But behind stars such as Stern John, who had a league-high 26  
goals last year, and national team member Brian McBride, the team 
won five times and leads the Eastern Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The stadium will be the site of next year's MLS All-Star game  
and the 2001 league championship. The U.S. Soccer Federation would 
like the men's and women's national teams to play there. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can definitely see it being a big part of the World Cup  
qualifiers,'' McBride said. ``This would be a great place to have 
that type of game.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 16:16:01 </DATE_TIME>
