<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> King Family Claims Rights to Speech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.'s estate has no  
right to claim ownership of footage depicting the civil rights 
leader delivering his ``I Have a Dream'' speech, says a lawyer for 
CBS News. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd Abrams argued Tuesday before a three-judge panel of the  
11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals that organizers of the Aug. 28, 
1963, rally at the Lincoln Memorial placed no limits on how the 
speech should be used. 
</P>
<P>
	King's family is asking the appeals court to rule that the  
speech is private property and that CBS should have to pay for 
using the footage in a documentary the network sold on videotape. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyer Joseph Beck argued that the speech is King's most  
important work and he would not have wanted it used for commercial 
purposes without his approval. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wouldn't have authorized this. He wouldn't have given away  
his most valuable work,'' Beck said, with King's widow, Coretta 
Scott King, and son Dexter King sitting a few rows behind him. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine minutes of the 16-minute speech, which became a powerful  
symbol of the civil rights movement, were used in ``The 20th 
Century with Mike Wallace.'' The King estate sued in 1996, seeking 
to stop CBS from using the footage. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge William O'Kelley ruled last July that King  
forfeited any copyright interest when he distributed advance copies 
to reporters without copyright notice, placed no restrictions on 
what use could be made of the speech and generally encouraged its 
distribution. 
</P>
<P>
	King and event organizers ``begged the press to come and cover  
this event,'' Abrams said. The speech ``was what Dr. King called, 
`A living petition to the public and the Congress.' It was directed 
at everyone,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The King family appealed that ruling to the 11th Circuit.  
</P>
<P>
	The three-judge panel's questions Tuesday centered on the  
advance copies and the publication of the speech in a Southern 
Christian Leadership Conference newsletter. 
</P>
<P>
	The King estate says the slain leader applied for a copyright of  
the speech on Sept. 30, 1963, a few days after the SCLC printed it 
in the newsletter. The judges questioned whether King, who headed 
the SCLC, authorized putting the speech in the newsletter without 
copyright notice. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard for me to believe that Dr. King didn't know what was  
in that newsletter,'' said circuit court judge R. Lanier Anderson, 
III. 
</P>
<P>
	Beck said ruling in favor of the King family would protect the  
speech from ``greedy'' people who would charge nonprofit 
organizations and schools to use the footage. CBS charges $1,000 
for schools to use 30 seconds of footage from the speech, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A ruling in favor of CBS would put the work -- and other public  
events, such as rock concerts, in the public domain, Beck said. 
``People could use 'I Have a Dream' to sell automobiles.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
