<DOCNO> APW19990512.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 06:20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Companies Get New Report Card </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the government poised to admonish them  
for poor performance, companies on the Internet are preparing for a 
new report card grading their efforts to protect the personal 
details they collect about consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry-funded survey of roughly 360 Internet sites will  
gauge whether businesses are doing better than last summer, when a 
similar government study found that only 14 percent of sites 
adequately warned how companies used private information they 
collected about customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important to show what level of progress has been made,''  
said Harold McGraw III, chief executive officer for the McGraw-Hill 
Cos. ``Last year, less than 14 percent, that doesn't speak very 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report, expected to be released today, will help define the  
role the federal government will play in regulating parts of the 
Internet, the worldwide computer network used by roughly 100 
million Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Trade Commission, expected to recommend to Congress  
this summer whether new Internet privacy laws are needed, has said 
it wanted to see results from the study before making any 
decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Privacy groups complain that the online industry has done a poor  
job on its own protecting the details it collects about customers, 
such as names, postal and e-mail addresses and even likes and 
dislikes. Some Web sites sell the information to third-party 
advertisers and others. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House, with the industry's support, has agreed so far  
to allow companies to develop their own guidelines because of 
concerns that federal intervention could stifle the growth of 
electronic commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Clinton administration has taken a carrot-and-stick  
approach. Last summer, Vice President Al Gore warned executives 
that unless the industry takes adequate measures to protect 
consumer privacy, ``we will be obliged to take action ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	People who don't use the Internet frequently cite privacy  
concerns as their primary reason for staying off line. The issue 
has taken on growing significance as more companies have begun 
selling products over the Internet, expected eventually to carry 
billions of dollars in transactions daily. 
</P>
<P>
	``Based on the numbers, there's going to be an argument over  
whether self-regulation is succeeding or whether legislation is 
necessary,'' predicted Jerry Berman, executive director of the 
Washington-based Center for Democracy and Technology. ``The 
question on the table is, is progress being made?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harriet Pearson of IBM, one of the companies that helped pay for  
the study, said nearly all the 100 most popular sites on the Web 
now explain what information is collected and how it's used, up 
from 71 percent of those biggest sites identified in last year's 
study. 
</P>
<P>
	But among Web sites of all sizes, large and small, IBM and  
others argued that merely doubling the number of sites with 
adequate privacy notices from last year's 14 percent would 
represent substantial progress. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a company, we're hoping to see the privacy surveys show  
that companies doing e-business are making significant strides, 
making the Internet a well-lit highway safe for consumers to 
travel,'' Pearson said. ``Is it going to be perfect? No, but it 
will be close to perfect for the top-traveled sites.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some critics complained that the latest study, which was not  
expected to include recommendations about whether new laws are 
needed, didn't measure whether a Web site's privacy policy was 
sufficient, but just looked to see whether one existed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is not whether there's a privacy policy, but  
is there privacy protection?'' said Marc Rotenberg, director of the 
Electronic Privacy Information Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the largest companies on the Web, including IBM, America  
Online, Microsoft, Compaq and eBay, paid a total of $60,000 for the 
study, conducted by Georgetown University business professor Mary 
J. Culnan. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 09:55:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Criticize DOE in Spy Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Energy Department should have searched the  
personal computer of a suspected spy at the Los Alamos weapons lab 
even if it jeopardized the case in court, several senators said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Protection of nuclear secrets was more important than  
prosecution, suggested Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska. ``If we 
can't convict, we can sure stop the process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Murkowski questioned the Energy Department's general counsel as  
to why the computer of Taiwan-born scientist Wen Ho Lee was not 
searched after lab officials offered such a search as early as 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Anne Sullivan, the DOE's general counsel, said the FBI had  
advised such a search could jeopardize their investigation and that 
a search would violate Lee's privacy and likely make the evidence 
unusable in court. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's clear we had the authority ... to search,'' Sullivan told  
the Energy and Natural Resources Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	But she said if the department proceeded with the search over  
the FBI's objections, ``We would have subjected ourselves to 
another criticism. That we compromised their ability to conduct an 
investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Murkowski had publicly wanted to question officials of the FBI  
and the Justice Department, but he said they declined to appear and 
would limit their testimony to a closed session because of security 
concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we should have initiated the search,'' agreed Sen.  
Blanche Lincoln, D-Ark. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee, who was fired March 8, has been under investigation by the  
FBI since 1996 for possible espionage. He has not been charged with 
a crime and through his lawyer has said he never provided secrets 
to anyone including China. 
</P>
<P>
	When Lee's unsecured computer was searched in early March,  
investigators found he had removed more than 1,000 files of 
top-secret computer codes that he allegedly transferred from the 
lab's highly secure computer system in 1994-95, according to 
government officials. Investigators have not determined whether any 
of those files left the Los Alamos lab in New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 10 congressional committees are investigating security  
lapses at the DOE weapons labs, including Los Alamos, where the 
espionage investigation involving Lee has been the primary focus. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, in announcing a broad  
restructuring of the department's security program on Tuesday, said 
he hoped naming a new ``security czar'' would avoid some of the 
confusion that marked the Lee investigation. Richardson has said it 
was a mistake that Lee, because of communication breakdowns, was 
not removed earlier from access to top-secret weapons material. 
</P>
<P>
	At times, the widely dispersed security structure resulted in  
unclear lines of authority and confusion and communications lapses, 
Richardson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson has moved on several fronts to try to assure Congress  
his department should continue to control the nation's prestigious 
weapons research labs and that the lab structure not undergo major 
change as some lawmakers have suggested. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can demonstrate that the labs are accountable to us. We run  
the labs,'' Richardson said in a meeting with reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	But the growing espionage controversy that has centered on the  
Los Alamos lab, where the first atomic bomb was made more than a 
half century ago, has raised questions about whether private 
contractors should manage the labs. 
</P>
<P>
	Some lawmakers have suggested the nuclear weapons labs ought to  
be brought under direct government management and perhaps under 
another department. The debate mirrors arguments, which were 
revived several years ago, over whether all nuclear weapons 
programs should not be shifted to the Defense Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Historically, the research labs have flaunted their autonomy,  
cultivated strong allies in Congress and resisted control -- on 
security matters or anything else -- from the Energy Department in 
Washington. They have been viewed by some as semiautonomous 
fiefdoms managed by private contractors. 
</P>
<P>
	Since its inception, Los Alamos, as well as the Lawrence  
Livermore National Laboratory in California, has been managed by 
the University of California. Sandia National Laboratories, also in 
New Mexico, is managed by a subsidiary of the Lockheed Martin Corp. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
