<DOCNO> APW19990512.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 23:22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kevorkian Associate Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO RANCHO, N.M. (AP) -- Police are investigating an associate of  
Dr. Jack Kevorkian about a woman who apparently suffered from 
multiple sclerosis and died from an overdose of the sedative 
pentobarbitol. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a death here that was caused by a poison -- a poison  
that has to be administered,'' said District Attorney Mike Runnels. 
``You can't take pentobarbitol by accident.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Donna Brennan's body was found in her Rio Rancho home nearly  
nine months ago by a neighbor who had been tending to her. 
</P>
<P>
	After her family raised questions about her death, police began  
an investigation that ultimately led them to Dr. Georges Reding's 
home near Galesburg, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	Evidence relating to her death was recovered at his home, along  
with numerous files that include apparent medical records for 
patients from across the country, police said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of circumstances to investigate,'' Runnels  
said. ``There will be charges filed if there's an indication that 
we have a crime committed here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No charges have been filed against Reding. A 1963 New Mexico law  
prohibits assisted suicide, which is a fourth-degree felony 
punishable by 18 months in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Reding, 74, was arrested last year with Kevorkian when the pair  
dropped off a body at a suburban Detroit hospital. Reding was 
acquitted of charges he interfered with police and resisted arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian was sentenced last month to 10 to 25 years in prison  
for second-degree murder in the nationally televised injection 
death last September of Thomas Youk, a Lou Gehrig's disease 
patient. 
</P>
<P>
	According to toxicology reports, Ms. Brennan died of an overdose  
of pentobarbitol. Authorities said she had apparently suffered from 
multiple sclerosis, an often-crippling nerve disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Schwartz, a Michigan-based attorney who has defended  
both Reding and Kevorkian, said Reding was being harassed by 
authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that they've gotten Dr. Kevorkian, they've decided they're  
going to go after his colleague,'' Schwartz said. 
</P>
<P>
	Runnels said investigators had no idea when they began the  
investigation eight months ago that it would led to Reding. 
</P>
<P>
	``To say it's harassment is absurd,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 19:42:48 </DATE_TIME>
