<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kevorkian Associate Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO RANCHO, N.M. (AP) -- An associate of Dr. Jack Kevorkian is  
under investigation in the death of a 54-year-old woman who had 
been suffering from multiple sclerosis. 
</P>
<P>
	Rio Rancho police said Wednesday that evidence relating to the  
woman's death has been recovered from Dr. Georges Reding's home 
near Galesburg, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	Police also found numerous files and documents, including  
apparent medical records for patients from across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said no charges have been filed against the  
74-year-old Reding. A 1963 New Mexico law prohibits assisted 
suicide, which is a felony punishable by 18 months in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of circumstances to investigate,'' Sandoval  
County District Attorney Mike Runnels said Wednesday. ``There will 
be charges filed if there's an indication that we have a crime 
committed here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reding, a retired psychiatrist, was arrested last year with  
Kevorkian when the pair dropped off a body at a suburban Detroit 
hospital. Reding was found innocent of charges he interfered with 
police and resisted arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian was sentenced last month to 10 to 25 years in prison  
for second-degree murder in the nationally televised injection 
death last September of Thomas Youk, a Lou Gehrig's disease 
patient. 
</P>
<P>
	According to toxicology reports, Donna Brennan died Aug. 30,  
1998 in Rio Rancho of an overdose of pentobarbital, a sedative that 
can be lethal. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Brennan had apparently suffered much of her adult life from  
multiple sclerosis, an often-crippling nerve disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities first believed the woman died of natural causes. But  
her family contacted Rio Rancho police shortly after her death and 
asked for an investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Michael Schwartz, who has defended both Reding and  
Kevorkian, said Reding was being harassed by authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that they've gotten Dr. Kevorkian, they've decided they're  
going to go after his colleague.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 15:24:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Devil Rays Pitcher Out for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Tampa Bay Devil Rays pitcher Jim  
Mecir fractured his right elbow when he tripped during batting 
practice Wednesday and will miss the rest of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Devil Rays' primary setup man fell while running after a  
ball prior the Tampa Bay's 9-4 loss to the Minnesota Twins. 
</P>
<P>
	Mecir, 0-1 with 2.61 ERA in 17 games, will have a pin inserted  
into his throwing elbow Thursday by Dr. James Andrews in Birmingham 
Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jim's an important part of the ballclub,'' Tampa Bay manager  
Larry Rothschild said. ``He's picked up some huge innings for us. 
Last year, he was the guy who kept it together in a lot of 
situations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents are hitting just .205 against Mecir, who has given up  
15 hits and seven runs -- six earned -- in 20 2-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay also placed reliever Albie Lopez on the 15-day  
disabled list Wednesday with a left oblique strain and activated 
infielder Aaron Ledesman (dislocated left thumb) from the DL. 
</P>
<P>
	The Devil Rays optioned right-hander Eddie Gaillard to Triple-A  
Durham. Tampa Bay, looking to add left-handed pitching depth, will 
make two roster additions on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
