<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 02:12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Move Members Mark Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Fourteen years after police destroyed 61  
homes in what a grand jury later called ``an epic of governmental 
incompetence,'' some residents complain the rebuilt houses are 
cursed. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 13, 1985, a police helicopter dropped a satchel bomb on  
the roof of a row house where members of MOVE had been blaring 
their anti-government messages. 
</P>
<P>
	MOVE -- a mostly black group whose members adopted the surname  
Africa, ate raw food, espoused equality with animals and preached 
against technology -- had been seeking the release of nine members 
convicted of killing a police officer in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	A gunfight broke out as police, acting on complaints from  
neighbors, tried to serve arrest warrants on four of the members. 
</P>
<P>
	During the assault, police dropped the homemade bomb to open a  
hole for tear gas. It missed and started a fire that killed 11 
people, including five children, and leveled 61 homes in West 
Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	City taxpayers have spent more than $36 million to rebuild the  
houses, settle claims by the estates of dead MOVE members and pay 
other expenses. But the houses continue to be plagued with 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Then-Mayor Wilson Goode had vowed to get people home by  
Christmas, less than eight months after the bombing, but the hurry 
may have compromised the construction. 
</P>
<P>
	After inspecting the houses two years ago, the U.S. Army Corps  
of Engineers estimated further repairs would cost at least $1.6 
million. The inspection itself cost $500,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The corps found evidence of a rush job. Stairways weren't where  
the design drawings put them, and living-room closets and half 
baths weren't there at all. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators reported that the vast majority of problems  
resulted from ``design and/or construction deficiencies.'' They 
include cracking bricks, deteriorating siding, faulty roofs, 
improper electrical wiring, and substandard windows and sliding 
doors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to stop being in the home-repair business,'' said Noel  
Eisenstat, executive director of the city's Redevelopment 
Authority. 
</P>
<P>
	He and Mayor Edward G. Rendell hope to complete the major  
repairs, as prescribed by the Army Corps, then make cash 
settlements with homeowners over smaller problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to get this work done quickly and well, and have these  
complaints addressed,'' said Kevin Feeley, Rendell's spokesman. 
Officials think repairs can be wrapped up before Rendell leaves 
office in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents are understandably skeptical.  
</P>
<P>
	``When I see them come out and start, that's when I believe  
them,'' Thomas Mapp told The Philadelphia Inquirer on Tuesday. ``I 
really don't believe them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The original developer of the houses, Ernest A. Edwards Jr., was  
convicted of stealing more than $137,000 from the project and 
served about seven years in prison. He now makes monthly 
restitution payments of $600 to the city. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1988, a city grand jury called the 1985 confrontation ``an  
epic of governmental incompetence,'' but found no basis for 
criminal charges against city officials or police. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, MOVE operates a World Wide Web site from a West  
Philadelphia home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
