<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TheStreet.com Up 216 Pct. in IPO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The latest success story in the still-buoyant  
market for new Internet stocks: TheStreet.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of the Internet news service soared 216 percent in the  
company's initial public offering Tuesday, rising from its opening 
price of $19 to close at $60 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. The stock 
rose as high as $73 at one point, as 13.5 million shares changed 
hands. 
</P>
<P>
	The offering convinced analysts that, despite a few flat  
Internet IPOs in recent weeks, money managers and investors are 
still willing to pay up for Web-related companies with strong brand 
names or ties to blue-chip businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	TheStreet.com is the brainchild of James J. Cramer, a hedge fund  
manager who founded the site in 1996. Cramer is a tireless and 
prolific promoter, supplementing his daily columns on TheStreet.com 
with appearances on cable news channel CNBC and guest columns in 
Time magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	The site itself has become a favorite of Wall Street traders  
with its chatty, sometimes irreverent stock market commentary. On 
Tuesday, the headline ``Net Stocks Discover There's Something About 
Mary,'' topped a story on the influence of Morgan Stanley Dean 
Witter analyst Mary Meeker. 
</P>
<P>
	``James Cramer is the trader crowd's apostle,'' said Gail  
Bronson, an analyst for IPO Monitor.com. ``He tells it as he sees 
it, no holds barred.'' 
</P>
<P>
	TheStreet.com also benefited from its association with  
high-profile backers like the New York Times Co., which bought a 
minority stake in February, and News Corp., which agreed last week 
to invest $7.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Several market watchers said that as new issues of Internet  
stocks continue to flood the market, money managers and investors 
may be applying tougher standards to the stocks they add to their 
portfolios. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is starting to focus on winners,'' said Ken  
Fleming, a research analyst at Renaissance Capital Corp. ``For 
these companies, that means big names, premier underwriters and 
good backers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One thing it still doesn't mean is profits. In 1998,  
TheStreet.com lost $16.4 million on revenue of $4.6 million. In 
this year's first quarter, the company lost $7.2 million on revenue 
of less than $2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Like many of its Web-based rivals, the company has opted to  
spend heavily to develop its content and attract subscribers and 
advertisers, in the hope of building profits down the line. 
</P>
<P>
	Subscriptions are on the rise, with 51,000 at the end of March,  
up from 32,000 at the end of December. Subscribers pay $99.95 a 
year, or $9.95 per month, although 5,500 signed on in last year's 
fourth quarter through a deal that exchanged subscriptions for 
frequent flier miles. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said Cramer's name, and his willingness to tout his  
business, enticed many investors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Marketing, marketing, marketing,'' Bronson said. ``It's the  
critical factor for a successful Internet IPO.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fleming said companies with strong, recognizable brand names are  
likely to dominate the IPO market in the months to come, naming 
Barnesandnoble.com, the online wing of the big bookseller, as the 
next hot offering. Its pricing has not yet been scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	TheStreet.com's big first day couldn't touch the debut of rival  
MarketWatch.com, which posted a stunning 474 percent gain when it 
hit the market in January. Analysts said MarketWatch benefited from 
its alliance with the CBS television network. 
</P>
<P>
	Cramer's media ventures have not always been smooth. CNBC  
suspended him from one show last December after questions arose 
about whether he was commenting on a stock and trying to trade on 
it at the same time. He denied the charge, which came from Internet 
company WavePhore Inc. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 21:05:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Agrees on $11.6B for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional negotiators agreed Wednesday to  
provide $11.6 billion for the air assault on Yugoslavia and to 
boost overall defense spending, nearly doubling the amount 
President Clinton requested. 
</P>
<P>
	But ongoing disputes over items ranging from fishing in Alaska's  
Glacier Bay to taxpayer assistance for some U.S. steel companies 
was hindering completion of the package, which House and Senate 
leaders want to send to Clinton by week's end. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers' demands for favored items were so insistent that they  
drove an exasperated GOP Rep. Bill Young of Florida, chairman of 
the House Appropriations Committee and a 29-year House member, to 
say, ``I'm practicing for my next career, and that is refereeing in 
the World Wrestling Federation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The provisions legislators were trying -- and in some cases  
succeeding -- in adding to the package also drew the ire of the 
White House, which has already threatened to veto the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've warned them not to load up this legislation'' with added  
language, said Linda Ricci, spokeswoman for the White House budget 
office. She also said Congress should avoid ``harmful cuts in other 
programs'' to pay for parts of the package. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the agreed-upon measures opposed by the White House would  
prohibit the federal government from laying claim to any of the 
$246 billion from settlements that states have reached with the 
tobacco industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest chunk of the bill -- and the item with the strongest  
political appeal -- was the money for U.S. participation in NATO's 
bombing of Yugoslavia. Though lawmakers are divided over the wisdom 
of the attacks, even many opponents are reluctant to oppose funds 
for the troops in the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do believe that this war was started frivolously and pursued  
incompetently,'' said Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash. ``But I do believe 
we've got to pay for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To the $6 billion Clinton sought for the confrontation over  
Kosovo, House-Senate bargainers agreed to add $1.8 billion for a 
troop pay raise that would begin in January; $2.5 billion for 
military operations and maintenance of equipment; $678 million to 
help Kosovo's refugees and the Balkan states sheltering them; plus 
additional funds to replace depleted bombs, purchase other weapons 
and recruit. 
</P>
<P>
	The bargainers also agreed to pare $1 billion the House approved  
to modernize overseas military bases to $475 million, and to 
provide $200 million for the Coast Guard. 
</P>
<P>
	The compromise also would include nearly $1 billion for recent  
natural disasters in the Caribbean, mostly to help Honduras, Costa 
Rica, El Salvador and Nicaragua rebound from last autumn's 
devastating Hurricane Mitch. 
</P>
<P>
	There is also $100 million for Jordan; $566 million to help  
American farmers struggling because of badly sagging commodities 
prices; and $900 million for the costs of the recent tornadoes in 
the Midwest and for a cushion for future disasters. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiators worked into the evening, attempting to heed orders  
by House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and Senate Majority Leader 
Trent Lott, R-Miss., to complete their bargaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said bargainers had accepted  
her Senate-approved proposal to continue a moratorium through 
September against new Energy Department rules that would force oil 
and gas producers using federal lands to pay higher royalties to 
the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., won his attempt to delay the Interior  
Department from implementing stricter cleanup requirements for 
mining companies using federal lands. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, participants said bargainers would allow the  
government to spend up to $4.3 million more for reparations to 
people of Japanese descent who were deported or placed in camps 
during World War II, and who missed an earlier round of federal 
reparation payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., dropped an effort to prevent the  
Interior Department from setting aside stretches of the Rio Grande 
River to protect the endangered silvery minnow. 
</P>
<P>
	Bargainers accepted a Senate-passed provision by Hutchison to  
keep the federal government's hands off the tobacco settlements. 
They also appeared ready to accept another by Sen. Robert Byrd, 
D-W.Va., to provide $140 million to back $1 billion worth of loans 
for some small steel companies facing competition from low-priced 
imports. 
</P>
<P>
	But key differences remained.  
</P>
<P>
	Kansas GOP Sens. Pat Roberts and Sam Brownback were pushing a  
provision to forgive more than $200 million in interest and 
penalties owed by the state's natural gas producers who were ruled 
to have overcharged customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Alaska's Republican Senate duo, Frank Murkowski and Senate  
Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, made a lengthy plea 
to block the National Park Service from phasing out commercial and 
subsistence fishing in Glacier Bay National Park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
