<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> RJR Sharholders Meet Before Spinoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) -- The separation of RJR Nabisco's food  
and domestic tobacco businesses will return tidy profits to 
shareholders in both companies, chairman Steven F. Goldstone said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone told me today, `All's well that ends well,' '' he told  
reporters following what amounted to RJR Nabisco's last 
shareholders meeting. ``We now have two companies that are in very 
good shape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In March, RJR Nabisco announced its intention to spin off its  
U.S. cigarette business from its food interests after selling its 
international tobacco business for nearly $8 billion to Japan 
Tobacco Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	RJR said the international tobacco sale was completed Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	The spinoff of the domestic tobacco business, which makes  
Winston, Camel and Salem cigarettes, is expected to be completed by 
June 15, Goldstone said. 
</P>
<P>
	It is second only to Philip Morris Cos. Inc., maker of Marlboro.  
</P>
<P>
	None of the moves required shareholder approval. The meeting  
drew about 200 shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing more relaxed than he has been at previous shareholders  
meetings, Goldstone said he could understand why one speaker 
described the meeting as a wake. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people are nostalgic about this company,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	RJR Nabisco was acquired just over a decade ago for about $25  
billion in the biggest leveraged buyout at that time. The deal 
capped one of the wildest corporate bidding wars of the junk 
bond-fueled 1980s and was chronicled on the book ``Barbarians at 
the Gate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to its tobacco business, RJR owns an 80.6 percent  
stake in Nabisco Holdings Corp., which makes Oreo cookies, Ritz 
crackers and Planters nuts. That is all RJR will own after the 
domestic tobacco spinoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Advocates of a split-up of the tobacco and food interests argued  
the market was undervaluing the food business because of its 
connection with the potential liabilities of the tobacco 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	With the spinoff of the tobacco business, Goldstone said,  
Nabisco shareholders won't have to worry about lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	``As time goes along, Nabisco shareholders won't be thinking  
about litigation,'' he said. ``They'll be thinking about Oreos and 
Chips Ahoy!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goldstone will remain with Nabisco as chairman while James M.  
Kilts will remain as president and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	As a separate publicly-traded company, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco  
will have the financial muscle to continue to defend itself in 
tobacco lawsuits, Goldstone said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders will have one share in each separate company when  
the spinoff is completed. 
</P>
<P>
	Several anti-smoking speakers addressed Goldstone during the  
30-minute question-and-answer session. Shareholders overwhelmingly 
rejected two shareholder proposals: one on tobacco advertising and 
youth and the second dealing with cigarette smuggling. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders also elected a company-backed slate of nine  
directors. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholder Carl Icahn had nominated his own slate to challenge  
the RJR nominees but withdrew it late last month. Icahn wanted RJR 
to spin off the food holdings rather than the domestic tobacco 
business. But he dropped his proxy contest after several large 
shareholders told him they supported management's spinoff plan as 
the quickest way to divide the company. 
</P>
<P>
	In his remarks, R.J. Reynolds chief executive Andrew J.  
Schindler said he was looking forward to the challenge of running 
the tobacco business as a separate entity. 
</P>
<P>
	He said cigarette consumption is declining, with estimates for  
1999 indicating U.S. consumption will fall as much as 8.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the industry is facing more lawsuits and political  
pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	``We intend to be as resilient and competitive as possible in  
this new environment,'' Schindler said. ``We'll fight hard to 
maintain our market position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of RJR closed up 37 1/2 cents, at $28.75, on the New York  
Stock Exchange, while shares of Nabisco were off 6 1/4 cents, at 
$42.12 1/2. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
