<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cyclist Denies Drug Use Confession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- French cyclist Richard Virenque on Wednesday denied  
he had confessed to taking drugs, but cast doubt on his future in 
the sport, saying he felt drained. 
</P>
<P>
	Judicial officials were quoted a day earlier as saying that  
Virenque told a judge investigating drug use that he had taken 
substances supplied by Bertrand Sainz, one of five people being 
investigated for involvement in what has been described as a 
drug-supplying network. 
</P>
<P>
	The Le Monde newspaper on Wednesday also said it had learned  
that Virenque had admitted to drug abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	But the former Festina cyclist, who now rides for Italy's Polti  
team, said Sainz had prescribed vitamins. 
</P>
<P>
	Virenque was at the center of last year's Tour de France doping  
scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike other Festina riders, he has continually denied he  
knowingly took banned substances. He has previously threatened to 
quit cycling over drug abuse allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, he said he needed time to think over his future.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm aware there's a problem in the sport ... but must Richard  
Virenque quit so there's no longer a doping problem? I don't 
know,'' he said in an interview with television channel TF1. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to have a long talk with my wife and we'll see at a  
later date, but today I feel drained.'' 
</P>
<P>
	World Cup leader Frank Vandenbroucke on Tuesday acknowledged  
taking medical products from Sainz, but said he thought they were 
homeopathic substances. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, two Spanish cycling teams, ONCE and Banesto, denied  
published reports that they may skip this year's Tour de France. 
Both said they intend taking part in the cycling's premier event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
