<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Lighter Side of Business /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CUTTING CULINARY COSTS: If your corporate travel managers clutch  
when they see the meal tab from your business trips, it may be time 
to cut back. The consulting firm Runzheimer International, which 
notes that meals are the third-biggest business travel expense 
after airfare and lodging, has some suggestions. First, don't eat 
in hotel dining rooms or airport terminals, which tend to have a 
huge markup. If you're staying in the suburbs and have access to a 
car, there are plenty of moderate and lower priced restaurants to 
choose from. Another idea is to find out where local residents eat; 
they probably know where to get decent food at a good price. And do 
some research about cheaper places to eat before you leave home. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	DINER DREAMS: For many people, a diner is the place to go for  
eggs-over-easy, blue-plate specials and mugs of coffee. For others, 
it's not just an eatery; it's a reminder of another era and a way 
to grab hold of fond memories. Really serious diner enthusiasts 
have their own convention, called Diner-Rama, that includes three 
days of eating, talking and field trips. This year's Diner-Rama is 
being held June 18-21 in Parsippany, N.J., and will include visits 
to companies that make diners and a day-long tour of notable nearby 
diners. But the American Diner Museum, which sponsors the 
convention, says it's not all fun -- it includes a seminar about 
operating a diner that will let wannabe owners know that a lot of 
hard work comes along with the nostalgia. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HOME EQUITY LOANS: Bank One, trying to find out more about  
Americans' borrowing preferences, says it found that many 
homeowners don't understand the tax advantages of home equity 
loans. The nation's fifth-largest bank says it commissioned a 
survey in which 40 percent of the 723 responding homeowners did not 
know that the interest on home equity loans is usually tax 
deductible for people who itemize deductions on their tax returns. 
That lack of knowledge may be contributing to the fact that 28 
percent of the homeowners said they have used home equity loans or 
lines of credits, while 66 percent have taken out auto loans and 58 
percent have received personal loans. The interest on auto and 
personal loans is not tax-deductible. 
</P>
<P>
	---	 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
