<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flynt Makes Deal With Prosecutors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Prosecutors dropped obscenity charges against  
Larry Flynt on Wednesday after he agreed to stop selling hard-core 
videos at his Cincinnati bookstore. As part of the plea bargain, 
the shop was fined $10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement came on the third day of jury selection in a trial  
that could have sent the Hustler magazine publisher to prison for 
24 years. Prospective jurors had been warned they would have to 
watch as many as 40 hours of porn videos. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors allowed Flynt, 56, and his brother, Jimmy, 52, to  
substitute their bookstore for themselves in a plea of guilty to 
two counts of pandering obscenity. Hustler News &AMP; Gifts, which 
Jimmy Flynt manages, was fined $5,000 on each count. 
</P>
<P>
	The Flynts agreed to remove sexually explicit videos from the  
store, which also sells Hustler and other magazines and sex toys. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors dropped 13 charges against the Flynts, including one  
count alleging a 14-year-old boy bought porno videos at the store. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very pleased,'' Larry Flynt said. ``The deal the  
prosecution offered us was the deal we always wanted. We want to 
sell our magazine. If they just leave the magazine alone, we'll be 
OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Flynt also said: ``My brother, who I love very much, is involved  
in this case and he faced 24 years right along with me. And even 
though we felt very good about the jury, you can never be sure what 
they're going to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Flynt opened the store just off downtown Cincinnati's  
centerpiece Fountain Square in 1997 because he was angry at 
obscenity crackdowns that kept his magazine largely unavailable in 
the city. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he hoped his trial would show that community standards  
for obscenity had changed since 1977, when he was convicted of 
obscenity for selling Hustler in Cincinnati. In that case, Flynt 
served six days of a seven-to-25-year sentence. The conviction was 
overturned in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Mike Allen said Hamilton County protected its values  
and made no concessions to the Flynts. 
</P>
<P>
	``He didn't win. He lost,'' Allen said. ``He turned tail and  
ran.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
