<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 14:35:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Police Study Proposal Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A proposal for a new commission to study  
training, recruitment and use of force by big-city police 
departments won't solve persistent problems of police brutality, 
House Democrats said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't need another study. What we need is real reform,''  
said Rep. John Conyers of Michigan, senior Democrat on the House 
Judiciary Committee, at a hearing on the National Police Training 
Commission Act of 1999. ``This is a serious, ongoing, historically 
important matter that's been troubling this committee ever since 
I've been on it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police groups voiced different concerns about the objectivity of  
the commission. 
</P>
<P>
	House and Senate leaders would appoint five members to the  
commission to study the ``effectiveness of training, recruiting, 
hiring, oversight and funding policies and practices in law 
enforcement'' and report to Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also authorizes $3 million in grants next fiscal year  
for New York, Chicago, Los Angeles and Washington for training 
programs. It is sponsored by House Judiciary Committee Chairman 
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and Rep. Jose Serrano, D-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyde, who alluded to a recent spate of high-profile cases of  
alleged police brutality, said that while individual incidents can 
be redressed through the civil and criminal courts, the legal 
system cannot solve underlying problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, he said, proposes solutions ``to bolster the  
confidence the citizens have in their police and to provide 
effective training for police officers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sgt. Marty Pfeifer, a national board member of the Fraternal  
Order of Police, said the organization was concerned that ``any 
commission with political appointees may not have the requisite 
objectivity needed to examine the issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Edward Flynn, police chief in Arlington, Va., and  
legislative chair of the Police Executive Research Forum, wanted 
details about how the study would be done. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., who said she comes from the  
``police brutality capital of the world,'' pronounced herself 
disgusted by the Hyde-Serrano bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that this bill is going to help at all if police  
departments don't get it yet,'' she said. Real penalties are needed 
to deter officers from ``using the badge and the gun to violate 
people's civil rights,'' Waters said. 
</P>
<P>
	Serrano, who represents the Bronx district where the fatal  
police shooting of Amadou Diallo, a street vendor from West Africa, 
has come to symbolize excessive use of force by police, said the 
problem can't be blamed on racism alone. 
</P>
<P>
	He said police departments ``must do a better job of recruiting,  
teaching use-of-force policies and selecting assignments for 
officers'' because many lack the skills and training to deal 
effectively with people from other cultures. 
</P>
<P>
	The NAACP said the bill also should include increased funding  
for several Justice Department programs and require police officers 
to collect racial information on drivers pulled over for alleged 
traffic violations. 
</P>
<P>
	Diallo's mother, Kadiadou, who also testified, said she still  
seeks answers to questions about what happened to her eldest son. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not against the police,'' she said. ``All I ask is justice  
against these four people who murdered my son. All I appeal to the 
federal government is to provide whatever they can to prevent this 
kind of situation in the future.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
