<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Morning Show Stunts Suffer Setbacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- TV's morning news shows may want to think twice  
the next time a travel agent comes calling. 
</P>
<P>
	After enduring an uncomfortable night on the side of Mount  
Everest, Matt Lauer of NBC's ``Today'' show was prevented Tuesday 
from traveling to a second mystery location when the Indian 
government grounded his plane. 
</P>
<P>
	Hostile weather in this country forced Charles Gibson, Diane  
Sawyer and the crew of ABC's ``Good Morning America'' to travel 10 
hours by bus from Austin, Texas, to New Orleans in time for 
Tuesday's show -- and another downpour. 
</P>
<P>
	Both shows are traveling to drum up interest during a ratings  
``sweeps'' month. For the second straight year, NBC's ``Where in 
the world is Matt Lauer?'' promotion sends the anchorman on a 
week-long mystery tour to destinations unknown to viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	He made it to the slopes of the world's tallest mountain Monday,  
but it's been all downhill since. 
</P>
<P>
	Fog obscured views of the peak and prevented Lauer from leaving  
after Monday's show. He was stuck in a shack with his wife, model 
Annette Roque Lauer, eating ravioli and crackers, and sleeping in 
sleeping bags. There was no running water, only an outhouse 
accessible after a jog in the freezing cold. 
</P>
<P>
	The fog finally lifted enough for Lauer to get off the mountain  
and fly to Katmandu, Nepal. But he waited on a runway for more than 
six hours when officials refused permission to fly over Indian 
airspace. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time Lauer finally took off, it was too late to reach his  
second destination in time for Tuesday's show, said Jeff Zucker, 
``Today'' executive producer. He was rerouted in the air to his 
planned third destination. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC scrambled overnight to fill time, calling former ``Partridge  
Family'' actor Danny Bonaduce after midnight for an interview on 
the perils of child stardom. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all part of the game,'' Zucker said. ``In order to score  
big, you've got to take big chances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Good Morning America'' picked Austin for its first stop in a  
bus tour of the South. But Gibson and Sawyer were planning to cheat 
Monday -- traveling by plane to Lafayette, La. -- and ride the bus 
from there to New Orleans. Instead, their plane was grounded and 
everyone had to make the long drive. 
</P>
<P>
	Lafayette, and about 2,000 people who were waiting to greet the  
crew, were bypassed. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Orleans, a downpour Tuesday forced ``GMA'' to move its  
broadcast site from the outdoor Jackson Square to the nearby 
Pontalbo Cafe. The Neville Brothers had to cancel a performance 
because their equipment was drenched, said Shelley Ross, the show's 
executive producer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were all calm,'' Ross said. ``A zen came over our  
production. In a funny way, I think we had a better show. It had 
energy and spontaneity.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
