<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Discovery Launch Could Be Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Hail damage to a fuel tank could  
delay space shuttle Discovery's upcoming launch to the new 
international space station. 
</P>
<P>
	Discovery's 15-story external fuel tank was gouged during a  
thunderstorm over the weekend, mostly near the top. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the 150 holes in the rust-colored foam insulation can be  
patched in time for a May 20 liftoff, NASA spokesman Bruce 
Buckingham said Wednesday. Thirteen gouges are near the top of the 
tank in the back, however, an area that typically cannot be reached 
when the shuttle is on the launch pad. 
</P>
<P>
	The concern is that ice could form in the holes, break off  
during liftoff and damage the shuttle. Ice could form because the 
tank is filled before liftoff with more than a half-million gallons 
of supercold liquid hydrogen and oxygen. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA is putting up scaffolding in an attempt to reach that area.  
If it's still inaccessible and engineers cannot determine the size 
of the 13 holes, shuttle managers may order Discovery back to the 
hangar for repairs, Buckingham said. 
</P>
<P>
	That would delay the station-outfitting mission by at least one  
week, Buckingham said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking at it closely,'' he said. ``Hopefully, we'll be  
able to get the engineering community to agree that it's OK to fly 
as is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A decision is expected Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	The largest hole that can be measured on the tank is 2 inches  
wide and one-third of an inch deep, Buckingham said. Most are only 
a half-inch wide and one-tenth of an inch deep. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time NASA had to return a shuttle to the hangar for  
fuel-tank repairs was in 1995 when woodpeckers chipped away at the 
protective outer foam. The shuttle was Discovery that time, too. 
</P>
<P>
	The fuel tank is in the large, bullet-shaped container between  
the two solid-fuel rocket boosters. It provides fuel for the 
shuttle's three main engines during ascent and then is discarded 
and breaks up in the atmosphere as the shuttle reaches orbit. 
</P>
<P>
	Discovery itself, protected by the launch tower, was not  
damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's storm already has delayed an Air Force launch.  
</P>
<P>
	Rain somehow leaked onto a military Global Positioning System  
satellite at the launch pad. The launch, which had been scheduled 
for as early as this weekend, is on indefinite hold while the Air 
Force removes the satellite from the rocket and checks for damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
