<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Nix Research Funds for Duke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- The federal government has suspended nearly  
all government-funded research involving humans at Duke University 
Medical Center because of lax safety oversight. 
</P>
<P>
	The ordered was issued by the federal Office for Protection from  
Research Risks, a division of the National Institutes of Health. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke, one of the nation's largest and most prestigious research  
facilities, was told not to enroll new subjects in federally funded 
experiments because administrators hadn't fixed problems cited in a 
review the government completed in December. 
</P>
<P>
	``Research activities involving previously enrolled subjects may  
continue only where it is in the best interests of individual 
subjects,'' Dr. Michael Carome, the federal research protection 
agency's chief of compliance, said in a letter Monday to the Duke 
medical center's top administrator. 
</P>
<P>
	Problems center on Duke's Institutional Review Board, which  
evaluates research proposals to see whether they are sound and 
ethical. Federal rules require hospitals to establish such ``IRBs'' 
to ensure that people are properly informed of the risks of the 
trials they are taking part in and to catch early side effects. 
</P>
<P>
	Government inspectors claimed that Duke's committee hadn't kept  
track of the research projects to make sure people weren't being 
harmed. Inspectors also said documents used to obtain consent from 
patients didn't meet regulatory requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	The Office for Protection from Research Risks also said the  
board violated rules that prevent members from reviewing projects 
in which they have a potential interest. After regulators ordered 
that members of one Duke office not vote on projects, they twice 
found that they had. 
</P>
<P>
	In December, Duke was told to fix a number of these problems,  
which also included insufficient training of review board members, 
meetings with too few members and poor record-keeping. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said the school's response was inadequate. But  
Duke emphasized that there was no evidence the oversight lapses had 
harmed anyone. 
</P>
<P>
	``We regret the need for OPRR's decision, but we agree with the  
importance of the administrative changes the agency has 
identified,'' Dr. Ralph Snyderman, Duke's chancellor for health 
affairs, said in a statement Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke said it submitted a plan for making the required changes in  
February, and progress reports in March and April. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke has about 2,000 clinical trials under way involving  
thousands of patients. Duke received $228 million in 1998 for 
federal and non-governmental research, with tens of millions of 
dollars for human clinical trials. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinical trials are the tests performed on humans to evaluate  
how well new medicines or techniques work and whether there are 
negative effects. The process is required by the U.S. Food and Drug 
Administration before any new drug or device can be made widely 
available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
