<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Mixed Early / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar rose against the yen Thursday,  
boosted by buying from Japanese institutional investors. Tokyo 
stocks were mixed amid concern over Russia's political situation. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.20 yen in early trading, up 0.34 yen from  
late Wednesday in Tokyo and also higher than its late New York 
level of 120.95 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 9.59 points,  
or 0.06 percent, to 16,956.95 in the first 30 minutes of trading. 
On Wednesday, the average rose 204.18 points, or 1.22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar gained ground on dollar-buying  
prompted by a belief that the successor to outgoing U.S. Treasury 
Secretary Robert Rubin may maintain a strong dollar policy. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Wednesday, the dollar fell 1.50 yen within  
minutes on news that U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin will 
resign in July. But the currency regained much of its losses later. 
</P>
<P>
	President Bill Clinton announced Wednesday that he will nominate  
Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, a former Harvard 
University professor who has worked closely with Rubin, as his 
third Treasury secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it weren't for Rubin, we probably would have seen the  
dollar go higher in New York, maybe testing 122 yen, so we could 
see some gains today,'' said Akihiko Ena, foreign exchange manager 
at Nippon Trust Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the euro suffered an overnight drop after Russian  
President Boris Yeltsin dismissed his prime minister Yevgeny 
Primakov. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was traded at 128.98 yen in early trading, down from  
129.15 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, sentiment remained low after the news about  
Rubin and the Russian prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
	Tsuyoshi Nomaguchi, a strategist at Daiwa Securities, said the  
succession by Rubin's deputy Summers may not have much impact on 
share prices on a long-term basis since there won't be any change 
in U.S. financial policies. 
</P>
<P>
	Nomaguchi said the Russia situation is more worrisome, as a  
political factor. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 0.96 points, or 0.07 percent, to 1,360.19 
points. The TOPIX closed up 5.33 points, or 0.39 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.325 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.340 
percent, driving its price up to 101.55 yen from 101.42 yen. 
</P>
<P>
 *(km-dj) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
