<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Literacy Program Making Strides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When most people think of early childhood  
learning programs, Head Start comes to mind. The $4 billion 
education and health program has served low-income preschoolers for 
30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	But for the past decade, the smaller Even Start Family Literacy  
program has combined early-childhood reading lessons, adult basic 
education and parenting training for eligible families. The $135 
million Even Start serves about 31,000 families compared with 
800,000 children in Head Start, which provides education, health 
screenings and family social services. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you can't deal with the whole family, you're not going to  
break the cycle,'' said Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa., who created Even 
Start in 1989. ``The academic success of the child is strongly 
related to the ability of their parents to support their 
education.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goodling, chairman of the House Education and Workforce  
Committee, said Even Start is more flexible and emphasizes parental 
involvement and represents his vision of what federal education 
policy should be. A hearing on the program's progress was being 
held today. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who work in the program knew from the start that it would  
have to be self-sustaining, said Deila Steiner, director of the 
Even Start program in Lincoln, Neb. ``We had to show that we could 
sustain the program beyond the life of the federal funding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Even Start grants last about 8 years, after which a program  
must come up with its own funds. Head Start programs are steadily 
funded, but must come up with matching funds. 
</P>
<P>
	--Even Start grants are administered by schools and community  
groups. Head Start centers, by comparison, are generally run 
independently of schools. 
</P>
<P>
	--Even Start programs -- nearly 700 nationwide -- are required to  
form local partnerships. Many of those are with local Head Start 
programs, which can operate alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Goodling is hoping to apply those principles -- partnership,  
self-reliance, local involvement -- as he leads the Republican 
congressional majority in its first chance to put its stamp on the 
34-year-old Elementary and Secondary Education Act, the 
comprehensive law that governs Even Start and most other federal 
kindergarten through 12th grade programs. Democrats controlled the 
House from the time the law was enacted in 1965 through 1994, when 
it was last reauthorized. 
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans are proposing changes in the law that would  
reduce the share of money spent on federal and state administration 
costs, cut federal education regulations and provide more 
flexibility to states and local school districts, bolster teacher 
training, and consolidate current programs. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton is focused on programs to end ``social  
promotion'' of students not academically ready to advance to the 
next grade and reduce class sizes by hiring new teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has said his ultimate goal is to serve 1 million Head  
Start children by 2002. Under his administration, Head Start 
spending has increased by 68 percent. Enrollment has increased by 
more than 200,000 children, reaching 835,000 this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Start's budget and scope have also grown this decade. In  
1989, it served approximately 2,500 families, compared with the 
31,000-plus today. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Head Start, eligible parents in Even Start must study for  
the General Educational Development certificate or take classes in 
basic adult education, parenting and job training. Their children, 
age 8 and under, read and play games to improve their literacy. At 
home, the families read together, draw and tell stories. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent Education Department report on Even Start showed that  
adults and children reached goals such as earning the GED 
credential and increasing reading test scores. However, even the 
most successful families still needed more intensive programs, the 
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodling, a former Pennsylvania school superintendent, said he  
found that despite years of aiming federal dollars at the poor, 
children from such families were not improving their reading or 
learning. So he made sure his early-childhood specialist visited 
preschool-children and their parents at home to help them all read 
better. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
