<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alborn Named To US Jumping Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARK CITY, Utah (AP) -- Alan Alborn of Anchorage, Alaska, who  
looks more like a choirboy than an emerging World Cup contender, 
heads a three-athlete U.S. Ski Jumping Team named today for next 
winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Alborn, 18, scored World Cup points in three competitions last  
season, his first full season on the World Cup tour. Coach Kari 
Ylianttila, who announced the 1999-2000 team, said he planned to 
work during the preseason on strengthening Alborn's takeoff for 
each jump. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Rhys Hecox of Ishpeming, Mich., who returned to the  
sport after two seasons away from ski competition, and 1998 
Olympian Brendan Doran of Steamboat Springs, Colo., were named to 
the national B Team. Hecox won a Continental Cup meet in Finland in 
March, the first merican victory since Doran won in Westby, Wis., 
in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Named to the national development team were Ben Erlandson, 16,  
of Westby, Wis.; Andrew Newcomb, 18, of Park City; and Clint Jones, 
14, Tommy Schwall, 14, and Logan Gerber, 15, all of Steamboat 
Springs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
