<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Siena Plans Cuba Baseball Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUDONVILLE, N.Y. (AP) -- Siena College wants to become the first  
American college baseball team to play in Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	The Franciscan school in suburban Albany has filed papers with  
the U.S. Treasury Department for a trade embargo waiver and the 
Cuban Intersection seeking permission for the January trip, 
athletic director John D'Argenio said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been college student trips to Cuba in recent years.  
But the NCAA said there has never been a U.S. university baseball 
game there. 
</P>
<P>
	If the trip is approved, Siena will play a Cuban team at its  
competitive level, D'Argenio said. A decision is expected within 
four to six weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to raise the profile of our baseball team,''  
D'Argenio said. 
</P>
<P>
	Travel from the United States to Cuba has been restricted since  
Fidel Castro took control 40 years ago, though tensions have eased 
in recent years for academic and artistic events. 
</P>
<P>
	The Baltimore Orioles played there last month against the Cuban  
national team. The two teams played in Baltimore last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Siena, a Division I team, won a school-record 31 games this  
season and was the Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference North 
Division champion. Siena will compete this week in the MAAC 
tournament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
