<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grateful Dead: OK To Download Us </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- It was the feeling of community and word of  
mouth that spawned the vast fan following of the Grateful Dead. Now 
four years after the band called it quits the Dead has found a way 
to keep its music alive -- online. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for the Grateful Dead announced Tuesday the band will  
allow Internet trading of MP3 digital file versions of live concert 
recordings captured by fans, as long as they don't try to make a 
buck in the process. 
</P>
<P>
	``They wanted to control this now rather than when the cow got  
out of the barn,'' said Grateful Dead attorney Eric Doney. He 
thinks online Deadheads would eventually police themselves enough 
to ensure that only the noncopyrighted MP3 files were made 
available. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement came after the band recently discovered an  
Internet Web site that posted live concert MP3 songs, but the 
site's owners also received revenues from banner advertisements on 
the Web page. 
</P>
<P>
	After a brief legal standoff, the site's operator has since  
removed links to the songs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Grateful Dead will continue to put the clamps on sites that  
post commercially released recordings in MP3 format, a practice 
that constitutes copyright infringement. MP3 is a file compression 
format that makes it easy to download high-quality music from the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Casey Meyers trades digital audio tape versions of Grateful Dead  
concerts over the Internet. He says the same word of mouth that 
created the band's fan base would also likely work toward 
discouraging the trading of concert recordings for profit. 
</P>
<P>
	``They just ignore people like that and ignore gestures like  
that,'' Meyers said of online Deadheads' attitude towards Internet 
profit takers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Grateful Dead's online `OK' will likely keep the buzz alive  
for a group that disbanded after lead singer Jerry Garcia died in 
1995 of a heart attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Grateful Dead spokesman Dennis McNally said the concert  
recording agreement between the band and its fans was always 
integral to the band's popularity. The music created by the 
Grateful Dead was to be shared first and foremost. 
</P>
<P>
	``To quote Jerry at the time, 'When we're done with it you can  
have it.' The Deadheads have always played fair'' McNally said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
