<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Rubin Resigns  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, credited for  
the country's economic boom in recent years, is stepping down, and 
President Clinton will nominate his deputy, Lawrence Summers, to 
succeed him. At a White House Rose Garden ceremony, Clinton heaped 
praise on both men. And Rubin said Clinton and Vice President Al 
Gore ``have repositioned our country with respect to fiscal 
discipline, with respect to leadership on international economic 
issues that are so critical to economic well-being.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Mixed; Dow Down 25.78  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices ended mixed today as blue chips  
recovered most of a sharp drop following Treasury Secretary Robert 
Rubin's resignation, and the broader market rose on strength in 
technology issues. The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 
25.78, at 11,000.37 at just about the time President Clinton 
formally announced Rubin's resignation at a White House news 
conference. The resignation had been made known earlier in the day. 
The Dow opened slightly lower and then plunged as much as 213 
points after word of Rubin's resignation crossed news wires about 
20 minutes later. The Dow is just shy of its record high close of 
11,031.59, reached last Friday. The Nasdaq composite index rose 
39.83 to 2,606.51. 

</P>
