<P>
	Home Resale Prices Rise  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prices of existing homes rose in most  
metropolitan areas during the first three months of this year. 
Nationally, the median resale price was $131,600 during the 
January-March quarter, up 4.6 percent from the same quarter a year 
earlier, the National Association of Realtors said today. Low 
unemployment, rising incomes, continuing stock market gains, and 
low mortgage rates helped fuel an unprecedented home-buying boom 
last year. 

</P>
<P>
	FCC Airwaves Auction Fetches $45.1M  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Government licenses to provide telephone,  
television and Internet services via relatively new wireless 
technology fetched $45.1 million in an auction that ended today. 
All 161 licenses on the block were sold at the Federal 
Communications Commission to 40 companies in bidding that closed 
after 43 rounds. 

</P>
<P>
	SEC Targets Internet Fraud  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators have charged 18 people and  
eight companies with using the Internet to defraud investors, in a 
third nationwide ``sweep'' against online investment scams. The 
Securities and Exchange Commission announced the action, alleging 
that 14 separate schemes deceived investors around the world by 
selling bogus securities over the Internet. The allegedly 
fraudulent investments included interests in gold mines, computer 
software, prefabricated hospitals in Turkey and a product described 
as a new way of processing gold. The agency said its surveillance 
team discovered some questionable offerings before any securities 
were sold, preventing any potential investors from losing money. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: NYSE Brokers Under Probe  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Federal prosecutors and regulators are  
investigating dozens of New York Stock Exchange floor brokers who 
may have illegally shared profits with customers, The Wall Street 
Journal reported today. Eight brokers already face charges for 
improper trading. The U.S. Attorney's office said investigators 
have reason to believe 64 other brokers traded in accounts in which 
they shared customers' profits, possibly violating securities laws, 
people familiar with the letter told The Journal. Brokers are 
prohibited from trading with their own money. 

</P>
<P>
	Food Prices Not Likely To Fall  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Growers trying to eke out a living amid a  
lagging farm economy can expect low prices again this year for 
rice, soybeans and other crops. But consumers might not find lower 
prices for food products and other goods, industry analysts say. 
Joe Miller of the of the American Farm Bureau Federation. The 
retail industry, because of packaging and handling costs, doesn't 
tend to lower prices when the raw commodity prices fall apart. 

</P>
<P>
	NY Times News Services Chief Named  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Thomas K. Carley, director of business  
development for The New York Times News Services division, has been 
named president of the division, the company announced today. 
Carley will be responsible for the development and marketing of 
services that extend The Times's reach outside of the traditional 
newspaper, said Janet L. Robinson, president and general manager of 
The Times. 

</P>
<P>
	Star Wars Tickets Available  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Fans are lining up in force outside movie  
theaters around the country on the first day tickets are being sold 
for ``Star Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace.'' The film, a 
``prequel'' to George Lucas' hugely popular ``Star Wars'' trilogy, 
doesn't open until May 19. But some fans have been camping outside 
theaters for weeks to ensure they're among the first to see it. 
Movie house operators and independent ticket sellers were gearing 
up for an expected onslaught of thousands of fans seeking tickets. 
MovieFone, which sells tickets over the telephone and Internet, 
boosted its Web capacity to enable 10 times more people than usual 
to use its site, and increased its phone capacity by 30 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM Claims Disk Storage Record  
</P>
<P>
	ARMONK, N.Y. (AP) -- IBM Corp. announced today that it set a  
computer disk-drive storage record by packing 20 billion bits of 
data into a square inch, double the old record and more than three 
times that of any disk drive shipping today. The new level of 
density means every square inch of disk space could hold 2.5 
gigabytes, equivalent to two TV-quality movies or the text of some 
2,500 average-sized novels. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM, Nintendo in $1 Billion Deal  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- IBM Corp. will supply the processor for  
Nintendo's next-generation video game system, enabling the device 
to display more lifelike images. Nintendo Co. also said it will be 
developing its next game console in partnership with Japan's 
Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. Matsushita will provide digital 
video disc drives for the new Nintendo game machine, which will go 
on sale worldwide at the end of 2000. IBM will make a custom 
computer chip for the new console based on its PowerPC processor. 
Sega Enterprises will release its next-generation Dreamcast in the 
United States in September, while Sony Corp. is expected to release 
its PlayStation II in Japan this year and in the United States by 
Christmas 2000. IBM shares were at 225 1/2, up 4 1/2 

</P>
<P>
	Cox Is Buying TCA Cable  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Cox Communications Inc. is buying rival TCA Cable  
TV for about $3.3 billion in cash and stock in the latest 
combination in the cable television industry. Cox will add about 
883,000 TCA customers, nearly all in Texas, Arkansas and Louisiana, 
and will become the fourth largest cable company in the nation with 
about 5 million subscribers. Cox is also assuming $736 million in 
debt. AT&AMP;T Corp. and cable TV company MediaOne Group Inc. recently 
agreed to a deal. Cox shares were at 86 1/8, down 1 15/16. TCA Cable 
shares were at 60 1/32, up 7 31/32. 

</P>
<P>
	Broadcom Chip Speeds Data Delivery  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Communications technology maker Broadcom Corp.  
announced a chip that can deliver video, voice and data over 
conventional copper wire networks 10 times faster than current 
technology. The new chip will allow companies to continue using 
their existing copper wiring inside their offices while achieving 
more network speed and capacity. The development has been hotly 
anticipated in the networking world because of the difficulty of 
achieving ever-higher speeds over the copper wiring used inside 
most offices. 

</P>
