<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Web Hacked, Back online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Internet site for the White House reopened  
Wednesday, a day after officials took it down because of an attack 
by computer hackers. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said only that the Web site  
was made unavailable because of ``problems with people trying to 
get into the system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Security procedures provided a response to the incident, which  
included limiting public access to the system until an assessment 
could be made,'' Lockhart said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The opening page of the White House site was altered briefly  
overnight Sunday to show a black Web page with the names of the 
hacker organizations claiming responsibility, along with messages, 
``Your box was own3d'' and ``Stop all the war.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Why did we hack this domain? Simple, because we (expletive)  
could,'' the hackers wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	In hidden computer code contained within the page, they included  
the comments: ``OK, no real msg (message) here. Stop all the war no 
point for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	White House computers automatically detected the altered page  
and removed it within minutes. The Secret Service said it was 
investigating but declined further comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet publication AntiOnline said it had interviewed one  
of the hackers involved, who said the White House site was targeted 
``because it was easily exploitable ... and was pretty high 
profile.'' But he also denied there was any political motivation 
behind the effort. 
</P>
<P>
	AntiOnline said it was furnished with computer logs and other  
materials that verified that the hacker, who wasn't named, was 
responsible. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one of the two groups claiming responsibility is fairly  
well known within the loose-knit community of computer hackers but 
traditionally has targeted low-profile Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just so happened they stumbled onto a vulnerability in  
Whitehouse.Gov,'' said B.K. DeLong, a Boston computer consultant 
who said he also talked with one of the hackers involved. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the equivalent of stealing secretive government  
information,'' DeLong said. ``It's like spray-painting a federal 
building in downtown D.C.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 18:21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deal Spares NYC Gardens From Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Singer Bette Midler teamed with conservancy  
groups Wednesday to keep the city from auctioning off 115 
city-owned lots that residents had transformed from trash-strewn 
eyesores into lush gardens. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Midler contributed $250,000 of her own money and got others  
to put up $4 million more to buy all the gardens, said Roberta 
Greene, a spokeswoman for the New York Restoration Project. 
</P>
<P>
	The lots had been slated for sale Thursday, before Ms. Midler,  
the New York Restoration Project and the Trust for Public Land 
stepped in. Ms. Midler started the New York Restoration Project in 
1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're thrilled. This is a joyous occasion and means that these  
gardens will stay in perpetuity,'' Midler said in a statement. 
``Today, I'm prouder than ever to be a New Yorker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The community gardens began springing up in New York about 25  
years ago, when residents tired of the trash-strewn lots and 
illegal dumping grounds scattered around the city. They cleared out 
broken bottles and rusted-out cars, replacing them with pansies, 
petunias, collard greens and corn. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mayor Rudolph Giuliani decided that he wants the property  
back on the tax rolls and that the city shouldn't own so much land. 
</P>
<P>
	The gardeners first tried to prevent the auction, testifying at  
hearings and subjecting themselves to arrest at protests. One man 
dressed like a sunflower, climbed a tree outside City Hall and 
demanded a meeting with the mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	The gardens are as diverse as the gardeners, capturing  
neighborhood character. One in Queens was photographed recently for 
National Geographic; another in Harlem looks to yield vegetables 
this summer for meals at soup kitchens. 
</P>
<P>
	Olean For, a 78-year-old gardener who has worked her little  
community plot for more than 20 years, said her phone rang all 
evening with the news. She was too tired to attend the impromptu 
parties being thrown together because she has spent the last 
several months trying to save her endangered green space. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't you think they did it pretty good?'' she asked of the  
deal, adding that it will take some time to plan her own 
celebration. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Mayor Randy Levine called the sale a ``win-win for  
everybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is right in the area where we expected to be if this went  
to public auction,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
