<DOCNO> APW19990512.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 21:52:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Merrill Lynch Wins Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- Singapore's High Court has ordered former  
Merrill Lynch banker Kevin Wallace to repay more than $25 million 
to the company for manipulating its accounts, news reports said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge G.P. Selvam ruled Wednesday that he was ``more than  
satisfied'' that Wallace had breached his employment contract with 
the international investment bank by using the clients' accounts 
for his market manipulations, The Straits Times newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge dismissed Wallace's countercharge of $480,000, which  
he had claimed was compensation not paid to him when he was asked 
to leave the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace joined Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. in Singapore in 1990 as a  
financial consultant. The company fired Wallace in May 1997, saying 
he had violated certain rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace left Singapore and went to Hong Kong, where he was  
arrested and later charged with money laundering. Although he was 
released on bail, he wasn't allowed to leave Hong Kong for nine 
months until the money-laundering charges against him were dropped 
in March 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Wallace offered a settlement of $10 million to his  
former employer, but was rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace had refused to testify in Singapore, saying his family  
received threats that he would be harmed if he came here, the 
newspaper quoted Wallace's lawyer as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace reportedly offered to testify via video from the United  
States, but the judge rejected the offer. 



</P>
</TEXT>
