<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tornado Victims Search for Photos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIDWEST CITY, Okla. (AP) -- Chris Abbott couldn't stop crying  
Wednesday as she talked about the photograph she lost in a tornado. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a sonogram image taken by doctors who thought it would  
confirm an enormous ovarian cyst. Instead it revealed tiny hands 
and feet. It was the first picture to go in her son's baby book. 
</P>
<P>
	Although her son is safe, the scrapbook is gone. So Ms. Abbott  
and her husband, Terry Hardy, went to the First Christian Church, 
which is serving as a lost-and-found site for tornado victims 
searching for photographs and other lost keepsakes. 
</P>
<P>
	The family escaped death last week as tornadoes killed 43 people  
in Oklahoma and injured hundreds. But the statistics do not account 
for the thousands of sentimental treasures and precious keepsakes 
suddenly swept away. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Abbott's tears hit the floor as she remembered the sonogram.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's the start of us being a family,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's when we decided to be something,'' Hardy added softly  
at her side. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of photographs and other mementos scattered by the  
twisters had been delivered to the church, and more arrived 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Untold stories loom in the mud-caked images: A grinning girl  
cradles a newborn in her lap. Four bridesmaids in pink dresses 
stare soberly toward an unseen bride. A woman stands in fresh snow, 
dressed in a long black coat of another era. 
</P>
<P>
	Church member Shauna Becker didn't know what to expect when she  
posted fliers offering the church as a repository. But the 
28-year-old mother said she had to do something when a 1971 
photograph of a man posing with his car blew into her yard. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought, what if that is someone's dad?'' she said. ``What  
if that's the only picture they have of him?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The church will be open every Tuesday evening for tornado  
victims who want to see whether their treasured keepsakes are 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	On the first night, a man was reunited with his patch from the  
Vietnam War, and a family found a photo of a niece. A couple whose 
grandson died in the tornado recognized his baby photos on a 
television broadcast and picked them up Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Moore, another Oklahoma City suburb, 73-year-old Thelma  
Pruegert was still picking through the heap of furniture, lumber 
and cars tossed where her house once stood. She had recovered other 
people's photographs from the pile, but photos of her 16 
great-grandchildren remained missing, along with the wall where 
they hung. 
</P>
<P>
	Down the street, Barbara Sexton, 66, found her mother's wedding  
picture plastered against a wall. The rest of her photographs 
escaped damage inside an antique trunk. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was real happy,'' she said. ``That's our lives in there.''  
</P>
<P>
	At First Christian Church, Ms. Abbott and Hardy recalled how  
they and their son, George, were lifted in the air as a tornado 
mowed through their home. 
</P>
<P>
	They lost everything, but the photos were first on their minds.  
They had made a point of keeping everything from the sonogram photo 
to birthday shots for George, who turns 8 on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	They searched the remains of their home and found nothing, and  
so they went to the church, hopeful. 
</P>
<P>
	Has anyone turned in any scrapbooks, they asked? Their eyes fell  
when Ms. Becker told them no. 
</P>
<P>
	``But come back,'' she said. ``I'm sure things will be rolling  
in all week long.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
