<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRL Is Struggling With Image Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Three years after its first race, the Indy  
Racing League has yet to overcome its biggest problem -- the 
drivers' image. 
</P>
<P>
	Since that inaugural race in 1996, the IRL has suffered from the  
widespread belief that the best-known and most-talented drivers in 
American open-wheel racing are in Championship Auto Racing Teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Tired of such talk is defending Indianapolis 500 champion Eddie  
Cheever, preparing for the fourth Memorial Day weekend classic 
since Indy speedway owner and IRL founder Tony George split with 
CART. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheever maintains that there's been a drop-off in CART's driver  
recognition because of retirements and defections of former 
champions to Formula One. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, are CART stars Juan Montoya, Adrian Fernandez and  
Greg Moore more talented or more familiar to the public than Scott 
Goodyear, Jeff Ward and Cheever? 
</P>
<P>
	``That definitely is not the case,'' Cheever said. ``The fur on  
the back of my neck stands up when somebody says the quality of one 
driver is better than another just because they're racing in a 
different series. 
</P>
<P>
	``Saying that is like saying the drivers in NASCAR are a bunch  
of idiots, and that's not true. Every series has its better 
drivers, and those drivers are the ones that win races.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Comparing the talent of the two series is difficult because the  
drivers don't meet. Also, about half of CART's races are on road 
courses. The IRL runs exclusively on ovals. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it comes to the best open-wheel, oval-racing drivers in  
the States, they are in the Indy Racing League, because that is all 
they do,'' Cheever said. ``A lot of the drivers in our series, 
that's all they did beforehand. 
</P>
<P>
	``That goes back to what created Foyt and Rutherford and  
Parnelli Jones, all racing drivers that came from midget racing and 
dirt tracks and whatnot. So we've really just gone back to 
emulating what worked in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation on how well IRL drivers would fare on road courses  
is of no interest to Cheever. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's irrelevant, because that's not where they're racing,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	League spokesman Ron Green also sees little reason for all the  
CART-IRL talk. He thinks the IRL has an entertaining product and 
some topnotch competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``The quality of drivers that are entered for the 1999  
Indianapolis 500 is outstanding,'' Green said. ``One of the 
nation's hottest drivers, most popular drivers, Tony Stewart, is 
entered again this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, the 1997 IRL champ who's now the top rookie in NASCAR's  
Winston Cup series, will try for a share of racing lore. He'll 
attempt to become the second driver to race in the Indianapolis 500 
and the Coca-Cola 600, in Concord, N.C., in the same day. 
</P>
<P>
	Even without the attraction of Stewart, Green likes what he  
sees. But he isn't happy about what he hears about the IRL. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, when talk of the split was going on, the focus  
moved away from the drivers. There was very little attention on the 
drivers,'' Green said. ``It was all on the politics going on. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now you're seeing a re-emphasis on the drivers.''  
</P>
<P>
	CART president Andrew Craig refused to talk about the IRL or  
comparisons between the leagues. He did say he hopes they can 
eventually get back together. 
</P>
<P>
	While that might not happen anytime soon, at least the two sides  
seem content to be going their separate ways without hostility. 
</P>
<P>
	``The CART series is obviously more developed than the IRL  
series,'' IRL car owner John Menard said. ``But it's interesting. 
This whole thing is getting closer and closer to being more 
together on a more businesslike basis. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just wouldn't have dreamt of doing that a couple years  
ago. Everybody hated each other so badly.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
