<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UAW Leader Critical of 'Dead' Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The top official for the United Auto Workers  
criticized a major manufacturing proposal by General Motors Corp., 
setting an early tone for what could be contentious negotiations by 
the two sides when national contract talks get under way later this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, United Auto Workers president Stephen P. Yokich  
described GM's modular assembly plan as a ``dead'' issue, and said 
its chief advocate at GM should be fired. 
</P>
<P>
	Modular assembly, which GM is promoting as a way to drastically  
cut its manufacturing costs, would allow the auto giant to use 
fewer UAW workers and rely more on independent suppliers to put 
together major parts clusters, or modules. 
</P>
<P>
	During a briefing with reporters, Yokich and vice president  
Richard Shoemaker harshly criticized GM's small-car manufacturing 
chief, Mark Hogan, for comments he made about the company's modular 
assembly plans at a manufacturing conference Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hogan reported that GM had selected the suppliers for 15 major  
parts modules that will be used for its next generation of small 
cars. He made it clear that GM was moving ahead with plans to build 
modular plants in Lansing and Lordstown, Ohio, even though it 
expected UAW opposition to delay its progress. 
</P>
<P>
	To the secretive UAW, Hogan's public statements were an insult.  
Yokich is loath to discuss negotiating positions and issues in the 
press, and expects automakers to be equally circumspect. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they should fire Mark Hogan, quite frankly, because he  
just can't keep his mouth shut,'' Yokich said. ``If they can't fire 
him, they should put a muzzle on him. I hope he understands that, 
because he is not helping General Motors or the UAW when it comes 
to these negotiations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yokich, who described modular assembly as an attack on job  
security, implied after the briefing that the union won't give in 
to GM on the issue. He noted comments in March by GM president G. 
Richard Wagoner Jr. that modular assembly was not the only way to 
cut manufacturing costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the issue's dead,'' Yokich said. ``I don't think it's  
going to be a big issue in negotiations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GM said Hogan was unavailable for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	But GM spokesman Edd Snyder noted that Hogan also told the  
manufacturing conference that ``there is a positive role for the 
union in helping us work with our supply chain'' and that both 
sides were ``making progress toward a mutually beneficial 
solution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The triennial negotiations are scheduled to begin with the  
ceremonial handshakes June 14 at Ford Motor Co., June 15 with the 
Chrysler unit of DaimlerChrysler AG, and June 16 at GM. The talks 
do not typically move into high gear before late August; the 
current pacts expire Sept. 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Yokich insisted each company has ``serious issues'' to  
resolve with the UAW, most of the attention will be on GM's efforts 
to improve its long-contentious relationship with the union. 
</P>
<P>
	GM and the UAW also will have to sort out the employment terms  
for thousands of UAW workers at Delphi Automotive Systems Corp., 
the big parts maker that GM plans to spin off later this month. The 
UAW, which opposes the spinoff, expects Delphi workers will remain 
under GM's national agreement when the talks are completed, 
Shoemaker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yokich said job security will again be the major issue in the  
pending talks with all three automakers. The UAW has watched its 
ranks among the U.S. automakers steadily decline in the past decade 
as the automakers have become leaner and more efficient. At the 
same time, the union has failed to organize newer plants opened by 
Japanese and German automakers. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
