<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Nets To Move to Newark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- The New Jersey Nets have notified Gov.  
Christine Whitman that the basketball team will move to Newark by 
2003, the Star-Ledger reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Nets owners sent a letter to Whitman formally rejecting an offer  
to participate in a new sports complex planned for the Meadowlands, 
the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter said the Nets owners had ``reached a unanimous  
decision to work with the Newark group and build in Newark.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority, which runs  
Continental Airlines Arena and the rest of the Meadowlands complex, 
also received a copy of the letter, authority president Dennis 
Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nets officials including owners Ray Chambers, Stan Gale and Finn  
Wentworth and team president Michael Rowe met with Whitman on 
Tuesday in Princeton to discuss their plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Team officials said they anticipate raising $200 million in  
private investment to build an 18,500-seat arena in Newark by 2003. 
But they say about $100 million in public financing also will be 
necessary to fund improvements to roads and mass transit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Newark complex also may include a 30,000 seat stadium to  
house Major League Soccer's New York-New Jersey MetroStars. The 
soccer club, which plays at Giants Stadium, is mulling its own move 
to Elizabeth. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey Devils owner John McMullen has said his ice hockey  
club will not follow the Nets to Newark. McMullen prefers instead 
to build a waterfront arena in Hoboken. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority had hoped to  
attract both the Nets and Devils to a new sports and entertainment 
complex in the Meadowlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Continental Airlines Arena, formerly called Brendan Byrne Arena,  
was built in 1981. The Nets' lease runs through 2007, but an escape 
clause allows the team to move anywhere in New Jersey anytime 
without penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson said he is disappointed that the Nets and Devils could  
not agree on an arrangement that would keep them in the 
Meadowlands, an East Rutherford complex that also includes Giants 
Stadium and Meadowlands Racetrack. Robinson was not surprised by 
Tuesday's letter, however. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's consistent with what the Nets have been saying all  
along,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
