<DOCNO> APW19990512.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 12:25:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Would Halt Internet Gambling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bill that would put a stop to the Internet  
gambling by closing down ``virtual casino'' World Wide Web sites 
cleared a Senate subcommittee on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, sponsored by Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., would extend to  
the Internet federal law prohibiting gambling via telephone wire. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the bill, businesses offering gambling over the Internet,  
including interactive, pay-to-play casino-style games, would be 
fined an amount equal to the bets it received or $20,000, whichever 
is greater. Owners of the business could be imprisoned up to four 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike a similar measure that passed the Senate but not the  
House last year, Kyl's legislation would not impose penalties on 
individual bettors. But they would remain subject to any state 
penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet service providers would be required to cut off service  
to anyone making a gambling site available to U.S. customers, 
allowing law enforcement to reach gambling companies with 
headquarters outside the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate Judiciary subcommittee on technology, terrorism and  
government information passed the bill by a voice vote. 
</P>
<P>
	No companion bill has been introduced in the House, although  
several Republicans have said they plan to do so soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Kyl has denounced Internet gambling as an addictive and  
potentially corruptive activity that is breeding crime. Unlike 
other forms of gambling, it is virtually impossible to regulate, he 
said, and there is no sure way to keep minors from becoming 
involved. 
</P>
<P>
	A trade group has contended that Internet gambling is popular  
and can be regulated successfully. The Interactive Gaming Council 
is opposing the bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
