<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senator Criticizes FBI in Spy Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno defended the  
Justice Department refusing to let the FBI search the computer of a 
suspected nuclear weapons lab spy in 1997 as ``a close call'' 
justified by a lack of evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno's defense in a closed-door meeting Wednesday of the Senate  
Intelligence Committee left Republicans and Democrats still angry 
over the slow response by the FBI and Justice Department to an 
emerging espionage crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics contend a computer search would have turned up years  
earlier evidence emerging only last month that Los Alamos scientist 
Wen Ho Lee shifted thousands of classified atomic weapons codes to 
an unsecured computer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The diligence of the Justice Department and the FBI just was  
not there,'' said Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., the committee 
chairman. ``I don't think the country was well served.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., the committee vice chairman, said, ``We  
don't understand why a surveillance opportunity wasn't granted. If 
the Justice Department isn't at fault, then the process is at 
fault.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reno did not speak to reporters after the meeting but Shelby  
said she described the ruling by her department as ``a close call'' 
justified at the time by a lack of evidence that Lee was spying for 
China. 
</P>
<P>
	To this day, Lee has not been charged with a crime, although he  
was fired from his job at Los Alamos in March. He has repeatedly 
denied through his attorney that he was a spy or that he provided 
China with classified information. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI was not looking for the shifted computer files in 1996.  
But it was acting then on intelligence indicating that China had 
obtained classified information about the W-88, a sophisticated 
U.S. nuclear warhead. Lee had worked on the W-88 program and had 
traveled to China, two facts that put him under suspicion. 
</P>
<P>
	The Department of Energy offered to search Lee's computer under  
internal guidelines permitting such searches for security purposes. 
The FBI, however, was concerned that if such a search turned up 
evidence it might be thrown out in court and could endanger a 
prosecution of Lee. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the FBI's general counsel and the Justice Department agreed  
that a search warrant granted by a secret federal court under the 
Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act would be required. The FBI 
applied, but in 1997 Justice ruled that there was not enough 
evidence against Lee and decided against seeking the warrant from 
the secret court. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, called the two-year delay in  
searching Lee's computer ``a classic case of bureaucratic 
bungling.'' Even if such a search jeopardized possible prosecution, 
it should have been conducted to help prevent additional losses of 
secrets, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can't convict, we can sure stop the process,'' Murkowski  
said. The Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee he chairs 
heard from Justice and FBI officials earlier Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	An FBI search in 1996 or 1997 may have made little difference.  
Lee had transferred the classified weapons codes over a 12-year 
period ending in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Anne Sullivan, the Energy Department's general counsel,  
said that Los Alamos lab managers twice had offered to search Lee's 
computer. 
</P>
<P>
	If the department proceeded with the search over the FBI's  
objections, Sullivan said, ``we would have subjected ourselves to 
another criticism. That we compromised their ability to conduct an 
investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., said Congress should make it clear  
there are certain times when national security is at issue that 
such a search of a government computer will not taint evidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
