<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Won't Meet WTO Beef Ban Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Union will formally notify  
the World Trade Organization that it does not intend to meet the 
Thursday deadline for lifting a ban on hormone treated beef 
imports. 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO has ruled the EU's 10-year-old ban on imports of  
hormone-treated beef is illegal and set the deadline for the 
15-nation bloc to lift the ban. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has threatened to impose $900 million in  
sanctions on EU goods if the ban is not lifted. Canada has also 
issued a list of proposed EU goods for possible retaliatory 
sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	Nigel Gardner, trade spokesman for the European Commission, said  
the EU plans to send a letter Thursday to the WTO's Dispute 
Settlement Body stating that the ban will remain in place. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at WTO headquarters in Geneva said the issue will be  
on the agenda when the dispute panel meets May 26. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commission says it won't lift the ban because studies  
carried out by European scientists indicate possible human health 
risks posed by six growth-promoting hormones used by beef farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the EU is waiting for final results on 17 other  
scientific studies before it can consider changing its position on 
beef hormones. Those studies won't be ready until late this year or 
early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Gardner said negotiations were continuing with the United States  
on a compensation proposal for U.S. cattle farmers that would head 
off the threat of sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're talking with the Americans,'' Gardner told reporters.  
``We want to continue the dialogue on compensation and the 
scientific evidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	EU Trade Commissioner Leon Brittan met with U.S. Trade  
Representative Charlene Barshefsky Wednesday in Tokyo, but the two 
sides didn't reach an agreement on beef hormones. Barshefsky said 
the U.S. reserves its right to seek WTO authorization for imposing 
sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will not drop our plan,'' she said, adding, ``We intend to  
avail ourselves of our WTO rights and seek authorization to 
retaliate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. cattle industry says that the ban cost them about $250  
million a year in lost sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
