<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Protest Affecting US Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- Recovery in China will be arduous for  
Kentucky Fried Chicken. After it rebuilds restaurants wrecked by 
rampaging protesters, it faces a new threat: calls for Chinese to 
boycott the Colonel's chicken. 
</P>
<P>
	Protesters enraged at the NATO bombing of China's embassy in  
Yugoslavia want Chinese to shun everything American, from KFC and 
Coca Cola to Motorola mobile phones. 
</P>
<P>
	``We definitely will see in the short term, maybe one to two  
months, our sales will fall. How much, we don't know,'' said Tony 
Chen, a spokesman for Tricom Global Restaurants Ltd., which owns 
310 KFC restaurants in China. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese leaders say foreigners are welcome and safe, but at  
least for now the boycott threats, security alerts and the echo of 
anti-American chants have changed the atmosphere for U.S. 
businesses in China. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies say long-term plans will not be affected by the events  
of this week -- when Chinese leaders encouraged protesters to stone 
the U.S. Embassy in Beijing. But many canceled their executives' 
trips to China or told American employees to stay at home. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest change could be in attitude among customers and  
business contacts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have seen among the Chinese almost a love affair with  
things American, and it's not clear whether that will continue. 
People are less enthralled,'' said Michael Furst, executive 
director of the American Chamber of Commerce in China. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese leaders have tried to reach out to foreign investors  
amidst the din of protests that equated Americans with Nazi 
Germany. In Shanghai, Mayor Xu Kuangdi visited General Motors Corp. 
and other companies Tuesday to reassure them, said Lawrence B. 
Zahner Jr., president of GM China. 
</P>
<P>
	American companies say they accept those assurances.  
</P>
<P>
	Boeing Co. denied rumors that it was evacuating some of the 100  
Americans working in its 18 offices in China. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought everyone would take advantage of this to stay home,  
but it's been business as usual,'' said Tom McLean, a spokesman for 
the aircraft maker. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. presence is vital to China, which relies on foreign  
companies for jobs and investment at a time of slowing growth and 
massive restructuring of state industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Kentucky Fried Chicken alone employs 23,500 people in China.  
</P>
<P>
	And U.S. business is one of Beijing's best friends, lobbying in  
Washington against trade sanctions and in favor of World Trade 
Organization membership for China. 
</P>
<P>
	But even basic precautions will force companies to postpone  
high-level meetings and crimp other activities. 
</P>
<P>
	British Petroleum has told its 20 British and American employees  
in China to avoid public events and others to put off trips from 
abroad, said Jeremy Yao, general manager of BP's Shanghai office. 
</P>
<P>
	And companies like Kentucky Fried Chicken and McDonald's, with  
far-flung restaurant networks spread across China, are hard to 
protect. KFC's signature Colonel Sanders statues were smashed this 
week outside dozens of restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to open our doors everyday for customers. A company  
like GM, General Electric or Motorola has much more flexibility,'' 
Chen said. 
</P>
<P>
	The protests come at a time when economic reformers led by  
Premier Zhu Rongji are struggling with hardliners who oppose the 
broad concessions Zhu offered the United States last month for WTO 
membership. 
</P>
<P>
	The scale and intensity of protests in some 20 Chinese cities  
could boost the premier's opponents, said Zhu Nongfei of the 
consulting firm A.T. Kearney. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before the protests, a string of surprise events had made  
companies more wary about possible political shifts on WTO and 
other issues, said Bob Broadfoot of the Political and Economic Risk 
Consultancy in Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	They included the January collapse of a major investment trust  
and an extraordinary silent protest in central Beijing last month 
by as many as 30,000 members of a martial arts group. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's going to be greater caution on the part of both  
Chinese and the foreign companies about when China is going to get 
into WTO. That has a really big impact,'' Broadfoot said. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign companies are watching for a long-term political  
backlash. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't see any impact right now, but it's still too soon to  
know for sure,'' said Brian Zhou, a spokesman in Beijing for the 
U.S. computer chip maker Intel Corp. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 05:55:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Bre-X Executive Charged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Ontario's stock market watchdog has charged  
former Bre-X Minerals Ltd. vice-chairman John Felderhof with 
violating the province's securities laws relating to the 1997 
Busang gold mining scandal in Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ontario Securities Commission announced late Tuesday it has  
filed eight charges against Felderhof, accusing the longtime mining 
industry executive of insider trading and other violations of 
provincial securities laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Commission spokesman Mark Conacher said the charges came after  
an exhaustive investigation which involved the analysis of more 
than 200,000 stock market transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took until now to conclude that offenses had been  
committed, in our view, and that the evidence supports that,'' 
Conacher said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	The Royal Canadian Mounted Police is also investigating  
Felderhof for possible violations of Canada's Criminal Code. 
</P>
<P>
	The long-time geologist is believed to have been holed up at his  
Cayman Islands estate since the Bre-X meltdown, which wiped $4.1 
billion in stock market value off the company's books and led to 
numerous lawsuits by disgruntled investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Busang site in Indonesia was once touted as one of the  
biggest gold discoveries in history. Bre-X Minerals shares, which 
started out worth 21 cents apiece on the junior Alberta Stock 
Exchange, became an instant heavyweight on the prestigious Toronto 
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	But after seeing its stock price rise to more than $137 a share,  
the Calgary-based exploration company collapsed after an 
investigation proved its Indonesian gold property was a fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission alleges that between April 24, 1996 and September  
10, 1996 Felderhof was involved in insider trading of more than 2.7 
million shares of Bre-X for about $57.5 million ``with knowledge of 
a material fact pertaining to rights of Bre-X in relation to the 
Busang properties that had not been generally disclosed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A further four counts allege that between June 20, 1996 and Feb.  
17, 1997 Felderhof ``authorized, permitted or acquiesced'' in Bre-X 
issuing misleading or untrue press releases about the amount of 
gold at Busang. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission said Tuesday that as a strict liability offense,  
it's not necessary to prove whether Felderhof knew at the time that 
the gold estimates were false. 
</P>
<P>
	``The issue, for the commission, is not whether or not he knew  
that the resource calculations were misleading or untrue,'' said 
Conacher. ``But given his position with the company, it's his 
responsibility to establish that they were not misleading or 
untrue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bre-X shares crashed after the scandal and the stock was again  
worth pennies before the company was pushed into bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	A subsequent investigation showed stellar drilling results were  
fabricated by Bre-X's chief geologist Michael de Guzman and his 
associates in Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	De Guzman later died -- authorities concluded he committed  
suicide -- after falling from a company helicopter over the 
Indonesian jungle. Bre-X chairman David Walsh, a Calgary mining 
promoter, died almost a year ago of an aneurysm at his Bahamian 
estate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ontario commission said Felderhof, or his lawyer, will be  
required to appear before the Ontario Court of Justice on June 15 
to answer the charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
