<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 16:14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lukas' Colts Draw Good at Preakness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The luck of draw was with trainer D. Wayne  
Lukas on Wednesday for his Kentucky Derby winner Charismatic and 
third-place Cat Thief. Trainer Bob Baffert's sensational filly 
Silverbulletday's outside post might keep her out of the Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert's other filly, Excellent Meeting, fifth in the Derby,  
will definitely be in the full field of 14 3-year-olds Saturday at 
Pimlico. It's only the eighth time in the 124-year history that 
there's been at least 14 starters. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll mull it over tonight, (Mike) Pegram and I,'' Baffert  
said of whether Silverbulletday, winner of 10 of 11 starts, will 
start in the Preakness. ``We're disappointed, really, you know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert said if Silverbulletday had drawn No. 1 or from No. 4  
through 10, she definitely would start. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert picking No. 13 could have had that post position for the  
filly, but he and Carl Nafzger, picking 14th for 18th-place Derby 
finisher Vicar, decided to have a little fun. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to make this interesting,'' Baffert said. ``We're  
going to flip a coin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nafzger called ``heads,'' won and picked No. 13.  
</P>
<P>
	Asked whose idea it was for the coin toss, Nafzger said,  
``Bob's. I ain't that smart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert picked No. 7 for Excellent Meeting, who broke from No. 5  
in the Derby and had what he called an horrendous trip. 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas chose No. 6 for Charismatic, who won from No. 16 in the  
Derby, and took No. 3 for Cat Thief, who left from No. 10 in the 
Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're delighted,'' Lukas said. ``Things are falling in  
place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic was made the early 6-1 fourth choice behind Derby  
runnerup Menifee (5-2), Silverbulletday (7-2) and Excellent Meeting 
(5-1). 
</P>
<P>
	``I know the story all week will be he's a claimer (he ran for a  
$62,500 tag Feb. 11) and everything went his way in the Derby,'' 
Lukas said earlier Wednesday. ``Don't discredit the horse because I 
was foolish enough to run him in a claiming race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee broke from the No. 18 post in the 19-horse Derby, was  
12th with a quarter-mile remaining, then just missed catching 
Charismatic by a neck. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten Derby starters are in the Preakness, the most ever in the 1  
3-16-mile Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	The other Derby veterans are sixth-place Kimberlite Pipe (No. 2  
post), seventh-place Worldly Manner (No. 10), 14th-place Stephen 
Got Even (No. 11), 15th-place Valhol (No. 12) and 17th-place Adonis 
(No. 9). 
</P>
<P>
	No jockey was named by trainer Nick Zito for Stephen Got Even,  
winner of the Gallery Furniture.com Stakes and second Derby 
favorite behind the entry of fourth-place Prime Timber and 
Excellent Meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris McCarron was supposed to ride the colt, but suffered a  
hairline fracture near his left heel when he was unseated during a 
workout Monday at Hollywood Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday or Excellent Meeting could become the fifth  
filly to win the Preakness and the first since Nellie Morse won 
from the No. 15 post in 1924. The last time there was more than one 
filly in the race was when three started in 1921. 
</P>
<P>
	The last Preakness winner not to have raced in the Derby was  
Deputed Testamony in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	The other Preakness starters who missed the Derby would be  
Patience Game (post 8), winner of the 1-mile Derby Trial April 24 
at Churchill Downs; Torrid Sand (No. 1), third in the 1 1/8-mile 
Arkansas Derby in his stakes debut April 10, and Badge (No. 4), 
winner of the one-mile Gotham and fourth in the Wood Memorial April 
10 in his last two starts. 
</P>
<P>
	While Stephen Got Even, Adonis and Valhol were already at  
Pimlico, the other 11 didn't arrive until Wednesday. Badge vanned 
in from New York and the others came in two flights from 
Louisville. 
</P>
<P>
	The first off the first van from the airport was Charismatic,  
who was greeted by owners Bob and Beverly Lewis, owners of the 
Baffert-trained Silver Charm, winner of the 1997 Kentucky Derby and 
Preakness. Bob Lewis was 75 on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
