<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Director Assails U.S., NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANNES, France (AP) -- It didn't even take a full day for the  
conflict in Kosovo to take center stage at the Cannes Film 
Festival. 
</P>
<P>
	Nikita Mikhalkov, the Oscar-winning Russian director of the  
festival's opening film, used his platform Wednesday to castigate 
NATO and especially the United States over the airstrikes on 
Serbia. 
</P>
<P>
	``The NATO action is a tragic, tragic error,'' Mikhalkov,  
director of ``The Barber of Siberia,'' told a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	War, he added, is not a video game, describing NATO pilots  
pushing buttons -- like a game -- as they fired their missiles. 
</P>
<P>
	``After 10 seconds, the plane goes back to its base,'' Mikhalkov  
said. ``The missiles are still falling. What happens on the ground, 
the pilot doesn't know. Maybe the bomb has hit the Chinese 
Embassy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many of those giving orders, he added, ``don't know what they're  
fighting for -- they don't know the difference between a Serb, a 
Croat and a Kosovar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mikhalkov, 53, considered a Russian nationalist, won an Oscar  
for best foreign-language film in 1995 with ``Burnt By the Sun,'' a 
story of Stalinist repression told through one family's 
experiences. 
</P>
<P>
	The son of the author of the Soviet anthem, Mikhalkov was a  
successful director in Soviet times and managed to maintain his 
popularity after the 1991 collapse of the Soviet regime. 
</P>
<P>
	He is known for his fierce patriotism, and has often said  
post-Soviet Russia lacks a ``national idea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mikhalkov spent 10 years making ``The Barber of Siberia.'' The  
film, being shown out of competition, is a lavish period drama in 
which the director himself plays Czar Alexander III. 
</P>
<P>
	Starring British actress Julia Ormond and Russian star Oleg  
Menshikov, it premiered in February at the Kremlin to an audience 
of 5,000 that included starlets, Cabinet ministers and tycoons. 
</P>
<P>
	It recounts a romance between a Russian cadet and an American  
woman who comes to Russia on behalf of an entrepreneur who wants to 
develop a logging device for Siberia. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, director Mikhalkov chided a journalist who  
suggested that the film's first half, which is lighthearted, was 
less realistic in portraying Russia than its second half, which 
veers into tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``You are a victim of your impression of life in Russia,'' he  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
