<DOCNO> APW19990512.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 15:24:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pro Sports Becoming Flea Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Don't look now, but the world of sports is turning into one big  
flea market, where just about anything is liable to be for sale at 
any given moment. 
</P>
<P>
	Want a franchise? There are plenty around. Want a stadium? Those  
are available, too. 
</P>
<P>
	There's a dizzying scramble of owners buying, selling or moving  
teams almost daily. 
</P>
<P>
	Start with the bankrupt Pittsburgh Penguins, swimming through a  
sea of bookkeeping red ink but doing very well, thank you, in the 
second round of the Stanley Cup playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins could win the Stanley Cup and have no place to  
display it because they may be moving out of town. Seattle 
billionaire Paul Allen, who also owns the NFL's Seattle Seahawks 
and NBA's Portland Trail Blazers reportedly is interested in buying 
the team for $85 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Want to buy an NHL team and move it? Hey, no problem. In this  
decade, Hartford went to Carolina, Quebec to Colorado, Winnipeg to 
Phoenix and Minnesota to Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	Want to buy a NHL team and forget about it? That's happened,  
too. The New York Islanders were sold a year ago to a group that 
included Howard Milstein, who then proceeded to ignore them and 
throw all his energy into trying to buy the NFL Washington 
Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
	That deal fell through because the package contained too much  
debt and not enough equity to suit NFL owners. They're set instead 
to approve the $800 million sale later this month to a group headed 
by Daniel Snyder. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Abe Pollin said he was selling the NHL's  
Washington Capitals and his minority interests in the NBA's 
Washington Wizards and the MCI Center to America Online executive 
Ted Leonsis. The 75-year-old Pollin said he decided to sell after 
his sons told him they had no interest in taking over his business. 
</P>
<P>
	Across town in the nation's capital, D.C. United of Major League  
Soccer is also on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	That means the most stable franchise in Washington right now is  
the WNBA's Mystics, who have been in existence only one year. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost as soon as Milstein and his partners bought the  
Islanders, their opening marketing ploy was to declare the Nassau 
Coliseum a dump and abandon the building until repairs were made. 
That issue remains in litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Over in New Jersey, they're planning a new sports complex for  
the Meadowlands. There's some question, though, who will be playing 
there. The NBA Nets have decided their future will be in Newark, 
and the NHL Devils want to move to Hoboken. 
</P>
<P>
	Hartford, which lost its hockey team to Carolina, thought it had  
a replacement franchise when it lured the NFL New England Patriots 
with a sweetheart stadium deal late last year. That went up in 
smoke last month with the Pats deciding to stay in Massachusetts in 
a new stadium that hopefully will afford better access to 
one-lane-in, one-lane-out Foxboro. 
</P>
<P>
	With the death last week of New York Jets owner Leon Hess, that  
franchise is likely to be on the market. Hess made it clear that he 
didn't want to burden his heirs with running a football team, 
perhaps after watching the legal tug-of-war going on in San 
Francisco between Ed DeBartolo and his sister, Denise. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the NFL has committed to placing its 32nd franchise  
in Los Angeles on the site of the old Coliseum, but don't ask more 
than that. An ownership group is to be selected by Sept. 15 with 
Houston still in the wings, hoping a resolution is not found and 
the franchise winds up in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Major league baseball hasn't had a franchise move since 1971,  
when the Senators left Washington -- that town again -- for Texas. 
But that track record may change soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Montreal keeps developing players for other franchises while  
operating on a shoestring, waiting for a new stadium and settlement 
of ownership issues. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of owners led by team chairman Jacques Menard is trying  
to buy out shares in the team controlled by general partner Claude 
Brochu and attempting to restart a stalled stadium project, which 
is seen as essential to keeping the Expos in Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	The future is cloudy as well for the Minnesota Twins and perhaps  
the Oakland A's. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is that except for a handful of people, sports  
teams are viewed as hobbies by the rich who do it for five or 10 
years and then sell,'' said Stanford economics professor Roger 
Noll. 
</P>
<P>
	Noll believes all the franchise turmoil is nothing new.  
</P>
<P>
	``This has been going on for several years,'' he said. ``The  
movement and frequency of sales were high in the '60s and '70s. 
It's not as big a tax advantage now as it used to be. 
</P>
<P>
	``The financial stakes have become so high with cities willing  
to pay hundreds of millions of dollars to lure teams or keep them 
that it's hard not to shop it around. Even if a team stays, it gets 
a better deal,'' he said. ``It's worth $100 million at least to 
just create the illusion that you're mobile.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ever increasing payrolls may also have taken the  
profitability out of it for some owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans in Kansas City have had their fill of the low budget Royals  
trying to compete with big bucks clubs, and they staged a protest 
last week when the New York Yankees came to town. 
</P>
<P>
	They waved dollar bills at the players and turned their backs on  
the action, leaving the visiting millionaires a bit befuddled but 
nevertheless amused. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
