<HEADLINE> Willey Knows Man Who Scared Her </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Kathleen Willey says she knows the identity of  
a man who allegedly threatened her and that prosecutor Kenneth 
Starr's office is investigating the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing Tuesday night on CNBC's ``Hardball'' program, Mrs.  
Willey told interviewer Chris Matthews that Starr's office had 
asked her not to reveal the identity of the man who she says 
approached her two days before she testified against President 
Clinton in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are investigating this,'' Mrs. Willey said of Starr's  
prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week at the trial of one-time friend Julie Hiatt Steele,  
Mrs. Willey said she had been frightened by an encounter in January 
1998 with a stranger who knew that her cat was missing and her car 
tires had been slashed. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey said that when she asked the man how he knew these  
things, he made a comment leading her to believe he was referring 
to her imminent testimony about the president. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was meant to scare me,'' Mrs. Willey said of the man's  
approach. 
</P>
<P>
	Two days after the incident, Mrs. Willey testified about  
Clinton's allegedly unwanted sexual advance in the Oval Office. 
</P>
