<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Food Maker To Cut 7,000 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Foods giant ConAgra Inc. said today it will  
cut 7,000 jobs and close at least 15 production plants to reduce 
expenses and concentrate on selling its major food brands and other 
products. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, whose brands include Healthy Choice, La Choy and  
Butterball, also will close at least 70 storage, distribution and 
smaller processing facilities and shed about 20 small non-core 
businesses. Specific plant and business closings will not be 
identified until employees are notified, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling the restructuring plan ``Operation Overdrive,'' the  
company wants its 80 independent operating companies to work more 
closely together, sharing sales tasks and buying products from each 
other, said spokeswoman Lynn Phares. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also wants to meet its longstanding goal of annual  
14 percent per share revenue growth. Last year, per share revenue 
grew 1.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the job cuts, including about 4,000 to be announced by  
May 30, will take place in the next few months, with others coming 
more than a year away, Ms. Phares said. The majority of workers 
probably will be laid off, she said, though some could find new 
jobs within the company. 
</P>
<P>
	The moves will mean a pretax charge of $810 million over three  
years, starting with $420 million in fiscal year 1999's fourth 
quarter ending May 30, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a couple years since they had much growth,'' said  
analyst David Nelson of CS First Boston. ``I think these are moves 
they're taking to maintain the growth they've had in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ConAgra, which owns businesses ranging from flour milling to  
frozen foods, said it wants to focus on more efficiently selling 
all its products, including beef and prepared foods to restaurants 
and its branded foods in grocery stores. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fair to say this is a company wide effort,'' Ms. Phares  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also will invest about $200 million and create new  
jobs over the next two years to get full value from its 
consolidation, said Bruce Rohde, chairman and chief executive 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Phares said the effort announced Wednesday is broader than a  
1996 restructuring that eliminated 6,300 jobs and overhauled 29 
plants, because it involves the way ConAgra's businesses work 
together. 
</P>
<P>
	Based in Omaha, ConAgra employs 83,000 people at about 250  
production plants and 1,150 total locations. Its net income last 
year was $613.2 million, compared with $615 million the year 
before. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
