<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mob, Stock Boost Trial Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The chairman of an Arizona company who was  
accused of paying mob-linked stock promoters to boost his company's 
stock was convicted of racketeering Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury verdict in U.S. District Court in Manhattan came four  
months after four reputed mobsters pleaded guilty to charges in the 
case, the largest prosecution ever to involve members of organized 
crime manipulating the stock market. Ten other people also had 
pleaded guilty. Four await trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's verdict came against Gordon Hall, the 45-year-old  
chairman and chief executive officer of HealthTech International 
Inc., a Mesa, Ariz., operator of health and fitness centers. 
</P>
<P>
	Also convicted was Michael Motsykulashvili, who helped run two  
branch offices of Meyers Pollock &AMP; Robbins Inc., a brokerage firm. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no comment. Have a nice day,'' Hall said politely as he  
stood outside court after the verdict was announced. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall was accused of arranging to pay off stock promoters who  
then bribed stockbrokers to drive up the value of his company's 
stock by aggressively promoting it to their customers. 
</P>
<P>
	James McGuire, Hall's lawyer, had told the jury his client was  
victimized by mob-tainted promoters he met in December 1996. 
McGuire said the promoters never told Hall they had mob ties when 
he signed a consulting agreement with them. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors relied in part on the results of court-ordered tape  
recordings of conversations between Hall and the stock promoters. 
</P>
<P>
	A key prosecution witness in the case was Irwin Norman  
Schneider, a disbarred securities lawyer who testified that he and 
Eugene Lombardo, a Bonanno organized crime family associate, paid 
off brokers to boost the value of HealthTech. 
</P>
<P>
	Schneider, who pleaded guilty in March to conspiring to violate  
securities laws, had suggested that sometimes the line between 
legitimate compensation for promotional services by a brokerage and 
the payment of bribes was blurry, noting: ``Some were perfectly 
proper. Others were not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lombardo pleaded guilty in January along with three others with  
alleged mob connections. 
</P>
<P>
	Lombardo said during his plea that the mob tried to extend its  
influence over Wall Street by inserting its own people as brokers 
at Meyers Pollock. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had even threatened to use force to remove a Meyers  
Pollock employee who was preventing people backed by the mob from 
being hired. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
