<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Trainers Barred for Violations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) -- The leading trainer at Freehold Raceway  
and a trainer he allegedly employed were suspended for the rest of 
the year by the track's judges on Wednesday for conduct detrimental 
to harness racing. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Krajczewski, 33, of Hopatcong, and Carl Rafanelli, 34, of  
Brick, were cited for conspiracy, fraud and other violations. A 
judge fined them $500 apiece and placed them on probation for next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The trainers were cited for violations in two races, including  
one on March 10 that led the suspension of George Brennan, the 
nation's leading driver at the time, and two other drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	In an action independent of the judges, Krajczewski and  
Rafanelli were also barred indefinitely from Freehold Raceway and 
Garden State Park in Cherry Hill by Richard Orbann, the president 
of both private tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfortunate that such measures have to be taken, but we  
are intent on fulfilling our obligation to protect our fans and the 
integrity of our sport. We will not tolerate any form of wrongdoing 
ever,'' Orbann said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Krajczewski, who leads the current trainers' standings with 32  
winners, was employing Rafanelli when the two twice had horses in 
the same race, according to the judges' ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	In the third race of March 10, each entered horses as separate  
wagering entities, even though they should have been coupled 
because of Krajczewski's and Rafanelli's employer-employee 
relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	Krajczewski's horse, My Dream Come True, finished last.  
Rafanelli's The Shawnster was second. 
</P>
<P>
	The March 10 race is the same one that led to the exclusion and  
suspensions of Brennan, James Morrill Jr. and Howard Parker for 
unsatisfactory drives. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan, who drove My Dream Come True, has maintained he did  
nothing wrong in the race, adding he was only following 
instructions given by Krajczewski. 
</P>
<P>
	An investigation found questionable betting in the race. A  
chauffeur for Parker won $24,000 in exacta and trifecta wagers, 
investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	Krajczewski and Rafanelli raced the same two horses as separate  
entities on Feb. 26. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
