<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Claims Disk Storage Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARMONK, N.Y. (AP) -- IBM Corp. announced today that it set a  
computer disk-drive storage record by packing 20 billion bits of 
data into a square inch, more than three times that of any disk 
drive shipping today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Armonk-based company said the advances came from researchers  
at its Almaden Research Center in San Jose, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The new level of density means every square inch of disk space  
could hold 2.5 gigabytes, equivalent to two TV-quality movies or 
the text of some 2,500 average-sized novels. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM said increasing data density could lead to disk drives that  
are lighter and consume less energy. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM's previous record storage level was 10 billion bits per  
square inch, announced in December of 1997. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
