<DOCNO> APW19990512.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 15:21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Star Wars Tickets Available </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- For Javier Sanchez, it was fate as much as  
the Force that led him to the long line of devotees camping outside 
Mann's Chinese Theatre to get tickets to ``Star Wars: Episode I -- 
The Phantom Menace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A week ago, the 15-year-old high school student and longtime  
``Star Wars'' enthusiast happened to see the cluster of fans 
outside the famous movie house. 
</P>
<P>
	``I decided I wanted to be out here with them,'' said Sanchez,  
whose love of the films began at age 9 when he saw ``Return of the 
Jedi.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanchez and others are getting their chance to buy tickets today  
when advance sales for ``Phantom Menace'' begin at 3 p.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	``Phantom Menace'' doesn't open until May 19. But some fans have  
been camping outside Southern California theaters for weeks to 
ensure they're among the first to see the long-awaited prequel to 
George Lucas' ``Star Wars'' trilogy. This morning, the line was a 
block long. 
</P>
<P>
	People also were in line today at theaters around the country.  
</P>
<P>
	The film picks up the ``Star Wars'' fable a generation before  
hero Luke Skywalker comes of age, tracing how his father Anakin 
Skywalker becomes the evil, black-masked Darth Vader, who later 
leads Empire forces against the Rebels in a battle for galactic 
control. 
</P>
<P>
	As sale time neared, theater operators and independent ticket  
sellers were gearing up for an expected onslaught of thousands of 
fans seeking tickets at theater box offices, over the Internet and 
by telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	MovieFone, which sells tickets over the telephone and Internet,  
boosted its Web capacity to enable 10 times more people than usual 
to use its site, and increased its phone capacity by 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this case, everyone's going to start coming after tickets  
at the same point in time,'' said Andrew Jarecki, the company's 
chief executive. ``That presents a challenge to us, but it's one we 
think we can handle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Loews, Mann Theatres and Edwards Cinemas were among the theater  
operators planning to sell in advance by telephone or at the box 
office at most theaters. 
</P>
<P>
	But Columbus, Ga.-based Carmike Cinemas Inc., elected to stick  
with its policy of not selling tickets in advance and even had to 
shoo away one fan who set up camp outside a theater. The chain has 
theaters in 36 states. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Carmike expects strong sales. ``It's going to be one of  
the fastest-grossing movies of all time,'' said Philip Smitley, a 
company spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Regal Cinemas, the world's largest movie chain, reported people  
lined up Tuesday outside theaters in San Antonio, Las Vegas, 
Cleveland, Philadelphia and Portland, Ore. Regal is showing Star 
Wars at 260 of its 411 theaters. 
</P>
<P>
	Some theater operators were standing in their own line of sorts.  
Studio executives on Tuesday still were negotiating sales with some 
chains, said Tom Sherak, head of 20th Century's domestic film 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue for most, Sherak said, were stipulations that the movie  
remain in theaters for a set period of time, ranging from two weeks 
to 12 weeks, depending on the location and time of opening. 
</P>
<P>
	Sherak expected ``Star Wars'' to open on 2,800 to 3,000 screens  
nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's sales won't end the vigil for some fans. Sanchez, for  
instance, plans to stay in line as part of a promotion that could 
land him a choice seat when the film finally hits the screen. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
