<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unions Have Little Say in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- By the time Tang Sin-hing joined the union, he  
had driven loaded container trucks an average 17 hours a day, six 
days a week all over Hong Kong for five years. 
</P>
<P>
	With 25 deliveries each week, it was hard for Tang to find time  
to spend with his unemployed wife and two daughters. But driving 
was his passion and he wanted to stay on -- even if relations with 
his bosses were beginning to chafe. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to talk to them about the long hours and a salary  
increase,'' said Tang. ``But they didn't take me seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the company tried to cut workers' pay 37 percent, Tang and  
about 40 other drivers formed a union. They negotiated with 
management for shorter working hours, medical benefits, and holiday 
allowances. 
</P>
<P>
	But Tang found out that being in a union can carry a price in  
Hong Kong, and he soon lost his job. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the company's word was final. Tang came away  
thinking that Hong Kong labor laws offer little to unionists, a 
lesson more people are learning amid the territory's long and deep 
recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the law here, employees can organize into unions, but they  
have no collective bargaining rights. In other words, unions can 
operate, but management can choose to ignore them. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you don't want to put up with it, you can always get out,''  
Tang said. ``But the management will always get someone cheaper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tang claimed he was fired to weaken the union, but his former  
employer, Orient Overseas Container Co., said that ``over an 
extended period of time he did not meet basic performance 
criteria.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike countries such as South Korea or the Philippines, known  
for their active and influential trade unions, Hong Kong's 
hyperactive economy for decades kept jobs abundant and unions 
docile. 
</P>
<P>
	But as companies cut back on salaries to maintain profitability  
in the fallout from Asia's economic crisis, more workers are 
turning to Hong Kong's 538 unions for help. In the past two years, 
more than 23,500 people have joined unions, which now claim 22 
percent of Hong Kong's 2.95 million workers as members. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven new unions have formed in the last six months and applied  
for membership in the Hong Kong Confederation of Trade Unions, an 
umbrella group representing 140,000 workers, says Lee Cheuk-yan, 
legislator and secretary-general of the confederation. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee has repeatedly called for legislation to establish  
collective bargaining rights and prevent discrimination against 
union members, saying it is a ``common misconception'' that union 
demands for concessions inevitably will deaden Hong Kong's 
enterprising spirit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Businesses close because of bad management and not collective  
bargaining,'' says Lee, sitting in an office adorned with such 
social-activism posters as ``Poverty is Wrong'' and ``Demand Women 
Workers' Rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong's labor laws came under scrutiny when Cathay Pacific  
Airways recently ignored a flight attendants' union and negotiated 
directly with individual cabin crew members to make them fly longer 
hours in exchange for pay increases. 
</P>
<P>
	The union cried foul, but Cathay pointed out that trade unions  
here have no right to collective bargaining when managers seek 
concessions from employees. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar fate could loom over Cathay's pilots and flight  
engineers, who have until May 31 to agree to a deal that includes 
an average 8 percent pay cut in exchange for stock options. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots won't comment publicly on their dealings with  
management, but flight attendants who just lost their own battle 
say the outlook isn't good. 
</P>
<P>
	``Forget the good times, a strike now would be unrealistic,''  
says Tess Lim, a Cathay Pacific flight attendant and active union 
member for 17 years. 
</P>
<P>
	K.W. Tsang, the assistant commissioner of labor, disputes  
suggestions that labor laws were designed to protect the interests 
of management, saying ``voluntary and direct negotiation is firmly 
in place and working well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Along with more innovative management techniques that foster  
``congeniality'' in the workplace, employers are now investing 
money on their employees by providing long-term training programs 
and seminars, says Eden Woon, director of Hong Kong's General 
Chamber of Commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the way society is going,'' says Woon.  
</P>
<P>
	The lack of union activism may stem from a corporate culture  
that traditionally encouraged job switching rather than 
confrontation with management, says Won Hong, a lecturer on labor 
issues and social work at the City University of Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	About 94 percent of businesses hire fewer than 20 people, and  
``many are run like family businesses, where workers and employers 
take a cooperative attitude toward profitability,'' says Hong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
