<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cox Is Buying TCA Cable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Cox Communications is reaching into smaller  
markets with the acquisition of Texas-based TCA Cable TV for $3.3 
billion in cash and stock. The deal announced Wednesday will make 
Cox the fourth-largest cable company in the nation with about 5 
million subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Robbins, president and chief executive officer of  
Atlanta-based Cox, said TCA ``will become the cornerstone of our 
plans to offer advanced services in middle-market communities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of Cox's markets are in large urban or suburban areas like  
southern California, Virginia and Phoenix. Cox will be adding about 
883,000 TCA customers, nearly all of them in Texas, Arkansas and 
Louisiana. 
</P>
<P>
	``There remain growth opportunities in our business, and we're  
going to continue to pursue mid-market opportunities as well as 
large-market opportunities,'' Robbins said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fred Nichols, TCA's chairman and CEO, said the merger will mean  
little change for subscribers in areas like programming but will 
add Cox's expertise and experience to TCA's efforts to be ``a 
totally integrated communications provider in our operating 
areas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cox officials noted that TCA's recent system upgrades have  
enabled the company to offer high-speed Internet access and digital 
video services. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox Communications has been a pioneer in building digital  
networks and offering new services such as digital television, 
Internet access and local telephone service. 
</P>
<P>
	Robbins also cited TCA's record of customer service, its balance  
sheet and a ``solid management team'' that will remain in place. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox is paying the equivalent of $4,115 per subscriber. AT&AMP;T  
Corp. recently agreed to pay about $4,600 per subscriber for cable 
TV company MediaOne Group Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox also is assuming $736 million in debt as part of the deal,  
which has been approved by both boards and is expected to close 
late this year. 
</P>
<P>
	TCA's stock rose Wednesday after the deal was announced, gaining  
$7.70 or 15 percent to $60.31 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. Cox's 
shares fell $1.93 3/4 to $86.06 1/4 on the NYSE. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
