<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Summers To Replace Rubin at Treasury  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, idolized on  
Wall Street for the policies many credit with spurring the U.S. 
economic boom, is stepping down. President Clinton today will 
nominate his deputy, Lawrence Summers, to succeed him. Rubin, a 
former investment banker, and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan have overseen the policies that set the U.S. economy on 
its longest peacetime expansion in history. Rubin has long been 
considered a candidate to replace Greenspan if he chooses to retire 
when his term ends in June 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Seeks Russia Support on Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Declaring NATO's mistaken bombing of the  
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade would not block a diplomatic solution 
in Kosovo, the Clinton administration is focused on winning 
Russia's approval of its tough demands on Yugoslavia. But President 
Boris Yeltsin declared today in remarks obviously aimed at 
Washington: ``Some people obviously aren't understanding our 
repeated proposals,'' which include a bombing halt. Still, White 
House press secretary Joe Lockhart said a meeting between Russia's 
envoy to Yugoslavia, Viktor Chernomyrdin, and Deputy Secretary of 
State Strobe Talbott had been productive. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin Fires Prime Minister  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Boris Yeltsin fired Prime Minister  
Yevgeny Primakov today, one day before Parliament was to begin 
impeachment hearings against Yeltsin. Political leaders warned that 
Primakov's dismissal would almost certainly guarantee that the 
Duma, the lower house of parliament, will vote to impeach. To 
remove Yeltsin from office, however, the impeachment motion must 
also be approved by two-thirds majorities of the upper chamber and 
the supreme and the constitutional courts. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Announces Grants for Cops  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Making good on a pledge to pay for 100,000  
police officers, President Clinton today announced a new round of 
grants allowing communities to hire cadets and urged Congress to 
support his anti-crime package. Clinton also used the announcement 
to celebrate what he said were the effects of the 1994 crime bill -- 
a drop in murder rates and other violent crimes -- and to call for 
renewal of the community policing grants. 

</P>
<P>
	FCC Mulls Cell Phone Rules for 911  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission is  
expected to take action tomorrow to increase the chances that 
cellular phone calls to 911 will go through. Under the FCC plan, 
new analog cellular phones would be required to have software to 
route 911 calls to another carrier when the customer's own company 
can't complete the call. More than 98,000 calls to 911 are made 
each day on cell phones. Digital phones wouldn't be covered by the 
FCC rules because they are more complex and technology doesn't yet 
exist to deal with the call completion problem. 

</P>
<P>
	House Considers Y2K Lawsuit Limits  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House neared a vote this afternoon on a  
bill to limit millennium-bug lawsuits -- a measure that businesses 
say is needed to avoid a year-2000 financial catastrophe. The 
legislation would try to stem a potential flood of lawsuits arising 
from computer breakdowns by establishing a 90-day waiting period 
before lawsuits can be filed, cap punitive damage and limit class 
action lawsuits. The White House sees it as slanted against 
consumers and deserving of a presidential veto. 

</P>
<P>
	Enzyme May Extend Worm's Life  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Scientists have found an enzyme in worms that  
helps them live longer -- a discovery that raises hopes of finding 
treatments for Alzheimer's and other human diseases associated with 
aging. The next step is to determine whether a similar enzyme 
exists in humans. The findings are published in tomorrow's issue of 
the journal Nature. 

</P>
<P>
	Wait Is Over for 'Star Wars' Tickets  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Next to the actual opening of the new ``Star  
Wars'' movie, this is the day fans have been waiting for: tickets 
for ``Star Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace'' were to go on 
sale this afternoon. Ticket sellers geared up for the expected 
onslaught by adding staff and equipment. The movie opens on May 19. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Recovering; Dow Down 13.75  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 13.75 at 11,012.40 after being down as much as 213 earlier 
today. On the NYSE, decliners led advancers 1,701-1,259. The Nasdaq 
was 32.12 at 2,598.80. 

</P>
<P>
	Hingis Beats Garcia, Novotna Upset  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Top-seeded Martina Hingis breezed into the third  
round of the German Open with a 6-3, 6-2 victory over Gala Leon 
Garcia today. Jana Novotna, the No. 2 seed, was upset by Ruxandra 
Dragomir 7-6 (7-4), 6-2. Meanwhile, fifth-seeded Mary Pierce pulled 
out of the $1 million clay-court event with a thigh injury. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
