<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Mixed; Dow Down 25.78 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed Wednesday as blue chips  
recovered most of a sharp drop following Treasury Secretary Robert 
Rubin's resignation, and the broader market rose on strength in 
technology issues. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close of trading, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 25.78 at 11,000.37, just as President Clinton formally 
announced Rubin's resignation and the nomination of Lawrence 
Summers as his successor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow opened slightly lower but plunged as much as 213 points  
after word of Rubin's resignation first crossed news wires 20 
minutes later. It made back most of its losses within the first 
hour of trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators, which also fell on the Rubin news,  
climbed quickly back into positive territory. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 
500 index closed up 8.39 at 1,364.00 , and the Nasdaq composite 
index gained 39.86 to 2,606.54. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was initially worried that new leadership at the  
Treasury might mean a change in the administration's approach to 
the economy, which has thrived since Rubin was installed in 1995. 
But market experts said Rubin's resignation had long been expected 
and that the White House had made a good move in choosing Summers, 
his deputy, as a successor. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers will need to be confirmed by the Senate. Market analysts  
warned that any delay on Capitol Hill could send the stock and bond 
markets lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Ned Riley, chief investment officer at BankBoston, said the  
choice of Summers helped the market regain its footing. ``The 
promptness of his appointment and well-orchestrated transition 
calmed the markets very quickly,'' Riley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with Federal Reserve Chairman Greenspan, Rubin is seen as  
having played a key role in the stock market's historic eight-year 
advance, although Summers is also well respected for his 
intellectual prowess and command of economic issues. 
</P>
<P>
	But Summers, who came to public life from academia, has a  
different style from Rubin, a former Wall Street investment banker. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Rubin is thought to be more reserved in his style of  
communicating, somewhat more contained,'' said Christine Callies, 
chief investment strategist at Credit Suisse First Boston, ``while 
Mr. Summers is thought of as someone who is a little more garrulous 
and slightly more outspoken on a number of issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Byron Wien, the U.S. investment strategist at Morgan Stanley  
Dean Witter who knows both men, said Summers ``can be acerbic,'' 
but that he was often the brains behind Rubin's formidable 
diplomacy. 
</P>
<P>
	And, although the market was concerned about interest rates,  
analysts were quick to note that Greenspan continues to lead the 
Fed. The 30-year Treasury bond yield ended at 5.82 percent, down 
from 5.83 percent Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial services stocks tumbled on the news of Rubin's  
resignation but recovered. Citigroup was up 1 7/16 at 73 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Cyclical stocks, which rise and fall in response to economic  
conditions, were lower. Alcoa was down 2 3/16 at 62 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil stocks fell after new government data showed an unexpected  
increase in oil reserves. Exxon was down 2 9/16 at 79 1/16, and 
Chevron fell 3 to 95 1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks rose sharply.  
</P>
<P>
	IBM climbed 4 1/2 to 225 1/2 after trading as high as a record 228  
7/16. IBM unveiled a new computer disk drive storage system that 
packs 20 billion bits of data into a square inch, twice the 
previous record. IBM also announced it had signed a $1 billion 
contract to make a computer chip for Nintendo's next-generation 
video game player. And in a meeting with analysts after the close 
of trading, chief executive Louis Gerstner said the Internet 
represents a ``gigantic service opportunity'' for IBM. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues had a narrow 9-to-8 lead on advancers on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where consolidated volume came to 1.01 
billion shares, up slightly from Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 1.91 to 647.68, the American Stock  
Exchange composite rose 9.06 to 798.35, and the Russell 2000 index 
of smaller companies added 2.45 to 449.26. 
</P>
<P>
	In foreign markets, the Nikkei 225 index in Tokyo advanced 1.22  
percent. In Europe, the DAX index in Frankfurt fell 0.02 percent, 
the CAC index in Paris rose 0.11 percent, but the FT-SE 100 index 
in London declined 0.55 percent. 



</P>
</TEXT>
