<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Almond Growers Expecting a Bounty / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- Almond growers are counting a record  
number of blossoms this spring and expecting a bounty this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	California, the nation's sole commercial producer of almonds, is  
expected to harvest 760 million pounds of the tree nut this season, 
eclipsing the previous high of 756 million pounds in 1997-1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1999-2000 forecast, based on predictions by 224 growers, was  
released this week by the California Agricultural Statistics 
Service, an arm of the U.S. Department of Agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
	Growers have been anticipating a bumper crop since the beginning  
of the season, with estimates based on thousands of additional 
plantings and buoyed by near-perfect pollination in the San Joaquin 
Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	But those expectations have been tempered by the knowledge that  
a huge drop might follow to compensate for the heaviness of the 
crop on the trees. Nutlets drop to the ground three different 
times, once during the bloom and again four and seven weeks after 
bloom. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a tremendously beautiful bloom,'' said D. Billings, who  
helps run a family farm in Delano. ``Coinciding with that we 
usually have a tremendous drop. It's natures way of letting the 
tree survive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The latest forecast reflects a continued trend in growth that is  
forcing the almond industry to find ways to broaden the 
marketplace, hoping to keep demand on pace with larger future 
crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past 20 years, almond production has jumped 575 million  
pounds, sales have nearly tripled and grower revenues have jumped 
nearly 700 percent, according to the Almond Board of California. 
</P>
<P>
	With the value-per-bearing acre trending upwards the past five  
years and now hovering above $2,000, trees have been planted at a 
rate too dizzying for statisticians to keep good count. The 
estimate now stands at more than 450,000 acres. 
</P>
<P>
	The almond board, based on a vote by an overwhelming majority of  
almond growers, will be expanding dramatically its overseas 
marketing programs, especially in China, Japan and Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry, which exports more than 70 percent of the crop,  
already has won awards for its domestic ``Almonds are In'' campaign 
featuring ads that show how California almonds can make food more 
special. 
</P>
<P>
	The board also is touting newly discovered health benefits,  
citing studies that show almonds help shed pounds, and can lower 
the risk of colon cancer and heart disease. 
</P>
<P>
	``Almonds are a luxury item. You don't have to have almonds in  
order to live,'' said Mario Viveros, a University of California 
farm advisor for Kern County, one of the state's largest almond 
regions with about 89,000 acres of trees. ``When people don't have 
disposable income to buy them, they are going to buy something that 
is more vital to their diet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	China's 1.2 billion consumers are of especial interest.  
California is already that country's top supplier. However, the 
record nine million pounds shipped there last year represent only 
1.5 percent of the state's total exports. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got all kinds of programs we've been working on in  
China,'' said Michael Marsh, director of finance, statistics and 
compliance at the almond board. ``We're hoping in very near term 
those programs will bear more fruit and we'll be shipping millions 
more pounds.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
