<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Valvoline Apologizes for Racing Ad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Sports Illustrated and Valvoline Co. are  
apologizing for the placement of an advertisement opposite a 
photograph of the body of a victim of a recent accident at a North 
Carolina speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Three spectators were killed and eight other fans were injured  
May 1 when debris from a crash during an Indy Racing League event 
flew over a 15-foot catch fence and into the crowd at Lowe's Motor 
Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	The photograph in the magazine's May 10 issue shows one victim,  
with a leg protruding from beneath a sheet, lying on the 
blood-covered grandstand steps. 
</P>
<P>
	On the opposite page, a full-page Valvoline ad shows five men  
working under the hood of a car, with the caption, ``You're born. 
You die. In between you work on cars. We should all be so lucky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Valvoline statement Tuesday to The Associated Press apologized  
for ``any offense that inadvertently may have occurred.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Valvoline has long given explicit direction to Sports  
Illustrated to never place any Valvoline ad near or adjacent to any 
article or photography which describes or illustrates death or 
injury, especially involving auto racing. This week, Sports 
Illustrated failed to comply with our policy,'' the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine took full responsibility.  
</P>
<P>
	``We make every effort to comply with their requests, but  
sometimes with quick closing deadlines and as people are scrambling 
to close the issue, these things happen,'' said spokesman Robin 
Shallow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
