<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Kenny Chesney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Kenny Chesney is a country singer  
looking for a little respect. 
</P>
<P>
	The breezy ``How Forever Feels'' recently spent six weeks at No.  
1, the most successful single of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Chesney is also playing to his largest audiences ever as part of  
superstar George Strait's tour of stadiums. And on the new album 
``Everywhere We Go,'' Chesney's song selection takes a serious turn 
with ``California,'' about a woman trying to brush off an abusive 
past. Randy Travis gave Chesney some props by singing a duet with 
him on another song on the CD. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the 31-year-old singer tends to get lumped in with the  
``country hunk'' movement of the early 1990s, when so many 
good-looking young men in cowboy hats had hits, it was hard to tell 
one from another. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of those aging hunks have disappeared from the charts.  
Chesney remains. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's still tons of people, millions of people out there who  
don't know who I am,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Suddenly his eyes narrow: ``But there's a couple million out  
there that do.'' Just as quickly the serious mood passes and he 
starts laughing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Slowly and surely people are putting the face with the  
songs,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``How Forever Feels'' has really struck a nerve with people.  
Why? 
</P>
<P>
	Chesney: I think 'How Forever Feels' was really just an  
infectious song from the very opening riff. I just think it's 
different. Also, I've never heard another love song that mentions 
Richard Petty. That song really opened up a brand new audience for 
me. My past two albums have gone gold (meaning sales of more than 
500,000), but a lot of people think 'How Forever Feels' is my first 
single. It's odd, because I've been out there for six years now. 
</P>
<P>
	1 1/2. In the video for the song you lose the cowboy hat and show  
off your balding head. Was that a big decision for a ``country 
hunk''? 
</P>
<P>
	Chesney: We were just having fun down there at the beach, and  
it's kind of hard to scuba dive with a cowboy hat on. ... If 
there's one thing about me -- I want to be real. It never once 
crossed my mind about competition or about what people would think. 
</P>
<P>
	2. Many of your hits are lighthearted love songs, but on  
``Everywhere We Go,'' there is a song about a woman abused by her 
father and the duet with Randy Travis is about getting baptized. 
Why the serious turn? 
</P>
<P>
	Chesney: I think it's just a reflection of a growing process  
that I'm going through. On my first couple of records, I recorded 
some songs that were well-written songs, and I had a couple of hits 
here and there. But there was nothing I feel like really dug deep 
down and got into people's minds and their hearts. 
</P>
<P>
	I wanted to have a lot of fun with this record, but I also  
wanted to have a little bit of depth. With 'California,' it doesn't 
come right out and say it's a molesting relationship, but then 
again it does. You just got to listen for it. Songs like that and 
'Baptism' -- those two songs might not be singles for us, but make 
the album just 10 times better. 
</P>
<P>
	3. You've also got a song called ``She Thinks My Tractor's  
Sexy'' on the album, which is a downright silly double entendre. 
</P>
<P>
	Chesney: Yeah, it's silly. But it's infectious, and it's written  
very well, and it made me laugh the first time I heard it. Music is 
like medicine to me, man. You've got to have serious things, and 
then you got to have 'She Thinks My Tractor's Sexy' to have fun 
with and let your hair down. ... We're getting a bigger response 
from the 'Tractor' thing then anything I've ever had out, and it's 
not even a single yet. 
</P>
<P>
	4. You're the country singer most identified with Tennessee  
football, yet you didn't attend the university in Knoxville, Tenn. 
What's the connection? 
</P>
<P>
	Chesney: I grew up there. I lived 10, 15 minutes from the  
stadium, so it's around you everywhere. It's in the blood over 
there. Peyton (Manning, the former Tennessee quarterback who now 
plays for the Indianapolis Colts) liked my music ... so we set it 
up and went to lunch one day and kept in touch and become really 
good buddies. I talk to him two or three times a week. 
</P>
<P>
	I think there's always been a bond between pro athletes and  
musicians. I've been trying to talk Peyton and the Colts 
organization into letting me suit up one day. Peyton goes, 'No way, 
not even in pre-season. You cannot do that.' 
</P>
<P>
	5. What's it like playing to such large audiences on the George  
Strait tour? 
</P>
<P>
	Chesney: It's pretty incredible. My fan base is growing and  
growing every weekend. We're playing in front of 70,000 people, and 
I'm singing a really big hit record, 'How Forever Feels.' The fact 
that George Strait wants me out there on tour with him -- thinks 
enough about my music and what I'm doing -- it means a lot to me. I 
made a joke to George the other night, that I seem to draw a lot 
better when I'm playing with him. He just kind of looked at me like 
I was a little crazy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
