<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arthritis Drug, Infections Studied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government is asking the maker of a new  
rheumatoid arthritis treatment to study whether the drug increases 
patients' risk of infections. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Enbrel was approved last winter, 30 of an estimated 25,000  
Enbrel users have developed serious infections -- including sepsis -- 
and six have died, the Food and Drug Administration said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases are puzzling because carefully controlled studies of  
Enbrel taken by rheumatoid arthritis patients had not shown an 
increased infection risk. 
</P>
<P>
	But Enbrel works by targeting an immune system protein that  
causes painful arthritis inflammation. So scientists had always 
wondered whether inhibiting that protein would suppress the immune 
system enough to render some people vulnerable. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday, the FDA warned doctors not to give Enbrel to anyone  
who has an active or chronic infection, and to be cautious when 
considering the drug for people with a history of recurring 
infections or other diseases like diabetes that may increase 
infection risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Until now, the drug's warnings had only prohibited giving Enbrel  
to people with sepsis, a dangerous bloodstream infection. And 
patients were urged to quit taking it if they became infected. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturer Immunex Corp. wrote thousands of doctors Monday  
informing them that the warning was coming. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty infections isn't an alarming number in itself. But  
officials became worried about a pattern, explained FDA immunology 
chief Dr. William Schwieterman. The sick patients often appeared 
predisposed to infections; the new infections developed within a 
week or two of starting Enbrel; and some of the fatalities occurred 
after antibiotic treatment failed. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA stressed that no one knows if Enbrel causes any problem,  
but urged doctors to consider the cases as a precautionary measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the agency asked Immunex to conduct a special, large study  
to settle the issue. The company and government are discussing how 
to do that. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
