<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Preakness Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Bob Lewis celebrated his 75th birthday  
Wednesday by greeting his Kentucky Derby winner Charismatic as the 
colt came off a van after shipping in from Louisville for the 
Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	``Imagine being this age and having so much fun?'' Lewis,  
accompanied by his wife, Beverly, said. ``It's incredible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lewises have won two of the past three Kentucky Derbys --  
Silver Charm won the Derby and Preakness in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FILLIES ARE HERE:* Trainer Bob Baffert showed up at Pimlico,  
too, bringing along his fillies Silverbulletday and Excellent 
Meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Both were expected to run in Saturday's Preakness, although  
there was still a chance one could run in the Black-Eyed Susan 
Friday, 
</P>
<P>
	``The fillies will be tough if they run in the Preakness,''  
Baffert said. ``Now it's up to fate and the draw.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday, owned by Mike Pegram, has won 10 of 11 starts,  
including an easy victory in the Kentucky Oaks the day before the 
Derby. Silverbulletday, to be ridden by Gary Stevens, would be 
running against males for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	Excellent Meeting, fifth in the Derby with Kent Desormeaux  
aboard, has won seven of 12 starts. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DERBY WINNER LIKES TO EAT:* Charismatic is the most seasoned  
horse in Saturday's Preakness, just like he was in the Kentucky 
Derby. He also may be the best fed. 
</P>
<P>
	``He likes to eat,'' owner Bob Lewis said. ``A few weeks ago, I  
suggested he may eat us out of house and home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, that was before the Derby victory and the winner's  
share of $886,200. 
</P>
<P>
	``He goes out there and does his business on the track, than  
comes back to the barn and eats the bottom out of the grain 
bucket,'' Lewis said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3-year-old colt will be making his 16th career start.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CHANGES:* Chris McCarron sustained a foot injury and will not  
be aboard Stephen Got Even in Saturday's Preakness. Trainer Nick 
Zito has yet to pick a replacement. ... Vicar, 18th in the Derby 
under Shane Sellers, has a new jockey in Robby Albarado. Sellers 
took the call on Kimberlite Pipe, who finished sixth in the Derby 
under Albarado. ... Lead Em Home was withdrawn from Preakness 
consideration by trainer Phil Marino, who will enter his colt in 
the Sir Barton Stakes on the undercard. ... Prime Timber, fourth in 
the Derby but out of the Preakness, won't run in the Sir Barton, 
either. ... Dubai-based Worldly Manner was one of the many 
Preakness horses who shipped in Wednesday. The colt went 5 furlongs 
in 1:00 2-5 in Tuesday's workout at Churchill Downs. ... Valhol 
will be ridden by Edgar Prado. 
</P>
</TEXT>
