<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Remains Firm on China, WTO Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Clinton administration will remain firm  
on requirements for China's entry to the World Trade Organization 
while seeking to ease tensions caused by the accidental bombing of 
the Chinese embassy in Yugoslavia, Commerce Secretary William Daley 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The bombing last week has complicated negotiations, but there  
are no plans for the United States to retreat from concessions won 
during negotiations before Premier Zhu Rongji's visit to Washington 
last month or demands that China further open its markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a political deal. This is not a political  
statement about how far China has come or how important they are. 
This is a commercial deal and these are commercial terms,'' Daley 
said during a question-and-answer period after a speech to Town 
Hall Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. aircraft bombed the Chinese embassy in Belgrade Friday.  
NATO officials have blamed the accident on outdated maps that 
identified the building as a Yugoslav government command center. 
</P>
<P>
	China's attempts to win U.S. support for its admission to the  
WTO already were hindered by allegations of Chinese spying, 
questionable political contributions and human rights abuses within 
China. 
</P>
<P>
	China has been negotiating for 13 years to enter the 134-country  
WTO. Based in Geneva, Switzerland, the organization sets rules for 
international trade and mediates disputes among its members. Entry 
to the body, which must be approved by member countries, would 
enable China to trade on more favorable terms with WTO nations. 
</P>
<P>
	In the days before Zhu's visit, China offered concessions that  
would open up aviation, agriculture, telecommunications and 
financial and other services -- sectors long-closed and in which 
American businesses excel. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration is hoping to secure greater access to  
China's financial services sector and protections for U.S. steel 
and textile makers from Chinese imports. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. and Chinese negotiators last met Friday in Beijing, hours  
before the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, the tragedy that occurred makes the timing of it  
more difficult. It should not impact the agreements that were 
reached before Premier Zhu came, the issues of agriculture and 
others,'' Daley told reporters after his remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	``If, by chance, someone in China thought that they could pull  
back some of those commitments and positions and somehow we would 
find that acceptable, that's not the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daley noted that European negotiators also have been unable to  
reach agreement with China on similar issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``That shows also that this is not just the United States that  
has problems on these economic issues with China,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
