<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pollin To Sell Washington Capitals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Abe Pollin has agreed to sell the NHL's  
Washington Capitals and minority interests in the NBA's Washington 
Wizards and the MCI Center, WRC-TV reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Capitals would be sold to America Online executive Ted  
Leonsis, the station said, although it did not say whether shares 
of the Wizards and MCI Center would go to Leonsis or other 
investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollin scheduled a ``major announcement'' involving his teams  
for 5 p.m. EDT, according to a statement released by his 
organization, Washington Sports &AMP; Entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	NHL spokesman Frank Brown said the NHL was aware of the news  
conference and the TV report, but would have no other comment. NBA 
spokesman Chris Brienza said the same thing. 
</P>
<P>
	The report came as another NHL club, the bankrupt Pittsburgh  
Penguins, is close to being sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The Capitals would also be the second of three major sports  
teams sales expected this year in Washington. The NFL is expected 
to approve the sale of the Redskins to Daniel Snyder later this 
month, and D.C. United of Major League Soccer is also on the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	The possibility of a sale has been circulating for months.  
Pollin spent about $200 million of his own money to build the 
downtown MCI Center two years ago, but his teams have continued to 
lose money since the arena opened in December 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	With more and more teams now being run by corporations, Pollin  
has been a throwback to the days of solo ownership. But the 
75-year-old executive never seemed comfortable with the high 
salaries and lifestyles of the 1990s athletes, and he was 
particularly discouraged by legal troubles involving Wizards 
players during the 1997-98 season. 
</P>
<P>
	This season for Pollin could be summed up in one word: losing.  
The Capitals and Wizards missed the playoffs for the first time 
since 1980-81. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wizards, despite the addition of Mitch Richmond to a  
high-payroll lineup that featured Juwan Howard and Rod Strickland, 
missed the playoffs during the lockout-shortened season. They fired 
coach Bernie Bickerstaff after 32 games and finished 18-32. 
</P>
<P>
	The Capitals, who made the Stanley Cup finals the year before,  
had their worst season since the early 1980s, finishing 31-45-6. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollin purchased the Wizards -- then known as the Baltimore  
Bullets -- in 1964 and became sole owner in 1968. He built his first 
arena, the Capital Centre in Landover, Md., in 1973 and moved his 
NBA team there. The Capitals, Pollin's expansion NHL franchise, 
opened play there a year later. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollin is liked by most of the Washington community. He was  
applauded when he built the MCI Center downtown with his own money 
and was optimistic the move would help revitalize the nation's 
capital. 
</P>
<P>
	But the arena hasn't been a panacea. Its showcase restaurant  
shut recently for nonpayment of taxes. The NBA lockout also kept 
the arena dark for many nights last fall, contributing to the 
team's losses and dampening the arena's impact on surrounding 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Leonsis is the president of AOL Studios, an arm of America  
Online that describes itself as the ``leading online content 
programmer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is a 1977 graduate of Georgetown University and has been  
labeled by The Wall Street Journal as ``one of the Web world's most 
influential players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman at America Online said the company was not  
involved in the purchase of the teams. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 05:55:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Gun Control Showdown Nears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three weeks after the Colorado high school  
shootings, Republicans and Democrats skirmished over gun control 
and youth violence Tuesday in the prelude to an expected Senate 
showdown later in the week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must do more to keep guns out of the hands of children,''  
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said as gun-control advocates 
readied a series of proposals ranging from an increase in the age 
for handgun possession from 18 to 21 and a measure to restrict 
sales at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without guns, families in Littleton, Colo., would not be  
grieving, and 15 people would be alive today,'' Kennedy added. 
</P>
<P>
	``Passing a law sounds good, but to really maximize our impact  
... we've got to prosecute the laws we've got,'' countered Sen. 
Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., as Republicans unveiled statistics showing a 
sharp decline in prosecutions for gun-related crimes since 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Republicans focused their attention on the violence  
that sometimes underpins modern-day culture. Lawmakers attending 
their weekly closed-door caucus were shown a sequence from 
Basketball Diaries, a move in which a high school student mows down 
some of his classmates with a gun while some of his closest friends 
laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican and Democratic aides said the fate of the gun control  
proposals was unclear, with the shock of the Colorado shootings 
adding an element of uncertainty to what is customarily a hotly 
controversial issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, they said, Senate passage of the provision to place gun  
shows under the law requiring an instant background check on anyone 
purchasing a gun at a licensed dealer was possible by the end of 
the week. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Republicans and Democrats both embraced a proposal  
to ban firearms possession by any person who has been convicted of 
a felony as a juvenile. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond that, Republican sources, who spoke on condition of  
anonymity, said GOP leaders were confident they had enough votes to 
block efforts to reinstitute a three-day waiting period for handgun 
purchases or to limit gun sales to one per month, as some Democrats 
want. Less clear was the outcome of any vote on the proposed 
increase in the age for handgun possession from 18 to 21. 
</P>
<P>
	No gun votes were expected before Wednesday as the Senate worked  
its way through GOP-drafted legislation relating to juvenile crime 
prevention and enforcement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate's looming debate on gun control marked the latest  
response to the shootings on April 20 in a high school in 
Littleton, where two students killed 12 fellow students and a 
teacher before turning their guns on themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Within days, President Clinton had called for fresh gun control  
restrictions and longtime advocates of such measures said their 
cause had fresh momentum. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Clinton hosted a summit that brought together gun  
manufacturers and the entertainment industry for a discussion of 
youth violence. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online and the video game industry agreed at the meeting  
to plug a loophole that allows children to buy violent video games 
over the Internet that they are too young to buy in stores. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the American Shooting Sports Council, representing  
350 firearms manufacturers and distributors, endorsed a five-point 
administration plan for gun control, including background checks 
for firearms bought at gun shows and increasing the minimum age for 
buying a gun to 21. 
</P>
<P>
	But the White House excluded the National Rifle Association from  
the session, and the organization purchased newspaper ads accusing 
the administration of failing to enforce existing laws. If the 
White House had succeeded in driving a political wedge between the 
gun manufacturers and the NRA, the issue was also potentially 
explosive for some Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	While Democrats from urban states are among the strongest  
supporters of fresh gun control measures, their colleagues from 
Western states have been noticeably less vocal on the subject. 
</P>
<P>
	The party's leader in the Senate, Sen. Tom Daschle of South  
Dakota, for example, issued a statement last week that embraced 
some of Clinton's proposals, but said others needed fresh scrutiny. 
In the past, Democrats have generally refrained from forcing gun 
control issues to a vote in the Senate in recent years for fear of 
putting vulnerable lawmakers at risk in an election year. 
</P>
<P>
	Most public opinion polls show strong support for gun control,  
but Democrats fear the political intensity of opponents, including 
the NRA. Some Democrats believe they lost control of the House in 
1994 in large measure because lawmakers who had supported gun 
control legislation were defeated. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
