<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
	Federated Department Stores, up 3 5/16 at 54 5/16.  
</P>
<P>
	The company reported first-quarter earnings of 40 cents per  
share, up from 27 cents a year earlier and beating analysts' 
expectations of 31 cents. 

</P>
<P>
	Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, down 4 3/16 at 89 5/16.  
</P>
<P>
	The clothing retailer earned 23 cents a share in the first  
quarter, up 92 percent from 12 cents a share in the year-ago period 
and up from analysts' estimates of 17 cents. The company also said 
it should meet second-quarter earnings estimates of 28 cents per 
share but said sales growth at stores open at least a year will 
slow to between 5 percent and 6 percent this year from a 22 percent 
rise in the first quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	Lyondell Chemical Co., up 1 1/8 at 20 3/4.  
</P>
<P>
	The company said it will sell 35 million common shares at $19 a  
share and offer $1.9 billion of senior secured notes and $500 
million of senior subordinated notes to institutional buyers. In 
addition, Lyondell will borrow $1 billion under its credit 
facility. The total $4 billion net proceeds will be used to retire 
substantially all of the company's debt maturing through 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	The Alpine Group Inc., up 2 5/8 at 16 3/8.  
</P>
<P>
	The company agreed in principle to sell its 83.4 percent owned  
unit, Premier Refractories International Inc., to Cookson Group 
PLC, a London-based technology company, for approximately $115 
million in stock and the assumption of approximately $295 million 
in debt. 

</P>
<P>
	Time Warner, up 3 5/8 at 77 1/4.  
</P>
<P>
	The company spun off its telecommunications unit, Time Warner  
Telecom Inc., in an initial public offering on the Nasdaq Stock 
Market. Time Warner Telecom rose to 20 1/2 from an initial offering 
price of 14. 


</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
	Cisco Systems, up 6 7/8 at 118 3/4.  
</P>
<P>
	The computer network equipment maker posted net income of 38  
cents a share, up from 4 cents in the year-earlier period, 
including charges. The results narrowly exceeded Wall Street 
analysts' expectation of 37 cents. 

</P>
<P>
	Lycos, up 8 3/4 at 107.  
</P>
<P>
	USA Networks, up 3 9/16 at 39 7/16.  
</P>
<P>
	Ticketmaster Online-CitySearch, up 3 7/16 at 36 1/16.  
</P>
<P>
	The companies formally called off their complicated merger. In a  
mutual agreement announced today, USA Networks and Ticketmaster 
also agreed to not acquire Lycos stock or make any proposal to 
acquire Lycos stock until July 15. If Lycos becomes the subject of 
an acquisition proposal prior to July 15, Lycos may be required to 
pay USA Networks and Ticketmaster an aggregate of $35 million under 
certain circumstances. The original merger agreement called for 
Lycos to be merged with certain USA Networks' assets and with 
Ticketmaster-Online. 

</P>
<P>
	TCA Cable TV, up 7 11/16 to 59 3/4.  
</P>
<P>
	Cox Communications, down 1 15/16 to 86 1/16 on the New York  
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox said it will acquire TCA, the Tyler, Texas, cable television  
developer, for $3.26 billion in cash and stock plus the assumption 
of $736 million in debt. Cox, an Atlanta-based cable operator, will 
pay $63.89 for each TCA share, a 23 premium over its closing price 
Tuesday. 

</P>
<P>
	Broadcom Corp., up 3 15/16 at 96 5/8.  
</P>
<P>
	The communications technology maker unveiled its chip that can  
deliver video, voice and data over conventional copper wire 
networks 10 times faster than current technology. The Irvine, 
Calif.-based company said the new chip will allow companies to 
continue using existing copper wiring inside their offices while 
achieving more network speed and capacity. 

</P>
<P>
	Uniview Technologies Corp., up 1 9/16 at 3 3/16.  
</P>
<P>
	The information technology company agreed with SBC  
Communications Inc.'s Southwestern Bell unit to deliver high-speed 
digital telecommunications service in the Dallas/Fort Worth area. 


</P>
