<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> La. Bus Driver Had Health Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The driver of a bus that crashed on Mother's  
Day, killing 22 people, had been diagnosed with congestive heart 
failure -- a condition that should have kept him from behind the 
wheel, a federal investigator said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are delving into Frank Bedell's medical history to  
determine what role, if any, his health played in Sunday's tragedy. 
He remains hospitalized in critical condition with head and pelvic 
injuries and has not been interviewed by police. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell, 46, was driving a group of mostly elderly women to a  
casino on Mississippi's Gulf Coast when his bus veered off a 
highway. 
</P>
<P>
	During an August 1998 physical exam, Bedell checked ``no''  
alongside every listed illness, including diabetes -- with which he 
was diagnosed in 1995 -- and cardiovascular disease, Ken Suydam of 
the National Transportation Safety Board said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But when asked by the attending physician if he was taking any  
medications, Bedell ticked off a list of medicines that led the 
doctor to conclude he had congestive heart failure, Suydam said. 
Congestive heart failure is a condition in which the heart cannot 
pump enough blood to meet the body's demands. 
</P>
<P>
	The doctor approved Bedell's fitness for driving, Suydam said,  
despite a federal law that bars people with congestive heart 
failure from holding commercial drivers' licenses. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the doctor also wrote ``congestive heart failure'' atop  
the form that was returned to Bedell's employer, Custom Bus 
Charters, Suydam said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was uncertain whether officials of Custom saw the notation or  
what, if anything, they might have been required to do, Suydam 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell failed a routine drug test taken shortly after he was  
hospitalized Sunday, indicating that he had smoked marijuana at 
least once within the past 30 days, the Times-Picayune of New 
Orleans reported today, citing a doctor at the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the newspaper quoted the doctor, who declined to be  
identified, as saying the test results do not necessarily mean 
Bedell was under the influence of drugs at the time of the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell tested positive for cocaine when he applied for a job  
with Greyhound in April 1997 and was not hired, said Suydam. 
</P>
<P>
	In June 1997, Bedell gave the Greyhound physical results to  
Custom and passed another drug test, said Suydam. He also passed 
random drug tests required by Custom in April 1998 and October 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell would have had to take a physical next November to renew  
his commercial driver's license and, because of his kidney disease 
and other health problems, probably wouldn't have passed the test, 
said Kay Covington, commissioner of the state Office of Motor 
Vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	``If his condition is as serious as we have been hearing since  
the accident, he probably wouldn't pass a test,'' Covington said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday, investigators removed two electronic monitoring  
boxes from the engine and transmission of the mangled bus, hoping 
they will yield information in the same way that ``black boxes'' 
can offer clues about airplane crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell and at least one witness have said Sunday's accident  
happened after a white compact car cut in front of the bus. There 
have been other reports that the bus narrowly missed hitting a 
green car just before it crashed. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of dollars in cash and various valuables were missing  
from the bodies of four of the victims, family members said in 
today's Times-Picayune. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen Marse, son of victims Arto and Juanita Marse, said most of  
their money and valuables were missing when he collected their 
belongings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Neither of them had near what they left with,'' he said. ``It  
was pathetic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Gagliano, spokesman for the coroner's office, said there  
were many passers-by at the crash scene before police secured it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time you get a disaster you expect things like that,''  
Gagliano said. ``There are so many people handling so many things. 
There's no way to control it. We expected it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
