<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.M. Suspect May Have Killed More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOCORRO, N.M. (AP) -- The girlfriend of a man charged with  
sexually torturing three women told police he may have killed as 
many as 14 people and buried their bodies in ravines. 
</P>
<P>
	The information, which came in an interview with Cynthia Lea  
Hendy soon after her arrest, was released Wednesday by Deputy 
District Attorney Jim Yontz. 
</P>
<P>
	Hendy, 39, told police David Parker Ray, her boyfriend and  
co-defendant, disposed of the bodies in in Elephant Butte Lake, in 
south-central New Mexico's Sierra County. Hendy told police that 
Ray had killed men and women, including two women who appear in 
photographs being tortured. 
</P>
<P>
	Details from Hendy's interview could explain why law enforcement  
officials mounted a massive effort after a woman, bleeding and 
wearing only a padlocked collar, fled Ray's mobile home in Elephant 
Butte on March 22. 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 100 agents from the FBI and state police investigated  
the case in the first few weeks, following leads in 10 states and 
using ground-penetrating radar and dogs trained to locate human 
remains. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents combed gullies in Sierra County and searched Elephant  
Butte Lake for bodies and other evidence. No bodies have been 
found. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray's attorney, Jeff Rein, said Hendy's allegations came after  
she had worked out a deal with prosecutors that reduced both the 
number of charges she faced and her potential prison sentence -- 
from 198 years to as few as 12. 
</P>
<P>
	``She told them what they wanted to hear,'' Rein said. ``I think  
if they would have found any bodies after 45 days, we would have 
seen some charges.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ray, 59 faces 25 charges involving two women who accused him and  
Hendy of kidnapping and sexual torture. He waived a preliminary 
hearing on 12 additional charges related to a third woman who says 
she was kidnapped by Ray and his daughter Glenda Jean ``Jesse'' 
Ray, 32, in July 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Ray and his daughter have said they are innocent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
