<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 15:57:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Primakov a Victim of His Popularity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Ousted Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov was widely  
admired even as Boris Yeltsin's own approval ratings plunged to the 
low single digits -- a factor that may have led the Russian 
president to fire him. 
</P>
<P>
	An experienced diplomat known for carefully deliberating his  
actions, Primakov, 69, was quiet about his political beliefs and 
did not assert his loyalty to any political force -- including 
Yeltsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he was seen as a patriot who ``protects the country's  
interests as he understands them, every time the country gives him 
the slightest opportunity to do so,'' columnist Alexander Minkin 
wrote shortly before Primakov's appointment last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	His wide popularity made him an ideal compromise premier between  
the Kremlin and the Communist opposition in parliament, and his 
appointment last fall quelled a major political feud. 
</P>
<P>
	But Primakov's growing popularity apparently became too much for  
Yeltsin and he fired him on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike his predecessor Viktor Chernomyrdin, Primakov was  
considered ``clean,'' without links to political parties or the 
often corrupt industrial managers and bankers who dominate Russian 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Primakov restored some measure of political calm to the country  
and helped bring at least temporary stability to the foundering 
economy. He paid back some wage and pension arrears, and was 
credited with inspiring hope among the Russians that the economic 
crisis could be resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	He had even promised to restore Russia's national soccer team to  
glory. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Primakov didn't present a coherent plan for tackling  
the economic problems, and seven months into his tenure no 
breakthrough was in sight. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, confidence in his government was surprisingly high,  
according to public opinion polls. For months there was talk about 
Primakov as a potential presidential candidate -- a notion he 
dismissed as ``rubbish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Primakov has a cordial, but cool stance toward the West,  
clashing with Western politicians on several issues in recent 
years. Still, was seen as a pragmatist. 
</P>
<P>
	Primakov vaulted to world attention in 1990-91 as the special  
envoy of Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev. 
</P>
<P>
	He was appointed head of the Soviet KGB's intelligence  
directorate in 1991, and stayed on through the collapse of the 
Soviet Union, Gorbachev's resignation, and the transformation of 
his KGB spy agency into independent Russia's Central Intelligence 
Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, as Yeltsin's spy chief and foreign minister, he developed  
Russia's ``multipolar'' view of the world, which sees its mission 
as fending off the United States as the world's only superpower. 
</P>
<P>
	An Arab affairs specialist, Primakov negotiated with Iraqi  
leader Saddam Hussein in December 1990 and January 1991 in a failed 
attempt to avert the 1991 Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
