<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Bradley Says Hard Work Pays Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Bill Bradley returned to a basketball  
court today to tell young people that, as an athlete, he learned 
that hard work pays off, and the same holds true in running for 
president and in life. 
</P>
<P>
	On his fourth trip to New Hampshire in his quest for the  
Democratic presidential nomination, Bradley said the American 
political system is based on a ``triangle of trust'' -- people 
trusting the president, trusting the political process and the 
president trusting that people will make good decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any decision a president makes will be based on that triangle  
of trust,'' Bradley said. ``The harder the decision, the more 
important that triangle is,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The former senator from New Jersey and NBA star used a  
basketball court as the backdrop for his remarks to about 200 young 
people and YMCA volunteers. He stressed the importance of hard 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	``Having learned that lesson in the game, it is directly  
applicable to academic life, it is directly applicable to service 
in the Senate, and it is directly applicable to running for 
president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, voters asked Bradley about health care and prisoners  
of war in Vietnam. He refused to be pinned down, saying it is still 
early and he will make his opinions known sometime this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being an armchair quarterback is easy, and I'm not going to do  
it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley met with 50 faculty members, students and area religious  
leaders at Rivier College in Nashua before speaking with 100 
supporters at a Laconia common. 
</P>
<P>
	Tracy Schier, a Rivier administrator, said Bradley genuinely  
seemed interested in voter concerns, but ``he needs to communicate 
where he stands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Rivier, Bradley said Americans are groping for meaning in  
their lives, exemplified by the fact they move on average every 
seven years and by the existence of a popular perfume called 
``Eternity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The search for meaning has led many young people to volunteer  
work, but they remain alienated from politics because of its 
emphasis on money and polls, Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to put service at the center of politics,'' he said.  
``That's why I'm in this process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley said he supports gun control, campaign finance reform,  
improving trade by raising living standards in other parts of the 
world, and making it easier to get health care. He did not say how 
he would accomplish those goals. 
</P>
<P>
	On the environment, he said, ``My approach would be to try to  
clean up what is polluted and prevent what is not polluted from 
becoming polluted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some recent polls showed a shrinking gap between Bradley and  
Vice President Al Gore, who leads by at least 20 percentage points 
in most of them. The Republican National Committee this month 
decided to begin spending as much time scouring Bradley's 
background as Gore's. 
</P>
<P>
	The move could indicate Republicans are taking Bradley more  
seriously, or could be an attempt to portray Gore as a weak 
candidate. Either way, Bradley said he is not concerned. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't really care what the Republican National Committee  
does,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
