<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Astros Coach Has Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Houston Astros hitting coach Tom McCraw will  
leave the team after Sunday's game to begin treatment for prostate 
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Doctors tell us we have caught this in the early stages and  
we're confident Tommy will make a full recovery,'' general manager 
Gerry Hunsicker said. ``At this time, he is deciding which doctor 
he will work with and what course of action he will take.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCraw, in his third season with the Astros, was tested in  
spring training and a more recent biopsy revealed the cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	McCraw is the second Astros coach to be sidelined by illness.  
First base coach Jose Cruz is out three to four weeks while 
undergoing treatment for an irregular heart beat. Bullpen coach 
John Tamargo is coaching at first base in Cruz' absence. 
</P>
<P>
	Harry Spilman, Houston's minor league field coordinator, will  
assume hitting coach duties during McCraw's absence. Spilman, who 
played for the Astros, Tigers, Reds and Giants during an 11-year 
major league career, is expected to join the team this weekend 
during the Astros' three-game series vs. San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros were batting a league-leading .295 going into  
Wednesday night's game. McCraw's diagnosis was announced the day 
after his hitters set or tied several team records in a 19-8 
victory over Pittsburgh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
