<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 06:15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cat Thief Could Capture Preakness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Even if Charismatic doesn't come up with a  
suitable encore in the Preakness, there's still a chance that D. 
Wayne Lukas will be smiling broadly in the winner's circle. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because his other entrant, Cat Thief, could very well  
steal the show Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief took third in the Kentucky Derby, his 11th straight  
finish in the money since his maiden run in April 1998. He 
challenged for the lead from the outset and never dropped lower 
than second place before fading in the stretch and coming in less 
than a length behind Menifee. 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief ran a fine race, but was clearly overshadowed by his  
stablemate. Charismatic, a 31-1 longshot, rallied from seventh 
place to give Lukas his fourth Derby winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas, who was to arrive with both colts at Pimlico today, took  
a diplomatic approach in assessing the chances of his horses in the 
Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since they've got different owners, you can't pick between  
them,'' he said. ``You don't want to hurt anyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The focus will be on Charismatic, of course, because he's the  
only horse in the field with a chance to win the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like when you win the Derby, everyone tries to figure  
out a way to beat you,'' Lukas said. ``This race may not suit him 
as well as the Derby. On the other hand, he's sharper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic ran five furlongs in 1:01 Tuesday, his final workout  
before being shipped to Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	Another notable trainer with designs of making some noise in the  
Preakness is Carl Nafzger, who will saddle Vicar with hopes that 
the colt's 18th-place finish in the Derby can be attributed 
entirely to an awful position in the starting gate (17th). 
</P>
<P>
	After watching the horse run five furlongs in 59 3-5 seconds at  
Churchill Downs on Tuesday, Nafzger declared Vicar primed and ready 
to go. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's steadier, more focused in what he's doing,'' Nafzger  
said. ``I was super impressed. I just hope we get a better post 
position. Regardless, with 14 horses we have a better shot at 
getting some rhythm going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Baffert, meanwhile, remained steadfast in his assertion that  
he will wait to decide what to do with his two talented fillies 
until after this afternoon's Preakness draw. Baffert has entered 
Silverbulletday and Excellent Meeting in both the Preakness and 
Friday's Black-Eyed Susan Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Excellent Meeting finished fifth in the Derby; Silverbulletday  
won the Kentucky Oaks one day earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're buddies, real good friends,'' Baffert said. ``Who'd  
ever think they'd be pals like that? I'm sure they discussed their 
races with each other in the barn.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
