<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Internet Privacy Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Businesses have made dramatic improvements  
since last year in warning people how companies use personal 
information collected about them at Web sites, an industry-financed 
study shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly two-thirds of commercial Internet sites displayed at  
least some warning that businesses were collecting personal details 
from visitors, such as names, postal and e-mail addresses, and even 
shopping tastes, the study found. But less than 10 percent of those 
sites had what experts consider comprehensive privacy policies. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Web sites sell the information to third-party advertisers  
and others. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar study last summer by the Federal Trade Commission  
found only 14 percent of sites warned how companies used private 
information they collected about customers. 
</P>
<P>
	FTC Commissioner Robert Pitofsky said companies on the Internet  
``deserve considerable credit for making progress over the last 
year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a remarkable increase in the number of Web sites  
posting information about their privacy practices,'' Pitofsky said. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC expects to recommend to Congress this summer whether new  
Internet privacy laws are needed. It previously said that it wanted 
to see results from this latest study before making any decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry groups argued that merely doubling the number of sites  
with privacy notices from last year's 14 percent would represent 
substantial progress. The latest study found almost 66 percent of 
the 364 commercial Internet sites examined had privacy notices. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that policy-makers take a look at these numbers and are  
encouraged by the progress and increase their determination to work 
with the private sector ... rather than resort to additional, broad 
laws applied to the Net,'' said Harriet Pearson of IBM Corp., one 
of the companies that paid for the study. 
</P>
<P>
	But there was troubling news: less than 10 percent of the  
commercial Web sites with the personal detail warnings had privacy 
policies deemed comprehensive by experts. 
</P>
<P>
	Those sites notified consumers, gave them the chance not to have  
their personal information collected, allowed customers to review 
their information, promised to keep the information secure and 
explained how to contact the company with questions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a survey that says only 10 percent of this narrow  
slice of the Web is providing notice that we think is the critical 
first step,'' said Deirdre Mulligan of the Washington-based Center 
for Democracy and Technology. ``Notice is clearly not enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House has agreed so far to allow the industry to  
develop its own guidelines because of concerns federal intervention 
could stifle the growth of electronic commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be people who will continue to call for  
legislation, but I think the message here is that this is 
working,'' said Christine Varney of the Online Privacy Alliance, an 
industry group. 
</P>
<P>
	People who do not use the Internet frequently cite privacy  
concerns as their primary reason for staying offline. The issue has 
taken on growing significance as more companies have begun selling 
products over the Internet, expected eventually to carry billions 
of dollars in transactions daily. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the largest companies on the Web, including IBM, America  
Online, Microsoft, Compaq and eBay, paid a total of $60,000 for the 
study, conducted by Georgetown University business professor Mary 
J. Culnan. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
