<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Last Cop-Hiring Subsidies Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is urging support for his  
crime-fighting proposals and seeking new controls on dangerous 
biological materials. 
</P>
<P>
	Announcing a milestone for his administration -- the federal  
funding of the 100,000th new police officer under the community 
policing component of his 1994 crime bill -- Clinton was presenting 
$95 million in grants today for a round of 1,500 officers. 
</P>
<P>
	He was pushing Congress to renew the community policing program  
for five years and embrace his omnibus crime package, especially 
its initiatives aimed at reducing juvenile violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also was unveiling new legislation to combat terrorism  
by toughening penalties for unauthorized possession of such harmful 
biological agents as anthrax and holding certified handlers of such 
materials accountable for their misuse. 
</P>
<P>
	``It essentially bans the possession of these agents for other  
than peaceful purposes and makes the unsafe handling of them a 
crime as well,'' said an administration official who spoke on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has made putting 100,000 new police on the streets a  
hallmark of his administration. Although the number of officers 
actually in place is lagging behind the number funded, White House 
officials said today's grants amounted to a goal attained. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the 526 grants being announced today, officials said, were  
$2.3 million to hire 30 new officers for the Miami-Dade Public 
Schools police in Florida; $1.5 million to hire 20 new officers in 
Raleigh, N.C.; $1.9 million for 20 new officers in Fairfax, Va.; 
and $1.6 million for 21 new officers in Irvington, N.J. A 
half-dozen towns in Puerto Rico were receiving funds for 137 new 
officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have criticized the administration for failing to  
make good on the 100,000 cops pledge, and a recent Justice 
Department Inspector General's report criticized several state and 
local police agencies for using the grants to supplant, rather than 
supplement, state and local funds. 
</P>
<P>
	But administration officials said there is a lag of up to 18  
months between the time an agency receives the funds and a new 
trainee is ready to hit the streets, and they estimate that Clinton 
can boast of more than 50,000 officers already on the street. 
</P>
<P>
	There is also some flexibility for police agencies who want to  
use funds to upgrade communications and other gear in order to free 
officers for patrols. 
</P>
<P>
	As to the Justice report, Jose Cerda of the White House domestic  
policy team noted that the agencies investigated represented less 
than 1 percent of the recipients and had been singled out for 
review because of administration suspicions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every indication from the Justice Department, from surveys  
that they conduct regularly, is that every six months there are 
more cops on the street,'' Cerda said. ``The program is working 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wants to extend the community policing program and spend  
$1.3 billion annually to help local law enforcement continue to 
hire more police, buy bulletproof vests and improved communications 
gear, hire more local prosecutors and engage schools and community 
leaders more closely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
