<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Home Resale Prices Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The price of existing homes went up in most of  
the nation's metropolitan markets during the first quarter of the 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The median resale price of used homes -- meaning half of them  
sold for more and half for less -- was $131,600 during the 
January-March quarter, the National Association of Realtors said. 
That was up 4.6 percent from the same quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	This contrasts with an inflation rate that was rising at only  
about a 1.7 percent annual rate during 1998 and kept to an even 
lower 1.5 percent rate so far this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rise in home prices in all regions has been fueled by a  
combination of buyers ready to move up to more expensive homes and 
a growing number of first-time buyers in this favorable economic 
environment,'' said James F. Smith, chief economist for the real 
estate group. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation enjoyed an unprecedented home-buying boom last year,  
attributed to low unemployment, rising incomes, continuing stock 
market gains and low mortgage rates. Sales of existing homes have 
continued to break records this year, rising at a seasonally 
adjusted annual rate of 5.88 million units from January through 
March, the group said, up 8.4 percent from the 5.24 million sales 
rate during the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten of the 120 metropolitan areas surveyed by the trade group  
reported median resale price increases of 10 percent or greater, 
while 24 posted declines. 
</P>
<P>
	Median resale prices ranged from $65,700 in Ocala, Fla., to  
$331,100 in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	The cities with the top five increases were: Kalamazoo, Mich.,  
13.6 percent; San Francisco, 13.2 percent; Miami-Hialeah, Fla., 
12.9 percent; Boise, Idaho, 12.4 percent; and San Diego, 11.6 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The cities with the five worst drops were Riverside-San  
Bernadino, Calif., 8.9 percent; Akron, Ohio, 7.3 percent; Omaha, 
Neb., 5.9 percent; Champaign, Ill., 4.6 percent; and Seattle, 4.5 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	By region, the West and the Northeast posted the largest  
increases, 6.8 percent and 5.6 percent, respectively. The South 
lagged, with a 2.9 percent rise. In the Midwest, the median prices 
advanced 4.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
