<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Samaranch's IOC Reform Tactics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The latest reshuffling of the deck at the International Olympic  
Committee leads to one inescapable conclusion: Three-card monte is 
about to become an Olympic sport. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no better explanation for the bait-and-switch games  
Juan Antonio Samaranch has been perfecting the past few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Every time the clamor grows for the IOC strongman to do  
something about the serial bribe-taking and pleasure-tripping by 
his cronies on the committee, Samaranch turns over a card and -- 
voila! -- suddenly the corruption is somewhere else. 
</P>
<P>
	His most impressive sleight-of-hand came earlier this month,  
when the Spaniard named a task force to review IOC membership 
policies and standards, voting practices and public accountability. 
</P>
<P>
	Ever since the bribery scandal broke last fall, Samaranch has  
come under increasing pressure by some very powerful Americans to 
clean up the IOC's act. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Justice Department opened an investigation into the  
Salt Lake City bidding process. Former Senate Majority Leader 
George Mitchell headed a special ethics panel that went so far as 
to draw up a blueprint. Not long after that, Sen. John McCain 
chaired a Senate Commerce Committee that promised a string of 
hearings to find out how things were going. 
</P>
<P>
	What he learned last week is that all those promises about ``no  
more business as usual'' must have been made by Samaranch while his 
fingers were crossed. 
</P>
<P>
	Though nearly three dozen IOC members were implicated in various  
bribery scandals, only 10 have resigned or been expelled so far, 
though one high-ranking member, Australian Phil Coles, is still 
twisting in the wind. But the chances for any further reforms were 
seriously damaged when Samaranch announced the makeup of ``IOC 
2000,'' the task force that will chart the course for the Olympic 
organization into the next century. 
</P>
<P>
	Original plans called for a panel of two dozen members, tops,  
most of them drawn from outside the IOC. The first hint that those 
plans were being scrapped came with a report that a provisional 
list was being floated that contained more than 60 names. The final 
version was even worse than critics feared. 
</P>
<P>
	``IOC 2000'' now has 80 members, 44 of whom are IOC members. Its  
three most important committees -- the bid process, administration 
and mission -- are headed by loyalists who owe Samaranch their 
Olympic careers. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Anita DeFrantz is one of those loyalists, the American  
rower who went on to become an IOC vice president has not lost any 
of her candor. ``What's the new IOC?'' she said, repeating a 
question put to her recently. ``The (old) IOC without 10 members.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No matter. Just the whiff of reform apparently is good enough  
for some people. After several U.S. corporations had proved 
skittish about going ahead with planned sponsorship deals, General 
Motors stepped forward Tuesday to say it would honor every penny of 
the $1 billion it promised the U.S. Olympic Committee -- beginning 
almost immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing quite captures center stage like the Olympics,'' GM  
vice president and marketing chief Phil Guarascio said at a news 
conference in Detroit, adding that the world's No. 1 automaker will 
launch 17 months of ads for the 2000 Summer Games during next 
month's NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	For all the knocks the Olympic movement has taken, it still  
possesses what advertisers like to call the ``halo effect.'' The 
greedy behavior by nearly one-third of the IOC membership made that 
halo seem tattered and cockeyed. Though nothing substantial has 
changed, GM stepped up Tuesday to say everything looked fine from 
where it stood. 
</P>
<P>
	To drive the point home, the company hired sportscaster Bob  
Costas (from NBC, which holds the U.S. Olympic TV rights through 
2008) as master of ceremonies for Tuesday's event. Then it trotted 
out a half-dozen U.S. gold medalists to tell stories about the 
sacrifices they made to succeed. 
</P>
<P>
	The GM announcement wasn't unexpected, since the company  
announced its sponsorship long before the current scandal broke, 
and shoring up the Olympic ``brand'' is as much about protecting 
its investment as anything else. But there was a lingering sense 
that the long arm of the U.S. Olympic Committee was somewhere in 
the background, nudging GM toward the spotlight and holding up the 
cue cards. 
</P>
<P>
	How the USOC got involved isn't hard to guess. The sad thing is  
that if Samaranch and his country-club pals knew half that much 
about sacrifice as the athletes they pretend to represent, they 
wouldn't be stumbling about, calling in every marker they can find. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 11:25:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Safety on Ark. Tour Boat Discussed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- A survivor of a tour boat accident in  
which 13 people drowned said today that the operator offered no 
safety instructions before piloting the amphibious craft onto Lake 
Hamilton. 
</P>
<P>
	Diane Ledin's testimony at a U.S. Coast Guard hearing  
contradicted that of driver Elizabeth Helmbrecht, who testified 
Tuesday that she had instructed passengers on how to use the life 
jackets before their $9 excursion began May 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Ledin said the driver showed passengers where the life  
preservers were but didn't say how to use them or point out any 
other safety features on the boat, known as a duck because it 
travels on both land and water. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mrs. Ledin said she probably would not have survived if she  
had put on a life preserver. The buoyancy would have trapped her 
inside the vessel, under a canopy where investigators say most of 
the victims were found. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I had a life jacket on, I wouldn't be here today. I  
honestly feel it would have been more of a detriment,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other survivors have said the bulky preservers might not have  
fit through a narrow opening between the sides of the boat and the 
canopy. 
</P>
<P>
	At the weeklong hearing, Mrs. Ledin said that what seemed like  
``a wall of water'' poured into the vessel just minutes after what 
was scheduled to be a 30-minute excursion on Lake Hamilton. 
</P>
<P>
	``We looked around and the water just gushed in. I don't think  
anybody had any time to react,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Ledin said she and her husband, Gary, were seated  
side-by-side. They were the only passengers not to lose a family 
member. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were so thankful, but we just felt guilty because we made  
it as a family and nobody else did,'' Mrs. Ledin said. 
</P>
<P>
	A rescue diver, Michael Roberson, testified today that while  
most of the victims were found beneath the boat's canopy, others 
were outside the boat. With the depth and darkness they probably 
didn't know which way to swim, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``At 34 feet, in fresh water, you begin to lose buoyancy. Air is  
compressed and you lose buoyancy. If you're trying to swim, you 
wouldn't know which way was up,'' said Roberson, a Garland County 
sheriff's deputy. Lake Hamilton is murky and the boat sank to a 
depth of nearly 60 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Ms. Helmbrecht broke down on the stand as she  
recounted the final minutes before the Miss Majestic slipped 
beneath the surface. She told the panel that there were no signs of 
trouble until shortly before the boat sank. 
</P>
<P>
	About five minutes into the tour, the amphibious boat became  
sluggish, she said. When it tilted slightly to the left, she asked 
a passenger to move to balance the weight. But water began pouring 
in from the bottom and from the rear ``like a propeller'' was 
blowing it in, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told the passengers, `Grab a vest and get off. We're going  
down,''' she said. ``It seemed like slow motion. Nobody would move. 
They just were real orderly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said she had no time to grab a life jacket. She said she  
tried to save a young boy as the boat went down, grabbing his hand 
and leading him toward an opening under the canopy. He was jerked 
away from her, apparently by the force of the water, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened two days after Ms. Helmbrecht had taken  
her boat to mechanics and complained that its bilge pump was 
switching on and off erratically. She said she was assured that the 
repairs had been made. 
</P>
<P>
	Inspectors checked out two pumps Wednesday night and both  
worked, the Coast Guard said today. The main bilge pump was 
dismantled and sent off for a detailed inspection, the service 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 16:32:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Announces Grants for Cops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton presented a new round of  
grants to hire community police officers Wednesday, checking off 
one of the biggest promises of his administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I signed the crime bill I pledged to help communities all  
over our nation fund 100,000 community police officers by the year 
2000,'' Clinton said. ``Today we are keeping the pledge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton presented $95 million in grants, created in the 1994  
crime bill, for a round of 1,500 officers. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will bring us to over 100,000 police officers funded,  
ahead of schedule and under budget,'' he said. Only half the 
officers actually are patrolling the street. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton used the announcement in the Rose Garden to celebrate  
what he said were the results of the 1994 crime bill -- a drop in 
murder rates and other violent crimes -- and to call for renewal of 
the community policing grants. 
</P>
<P>
	``In making America's thin blue line thicker and stronger, our  
nation will be safer,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans in Congress have been resisting the idea of renewing  
the community police grants, saying there is too little room in 
next year's budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``Funding existing programs is going to be tough enough; new  
ones are impossible,'' said Elizabeth Morra, spokeswoman for the 
House Appropriations Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, Morra said, Clinton's budget would eliminate  
anti-crime block grants favored by Republicans. Republicans are 
anxious to see money set aside for a $523 million program that 
provided aid to local law enforcement agencies and $250 million in 
block grants for state and local juvenile crime programs, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent Justice Department inspector general's report  
criticized several state and local police agencies for using the 
grants to supplant, rather than supplement, state and local funds. 
Also, GOP officials have contended that the grants program has not 
worked as promised. 
</P>
<P>
	But administration officials said there is a lag of up to 18  
months between the time an agency receives the funds and a new 
trainee is ready to hit the streets. They estimate that Clinton can 
boast of more than 50,000 officers already on the street. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also was pushing Congress to embrace his omnibus crime  
package. He unveiled legislation to combat terrorism by toughening 
penalties for unauthorized possession of harmful biological agents 
and holding certified handlers of such materials accountable for 
their misuse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 09:05:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Korean Hospital Workers on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Thousands of South Korean metal and  
hospital workers walked off their jobs Wednesday to protest planned 
layoffs and wage cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers said about 20,000 workers were participating, but the  
government put the figure at fewer than 8,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee Gap-yong, head of the Confederation of Korean Trade Unions,  
said more metal, hospital and insurance company workers would join 
the walkout this week. But the government said the strike was 
fizzling on its first day. 
</P>
<P>
	Half of the 35 unions that the militant labor confederation  
urged to go on strike Wednesday failed to heed the call as workers 
showed little enthusiasm, the Labor Ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's walkout was led by 4,000 union workers at carmaker  
Ssangyong Motor Co. who fear layoffs after their company's merger 
with Daewoo Motor Co., South Korea's No. 2 car maker. 
</P>
<P>
	Ssangyong's assembly lines ground to a halt.  
</P>
<P>
	About 400 nurses and other workers at Seoul's state-funded Korea  
Cancer Center Hospital walked off their jobs to protest the 
hospital's plan to shed workers and cut wages by 7 percent. A lack 
of staff forced the hospital to postpone nonemergency surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second strike in a month called by the labor  
confederation to protest planned layoffs by manufacturers grappling 
with a severe economic recession. 
</P>
<P>
	The group has not been able to muster strong support in recent  
months amid public concern that rekindled labor unrest could scare 
off foreign investors just as the economy is showing signs of 
recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has gotten tougher as well. It used police to  
break an illegal subway strike last month and fired dozens of union 
leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korea was forced to accept a $58 billion bailout from the  
International Monetary Fund in late 1997. In return, it promised 
structural reform of industries, which expanded rapidly during the 
boom years of the 1970s and 80s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
