<DOCNO> APW19990512.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 16:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Phipps' Horses Star at Belmont </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ogden Phipps, whose family name has been  
synonymous with Belmont Park, enjoyed a banner day with the opening 
of the track's meeting Wednesday. Two Phipps horses, both 
longshots, won. 
</P>
<P>
	Oh What a Windfall, a Phipps stable homebred, rallied for a  
three-quarter length victory in the featured $110,800 Nassau County 
Handicap for 3-year-old fillies. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, another Phipps homebred, Finder's Fee, made an  
impressive debut with a three-length triumph in the third race at 
15-1. The 2-year-old went five furlongs in 58 2-5 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Paved in Gold was second in a field of eight in the Nassau  
County. It was another two lengths to Times Change, the favorite, 
who tired after racing on or near the lead into the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	Oh What a Windfall carried 118 pounds with Mike Smith over seven  
furlongs in 1:23 2-5 to earn $66,480 with her first win in four 
starts this year and her first stakes win since taking Aqueduct's 
Tempted Stakes Nov. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Oh What a Windfall returned $22.40, $8.90 and $4.60. Paved in  
Gold paid $5.10 and $3.60 and Things Change was $3.10 to show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 16:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
