<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 15:44:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alexander Urges Support for Yeltsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate Lamar  
Alexander said Wednesday that the tumult in Russia's government 
``could be a force for stability'' and should not diminish U.S. 
support for President Boris Yeltsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Arguing that the Russian leader could emerge stronger from the  
political chaos, Alexander said, ``Yeltsin has more lives than any 
cat we know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, in a telephone interview during a campaign stop in  
New York, said the Clinton administration should not overreact to 
the abrupt firing of Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov or the 
upcoming impeachment proceedings against Yeltsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is a valuable ally, particularly when the country is in a  
position to help end fighting in Kosovo, said the former Tennessee 
governor, who visited Russia in November 1998 to meet political 
leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new prime minister is well respected and could be a force  
for stability,'' Alexander said. ``There will be an initial 
temptation to say we should review our (international) loans, that 
we should step back from involving Russia in Kosovo but we should 
stay the course, push right ahead and continue our relationship 
with them as before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet even as Alexander made the remarks, Yeltsin was warning that  
Russia may pull out of Kosovo talks. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate phone interview, Alexander urged President Clinton  
to go to Congress for the authority to ``win the war quickly'' in 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I regret that we are in it,'' he said. ``But now that we are  
in it, we have to win it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until then, he said, the NATO bombing should continue.  
</P>
<P>
	Alexander said that once the president has asked ``for the full  
support of the American people,'' he should be given ``all the 
options he needs'' to get Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to 
withdraw his troops from Kosovo and allow the ethnic Albanians to 
return home. 
</P>
<P>
	Firing Primakov and replacing him with Interior Minister Sergei  
Stepashin, as acting prime minister will strengthen Yeltsin's hand, 
Alexander said. ``He dismissed one prime minister and appointed 
another. The new one is the Interior minister who is in control of 
the police. Yeltsin is probably a good deal more secure than it 
look like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the appointment of Stepashin, a Yeltsin ally, appears to  
have little chance of approval in the Duma, the lower house of 
parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin is now on a collision course with the parliament, which  
is scheduled to begin impeachment proceedings Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should not be surprised if Yeltsin dissolves the  
parliament,'' Alexander said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if that would be a bad move, Alexander said, ``It's a  
matter of Russian politics but we should not become overly 
concerned about it because the Duma is filled with Yeltsin 
opponents and he might do it just to keep them off balance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- AP correspondent Duncan Mansfield in Knoxville,  
Tenn., contributed to this story. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 10:15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: NYSE Brokers Under Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Federal prosecutors and regulators are  
investigating dozens of New York Stock Exchange floor brokers who 
may have illegally shared profits with customers, The Wall Street 
Journal reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight brokers already face charges for improper trading.  
Prosecutors are preparing for a June 1 trial in the case of five of 
those eight brokers, a broker-dealer and two of its principals. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Attorney's office, in a letter to defense attorneys in  
the case, said investigators have reason to believe 64 other 
brokers traded in accounts in which they shared customers' profits, 
possibly violating securities laws, people familiar with the letter 
told The Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers are prohibited from trading with their own money.  
However, defense attorneys for brokers headed to trial have argued 
that the stock exchange until recently took the view that it wasn't 
illegal to share in profits with customers for whom they trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Walker, enforcement director at the U.S. Securities and  
Exchange Commission, confirmed that ``an investigation is ongoing 
with respect to floor brokers'' on the NYSE and that the SEC is 
participating. 
</P>
<P>
	But he declined further comment.  
</P>
<P>
	The exchange's approximately 500 independent floor brokers trade  
blocks of stock for outside brokerage firms or large professional 
investors. They have access to highly sensitive information about 
trading at the exchange, so the exchange bars them from trading for 
themselves or putting their trading interests ahead of clients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 16:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pollin To Sell Washington Capitals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Abe Pollin plans to sell the NHL's Washington  
Capitals and his minority interests in the NBA's Washington Wizards 
and the MCI Center to America Online executive Ted Leonsis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to stress here and now that I am not retiring.'' Polin  
said Wednesday at a news conference. ``I never planned to retire. I 
am going to be actively involved and in control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 75-year-old executive, accompanied by his wife and two sons,  
said his family agonized about the decision for months because ``we 
did not want a repeat of the mess that the Redskins went through in 
their transition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	News of the sale came as another NHL club, the bankrupt  
Pittsburgh Penguins, is close to being sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The Capitals would be the second of three major sports teams  
sales expected this year in Washington. The NFL most likely will 
approve the sale of the Redskins to Daniel Snyder this month, and 
D.C. United of Major League Soccer is also on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollin said he decided to sell after his sons told him they had  
no interest in leaving their careers to take over his business. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were talked to by a lot of people, met with a lot of people  
and there was one person who stood out among all of them,'' Pollin 
said of Leonsis, whom he called ``a really good and kind person.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pollin said he still has big sports aspirations.  
</P>
<P>
	``My goal is to bring another NBA championship to Washington and  
we're not going to quit until we do it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``My hope and my prayer is that I'll be able to spend a little  
more time with a little bit more money that I have now with people 
who are little less fortunate than we are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The possibility of a sale has been circulating for months.  
Pollin spent about $200 million of his own money to build the 
downtown MCI Center two years ago, but his teams have continued to 
lose money since the arena opened in December 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	With more and more teams now being run by corporations, Pollin  
has been a throwback to the days of solo ownership. But he never 
seemed comfortable with the high salaries and lifestyles of the 
1990s athletes, and he was particularly discouraged by legal 
troubles involving Wizards players during the 1997-98 season. 
</P>
<P>
	This season for Pollin could be summed up in one word: losing.  
The Capitals and Wizards missed the playoffs for the first time 
since 1980-81. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wizards, despite the addition of Mitch Richmond to a  
high-payroll lineup that featured Juwan Howard and Rod Strickland, 
missed the playoffs during the lockout-shortened season. They fired 
coach Bernie Bickerstaff after 32 games and finished 18-32. 
</P>
<P>
	The Capitals, who made the Stanley Cup finals the year before,  
had their worst season since the early 1980s, finishing 31-45-6. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollin purchased the Wizards -- then known as the Baltimore  
Bullets -- in 1964 and became sole owner in 1968. He built his first 
arena, the Capital Centre in Landover, Md., in 1973 and moved his 
NBA team there. The Capitals, Pollin's expansion NHL franchise, 
opened play there a year later. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollin is liked by most of the Washington community. He was  
applauded when he built the MCI Center downtown with his own money 
and was optimistic the move would help revitalize the nation's 
capital. 
</P>
<P>
	But the arena hasn't been a panacea. Its showcase restaurant  
shut recently for nonpayment of taxes. The NBA lockout also kept 
the arena dark for many nights last fall, contributing to the 
team's losses and dampening the arena's impact on surrounding 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Leonsis is the president of AOL Studios, an arm of America  
Online that describes itself as the ``leading online content 
programmer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is a 1977 graduate of Georgetown University and has been  
labeled by The Wall Street Journal as ``one of the Web world's most 
influential players.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 16:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
