<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teacher Arrested on Rape Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A kindergarten teacher has been charged with  
raping a 6-year-old girl who was a student in his kindergarten 
class. 
</P>
<P>
	Neil Ray pleaded innocent Monday in Dorchester District Court to  
charges of rape of a child and indecent assault and battery of 
child, said Jim Borghesani, a spokesman for the Suffolk County 
district attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray was released on $1,000 cash bail.  
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Ray, a teacher at Grove Hall Child Development  
Center, lured the girl to his apartment in the city's Dorchester 
neighborhood on Saturday and assaulted her. 
</P>
<P>
	There were several listings for Neil Ray in the Boston area and  
messages left on two answering machines were not returned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990512.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 00:33:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Sentenced for Fake Hate Mail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The problem began in December 1996 when United  
Parcel Service began delivering overnight envelopes scrawled with 
racist words and phrases to prominent black leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	When the shipping company protested that its employees weren't  
to blame, FBI agents fanned out to discover whether the envelopes 
were part of a racist plot or an attempted extortion scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	The final chapter came Tuesday when former law student Angela  
Jackson was sentenced to five years and five months in federal 
prison for scheming to defraud UPS out of hundreds of thousands of 
dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were so many falsehoods and lies, they were like  
dandelions in the spring grass,'' U.S. District Judge Charles 
Norgle declared. 
</P>
<P>
	The 29-year-old Jackson, who is black, had claimed that white  
racists working for UPS had damaged or lost four packages 
containing her artwork. She tried to collect $143,500 for each of 
the packages. 
</P>
<P>
	To make her claim credible, Jackson scrawled racist remarks on  
letters sent via UPS to herself and several prominent black 
leaders, including the Rev. Jesse Jackson, NAACP President Kweisi 
Mfume and eight members of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Her aim was to make it appear the remarks were written by UPS  
workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, who is not related to Jesse Jackson, was also convicted  
of trying to torpedo the career of a Chicago police sergeant who 
arrested her in 1996 by making it look as if the officer had stolen 
her credit card. 
</P>
<P>
	She took the witness stand at her trial and tried to talk her  
way out of trouble but became hostile and defiant under 
cross-examination. At one point, she called prosecutor Ryan Stoll 
``an animal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the sentencing, she apologized to her family, seated in  
court, saying she was ``sorry that their introduction to the 
American judicial system had to be so negative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Norgle said that Jackson ``has not shown remorse for what she  
has done.'' But he declined to impose the maximum sentence of 6 1/2 
years, saying she is young and had a troubled youth. 
</P>
<P>
	She was a student at Chicago-Kent College of Law and later  
transferred to William Mitchell College of Law in St. Paul, Minn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
