<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Food Prices Not Likely To Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Growers trying to eke out a living amid a  
lagging farm economy can expect low prices again this year for 
rice, soybeans and other crops. 
</P>
<P>
	But consumers might not find lower prices for food products and  
other goods, industry analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	``Will the consumer see the benefit of it?,'' said Joe Miller of  
the American Farm Bureau Federation. ``The answer is probably no. 
The (retail) industry because of packaging and handling costs. . . 
they don't tend to lower their prices when the raw commodity prices 
fall apart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It shows there is a real disconnect in what the actual price  
of wheat or corn is and what the consumer pays for it,'' Miller 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Major cereal makers, for instance, recently announced breakfast  
cereal price increases of 2.5 percent to 3 percent, even while 
wheat prices are at their lowest in years. 
</P>
<P>
	The situation is similar in the cotton industry, which recently  
completed the 1998 season at 13.9 million bales -- the smallest crop 
since 1989. Cotton farmers are getting significantly less for their 
crop, about 56 cents a pound compared with 64 cents a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	But does that mean Americans will pay more for blue jeans,  
T-shirts and other textiles because of short supplies? Not exactly, 
says Mark Lang, director of economic services for the National 
Cotton Council. 
</P>
<P>
	A surge in foreign textiles entering the country is leaving the  
American consumer ``unscathed with maybe actually a small 
benefit,'' Lang said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the U.S. imported the equivalent of 12.5 million  
bales, compared with 8.7 million in 1996. Most of that surge is due 
to the economic crisis in Asia, which has left that part of the 
country searching for customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the finished textile product is significantly different  
from the raw product, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	In general, Miller of the American Farm Bureau predicts ``a  
rough year price wise'' after ``some fairly low prices'' in the 
last half of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``We could see even lower prices in 1999 for most of the  
commodities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Congress passed a $6 billion bailout package for farmers last  
year and lawmakers are talking about a similar deal in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Total wheat production is down 12 percent to 2.2 billion  
bushels. The smaller crop coupled with increased exports will give 
wheat prices a slight boost, to $2.60 to $3.10 a bushel, compared 
with $2.65 last year, the government said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat prices have not been this low since the 1987-88 season  
when farmers got $2.57 a bushel. In the 1997 and 1996 seasons, 
wheat farmers got $3.38 and $4.30, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Likewise, rice prices are expected to average $6 to $7 per  
bushel, compared with $8.55 to $8.75 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean prices are also forecast to drop to between $3.95 and  
$4.75 per bushel, compared with an estimated $5.05 last year and 
$6.47 in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
