<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Finding Old Stocks Brings New Cash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	While stationed in Pakistan with an engineering company, R.W.  
Johnson Jr. decided to put $5,000 in a growing Swiss mutual fund as 
an investment for the future. That was around 1962. 
</P>
<P>
	After a little globetrotting, some job changes and his marriage  
to Louise 10 years later, he lost track of the fund -- and the fund, 
the notorious Investors Overseas Services of Geneva, which folded 
amid scandal in the early 1970s, lost track of him. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was told they weren't worth anything, and he kept thinking,  
'I'll throw them out ...,''' recalled Louise Johnson, of Escondido, 
Calif., whose husband passed away in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1991, the Johnsons redeemed those shares for $7,500.  
</P>
<P>
	``When he finally got the money, he said it felt like a  
windfall. He bought a pickup truck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Countless other families have had similar stories to share: Old  
stocks and bonds turning up in attics, closets or safe-deposit 
boxes, most of which had been lost or forgotten over the years. 
</P>
<P>
	In most cases, the companies that issued them have long  
disappeared, which means the certificates probably have no 
intrinsic, or market, value. 
</P>
<P>
	However, there are some instances when a company may have been  
acquired or changed its name, so owners might be able to recover 
some money if they can track down the company. Also, some defunct 
companies may have had funds set aside in bankruptcy court to repay 
creditors or shareholders, which had been the case with the 
Johnsons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people that have old stocks and bonds, especially from  
companies that went bankrupt, believe they lose everything no 
matter what. It's not true ... (but) they don't know how to get 
their money,'' said Pierre Bonneau, chief executive of Stock Search 
International Inc. in Tucson, Ariz., one of several companies 
specializing in tracking old securities. The company helped the 
Johnsons get money back from their old fund shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Even when a stock isn't actually redeemable -- and Bonneau says  
only 20 percent are -- a growing number are getting attention from 
collectors. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock Search conducts about 150 searches a month. It charges $85  
per search, and keeps around 30 percent of whatever money is 
returned. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the largest securities research firms is R.M. Smythe of  
New York (www.rm-smythe.com). For $75, Smythe provides a report 
detailing a company's history -- any name changes, mergers, 
bankruptcies, predecessor and successor companies. If the 
researched security has no market value, Smythe says it will make 
an offer for it as a collectible. 
</P>
<P>
	For those with the time, and inclination, it's possible to do a  
search on your own. 
</P>
<P>
	The first stop should be a broker. He or she may be able to tell  
if a security is still traded on an exchange, or if the company 
might have merged with another over the years. 
</P>
<P>
	Another good source: the Internet, where you can search for a  
company name or product. A listing of resources can be found at 
www.HappyTrails.com. It even has direct links to the Securities and 
Exchange Commission Edgar Archives. (For you low-techers: Financial 
reference books found in many public libraries are available.) 
</P>
<P>
	The transfer agent listed on the front of each certificate is  
another potential source. However, if the agent no longer exists, 
the state where the company was incorporated, which is usually 
listed on a certificate, may help. Contact the Secretary of State 
and ask for the Business Corporations Section. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Johnson says her husband went through various sources  
himself over the years -- each time coming up with new bits of 
information -- before finally turning to a professional for help. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock Search learned that there were still millions of dollars  
held by at least seven international liquidators available to 
former holders of Investors Overseas Services Fund of Funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The scandal-ridden IOS was started in the early 1960s as a  
mutual fund for Americans stationed overseas. In 1970, control of 
the company was taken over by a young financier named Robert L. 
Vesco. Very quickly, however, IOS funds were mysteriously 
misdirected and by the time the Securities and Exchange Commission 
was ready to indict Vesco, he was gone -- along with about $224 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	``My advice is to follow through and don't give up,'' Mrs.  
Johnson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
