<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> USA Networks Abandons Lycos Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- USA Networks Inc. officially called off plans to  
buy Internet site Lycos Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	USA Networks chairman and CEO Barry Diller had planned to create  
a company worth $22 billion by combining Lycos with his Home 
Shopping Network and Ticketmaster Online-Citysearch Inc., a ticket 
agency and online entertainment directory. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies announced today they had called off the deal by  
mutual consent. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the termination agreement, Lycos has agreed to pay USA  
Networks $35 million if it agrees to be acquired by someone else 
before July 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the companies said they had reached an agreement  
under which Ticketmaster and CitySearch services will be featured 
on Lycos Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Diller couldn't win over small day traders who own a major stake  
in Lycos and trade it in average blocks of 419 shares. In addition 
to the small investors, Diller failed to keep the support of Lycos' 
largest shareholder, CMG Information Services, a Boston-based 
investment firm that owns about 20 percent of the Internet company. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders want the Waltham, Mass.-based company to remain a  
pure Internet company, and avoid the traditional business problems 
of a retail company like Home Shopping Network, which include 
inventory controls and distribution. Lycos' Web site offers 
research, news, music and shopping links. 
</P>
<P>
	Lycos investors criticized the deal when it was announced in  
February and have swamped Internet chat rooms and message boards 
with virulent and caustic opinions about the deal, Diller and Lycos 
chairman Bob Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	CMGI, which originally supported the deal, reversed itself after  
Lycos shares nosedived. The firm then hired the investment banker 
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter to help find a more favorable suitor to 
knock out Diller's bid. While CMGI does not appear to have found 
one, smaller investors cheered the prospect that Lycos may again be 
a target for a takeover. 
</P>
<P>
	USA Networks owns the Home Shopping Network and is a majority  
shareholder in Ticketmaster Online-Citysearch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
