<HEADLINE> Ordonez Comfy As White Sox Cleanup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Magglio Ordonez moved into right field as a  
rookie last season and found a home. Now the Chicago White Sox have 
given him a bigger assignment: fill in the huge No. 4 hole in the 
batting order created by the departure of Albert Belle. 
</P>
<P>
	Ordonez won't put up Belle-like numbers, but he's shown in his  
short stint as the cleanup hitter that he can be a consistent run 
producer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think my concentration has been better and I'm getting a lot  
of good pitches to hit, and I'm being patient,'' Ordonez said after 
Wednesday night's game with the Texas Rangers was rained out. 
</P>
<P>
	Since moving into the cleanup spot April 15, Ordonez has batted  
.318 with seven homers and 25 RBIs. For the season, he's hitting 
.296 with eight homers and 29 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	Best of all for the White Sox, he's making decent contact with  
only 11 strikeouts in 115 at-bats. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want to be a good hitter. I can hit home runs, but I'm  
not a home run hitter,'' Ordonez said. 
</P>
<P>
	``With home runs, you just never know. Sometimes, you can go 20  
or 30 games without one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ordonez was named the American Association Player of the Year at  
Triple-A Nashville in 1997, winning the batting title with a .329 
average. He was promoted to the majors and in 21 games showed 
promise with four homers and 11 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	Then last year he took the right field job, hitting .282 with 14  
homers and 65 RBIs in 145 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Early this season, the Sox experimented with Paul Konerko at  
cleanup before moving up Ordonez. So far, it has worked. 
</P>
<P>
	At 25, Ordonez is currently one of the best bargains in baseball  
with a salary of $275,000. He will continue to get RBI 
opportunities with Ray Durham, Mike Caruso and Frank Thomas ahead 
of him the order. All have a penchant for getting on base, 
especially 1997 batting champion Thomas, who has walked more than 
100 times in eight straight seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Frank is always on and there will be lot of chances for me,''  
Ordonez said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers and White Sox will make up Wednesday's postponement  
as part of an Aug. 13 doubleheader beginning at 5:05 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Parque, Chicago's scheduled starter Wednesday, will pitch in  
Friday's series opener against the Yankees at New York. John Snyder 
will start Saturday and Mike Sirotka will pitch Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas will move Mark Clark, Wednesday's scheduled starter, to  
Friday for the second game of a four-game series at Arlington 
against the Baltimore Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Morgan will start Thursday night followed by Clark, Rick  
Helling on Saturday and Aaron Sele on Sunday. Sele's start will 
depend on his health after he missed his turn Tuesday night because 
of the flu. 
</P>
<P>
	Juan Gonzalez, who had to leave Tuesday night's game in the  
fourth inning with a strained hamstring, an injury suffered while 
running the bases after a home run, was not in the Rangers' posted 
lineup before Wednesday's game was called off. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez will be evaluated on a daily basis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
