<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rep. Seeks To Boost Even Start Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nearly a million low-income preschoolers get a  
Head Start, participating in the 30-year-old education and health 
program. But for the last decade, many fewer children have been 
getting an Even Start. 
</P>
<P>
	The $135 million Even Start Family Literacy program has combined  
early-childhood reading lessons with adult basic education and 
parenting training for eligible families. And Wednesday its 
creator, Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa., said he would seek $500 million 
from this year's spending bill to boost the program. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our quest for a literate society has come along way,''  
Goodling, chairman of the House Education and Workforce Committee, 
said at a hearing Wednesday. ``The academic success of the child is 
strongly related to the ability of their parents to support their 
education.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even Start serves about 31,000 families, compared with 800,000  
children in Head Start, which provides education, health screenings 
and family social services and is administered by the Health and 
Human Services Department, not the Education Department. Parents 
receive some of the services in Head Start. 
</P>
<P>
	During last year's renewal of the Head Start law, GOP lawmakers  
pushed for it to be more of an educational program and include 
specific skills that children should learn. 
</P>
<P>
	With Even Start, children, age 8 and under, read and play games  
to improve their literacy. At home, their families read together, 
draw and tell stories. And their income-eligible parents must study 
for the General Educational Development certificate or take classes 
in basic adult education, parenting and job training. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even Start has been right on the mark,'' said Andrew Hartman,  
director of the National Institute for Literacy. ``Given the role 
that a high school diploma plays in opening doors to both job and 
educational opportunities, this is an important outcome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Brown, Even Start director in Oklahoma City, said Even  
Start children are helped by the program's emphasis on their 
parents earning their GED certificate or taking classes in basic 
adult education. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even Start has a lot to contribute to welfare reform,'' she  
said. ``It helps the second generation by not warehousing the child 
somewhere while the mom goes to a minimum wage job. The parent and 
child learn together. They spend more time together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Goodling is hoping to apply those principles -- partnership,  
self-reliance, local involvement -- as he leads the Republican 
congressional majority in its first chance to put its stamp on the 
34-year-old Elementary and Secondary Education Act, the 
comprehensive law that governs Even Start and most other federal 
kindergarten-through-12th grade programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats controlled the House from the time the law was enacted  
in 1965 through 1994, when it was last reauthorized. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton, who has focused on programs to end ``social  
promotion'' of students not academically ready to advance to the 
next grade and reduce class sizes by hiring new teachers, has 
championed Head Start. Under his administration, Head Start 
spending has increased by 68 percent and enrollment has increased 
by more than 200,000 children. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Start has also grown. It started in 1989 with about 2,500  
families, compared with the 31,000 today. 
</P>
<P>
	--Even Start grants last about 8 years, after which a program  
must come up with its own funds. Head Start programs are steadily 
funded, but must come up with matching funds. 
</P>
<P>
	--Even Start grants are administered by schools and community  
groups. Head Start centers are generally run independently of 
schools. 
</P>
<P>
	--Even Start programs -- nearly 700 nationwide -- are required to  
form local partnerships. Many partnerships are with Head Start 
centers, which can operate alone. 
</P>
<P>
	The Education Department found that Even Start adults and  
children reached goals such as earning the GED credential and 
increasing reading test scores. A research panel was created last 
year to measure the quality in the Head Start program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
