<HEADLINE> AOL Considers Net TV Possibilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- America Online Inc., which connects 17 million  
subscribers to the Internet through computers, now is looking to 
establish its service through television sets. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, AOL announced new partnerships with DirectTV, Hughes  
Network Systems, Philips Electronics and Network Computer Inc., to 
develop a system to connect televisions to the Internet by using 
satellite dishes, high-speed digital subscriber lines and 
high-speed modems. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Schuler, president of America Online's Interactive  
Services Group, said the proposed system also would allow viewers 
to watch TV while surfing the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The targeted audience, he said, are the AOL subscribers who  
already access the service through personal computers. While the 
computer will still be the main device used to access the service, 
he said, AOL would like to expand onto other appliances in the 
home. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analysts saw the deals as a good first step toward  
AOL's goal of reaching viewers through other means besides the PC. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've pretty well maxed out the number of people signing up  
using computers,'' said Gerry Kaufhold, a multimedia and digital 
television analyst for Cahners In-Stat Group, a market research 
company for emerging technology in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Kaufhold said AOL is getting pinched by AT&AMP;T, which is moving  
aggressively to provide high-speed hookups to the Internet using 
recently acquired cable systems. 
</P>
<P>
	``AOL is in a footrace,'' he said. ``It expands their turf from  
the 14-inch monitor in your den to the 36-inch TV in your living 
room.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If AOL succeeds in drawing in more viewers, it could increase  
their advertiser base and revenues. The new system is scheduled to 
be available some time in 2000, said Schuler. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
