<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Star Luge Racer Back After Injuries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE PLACID, N.Y. (AP) -- Duncan Kennedy, the most successful  
singles luge racer in United States history, announced his return 
to international competition Wednesday after an absence of two 
seasons due to physical problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-time Olympian (1988, 1992, 1994) from Lake Placid,  
N.Y., was diagnosed with bleeding on the brain stem in the fall of 
1997 and was forced to retire and forego a fourth Olympic team 
berth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I started to think about returning last winter as the symptoms  
were clearing and thought more about it this spring,'' Kennedy 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	During that time, Kennedy, 31, was racing competitively on the  
eastern snowboard circuit, coaching luge juniors and luging 
recreationally in Lake Placid. 
</P>
<P>
	``I missed the sliding, the travel, the people and the racing  
most of all,'' he admitted. ``Now the symptoms have basically 
cleared and the doctors are confident that I can do this. Dr. 
(Michael) Edwards (of Sacramento), the neurologist, said it was 
more a matter of controlling non-physical stress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Dr. Edwards has said that the symptoms are stable and activity  
will not be harmful,'' said U.S. Luge team physician Dr. Brad 
Stephens of Lake Placid. ``We also have independent neurologic 
evaluations from Burlington (Vt.) and Boston that feel it is safe 
for Duncan to compete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added USA Luge trainer and strength and conditioning coach Dan  
Smith: ``Dr. Edwards is very comfortable that luge and physical 
training should not exascerbate Duncan's situation. Dr. Stephens 
and I will monitor him closely and re-evaluate if necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	``We tested him at our spring camp last weekend and he felt  
good. Duncan's test results were comparable alongside our other 
athletes. Currently, there are no limitations on his physical 
training.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That is one of two areas in which the veteran luger will have to  
excel in order to be completely reinstated. The U.S. coaching staff 
has insisted that he pass the conditioning test this summer. 
Thereafter, Kennedy will enter a race-off series in October against 
four teammates and must place in the top two in order to be 
guaranteed a spot for the fall World Cup trip to Europe. Anything 
less would require concurrence by the coaching staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy, who gained worldwide reknown as much for standing up to  
a group of neo-Nazi skinheads in Germany in 1993 as for his luge 
prowess, has 21 international medals including the United States' 
first-ever World Cup gold during the 1991-92 campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I plan on coming back strong, hopefully on the podium next  
season,'' he said. ``I felt great last year on the sled and I think 
it'll be a lot of fun. I'm very lucky to have this opportunity to 
come back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy's return will make him the fourth-oldest competitor on  
the tour when the 1999-2000 season begins in November. Austrian 
Markus Prock will be 35, Jens Mueller of Germany 34 and Georg Hackl 
of Germany 33. 
</P>
</TEXT>
