<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Siena Hopes To Play Baseball in Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUDONVILLE, N.Y. (AP) -- Siena College's baseball team has  
applied for permission to play in Cuba next winter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Franciscan college in suburban Albany has filed papers with  
the U.S. Treasury Department and the Cuban Intersection seeking 
permission for the January trip, athletic director John D'Argenio 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to raise the profile of our baseball team,''  
D'Argenio said. The Division I team posted a school record 31 
victories this season. They finished as the Metro Atlantic Athletic 
Conference North Division champions and will compete this week in 
the MAAC tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Travel from the United States to Cuba has been restricted for  
more than 40 years under the Communist control of Fidel Castro. 
Though American tourists are still not allowed in Cuba, the 
Baltimore Orioles played in Cuba last month against the Cuban 
National Team and the Cuban team played in Baltimore last week. 
</P>
<P>
	If Siena's trip is approved, they team will play a Cuban team  
that is at its competitive level, D'Argenio said. A decision is 
expected within four to six weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
